the nevado del ruiz volcano grew calmer, but the government insisted that people continue evacuating areas close to the crater
the volcano was spouting steam on monday, but no ash was falling in areas around the volcano, the government's national emergency committee said. also, no tremors were being recorded
the volcano started spewing steam and ash on friday, becoming the most active since it erupted nov. 13, 1985, when 23,000 persons were killed
people within a six-mile radius of the volcano were ordered to evacuate
the bogota newspapers el tiempo and el espectador reported monday that many people in small villages were refusing to leave. in murillo, the largest village close to the volcano, mayor jesus maria romero aranzazu said only eight of the 600 residents there had left, el espectador reported
murillo, undamaged by the 1985 eruption, is five miles from the volcano
a fire in a northern village destroyed more than 150 mud-and-straw homes and killed at least six children
the fire on monday left 1,000 people homeless in jangaldi village, 60 miles north of dhaka, the independent bengali-language daily ittefaq said
it said the six children killed were trapped inside homes during the two-hour fire, which was put out by villagers using buckets of water
a dc9 jetliner and a two-seat training plane flew within 700 feet of each other over england, the civil aviation authority said
the incident occurred sunday two miles south of cambridge airport, the authority said monday
it involved a paramount airways dc9, which was carrying no passengers, and a piper pa38 tomahawk. the two planes were flying at an altitude of 2,000 feet
the civil aviation authority did not say what caused the planes to fly so close to each other, but said the incident would be investigated by the independent joint air miss working group
the standard safe distance between two planes is 1,000 feet
paramount airways is a new regional airline based in bristol, england
the civil aviation authority recently adopted a policy of reporting all near-collisions over british air space
the south african army's display of nazi flags at a military pageant has drawn criticism, a military spokeswoman said
the military displayed the nazi flags last week at the castle, a historic military building in cape town
a jewish visitor complained when he saw the flags, which contain a swastika, the military spokeswoman, lt. ina fourie, said on monday. a number of telephone callers also objected to the display, ms. fourie added
she said the use of the flags was ``merely symbolic in depicting world war ii. we are very sorry if we have offended or hurt anyone.''
she said the flags would no longer be displayed
south africa supported the allied side in world war ii, but a large segment of the white population was sympathetic to germany
a nationwide teachers' strike that has prevented 7.2 million children aged 3 to 18 from starting public school this year has entered its third week with no end in sight, officials said
the walkout by 505,000 primary and secondary school teachers belonging to ctera, the confederation of educational workers of the argentine republic union, began march 14 over demands to be paid a minimum of $115 a month
the government under education minister jorge sabato, while admitting teachers' salaries are low, has offered $85, saying it cannot pay more because of the economic crisis. some teachers receive only $55 a month
inflation in argentina, the developing world's third-most indebted nation, was 189 percent in 1987 and 10.4 percent in february
private schools have been mostly untouched by the strike, which entered its third week on monday
