latin american nations met in emergency session at panama's request and were asked to denounce foreign intervention in panama and call on the united states to end economic measures aimed at toppling gen. manuel antonio noriega
a formal regional position on the crisis in panama is to be drawn up later at the extraordinary meeting of the 26-member latin american economic system
the organization, based in caracas, was founded in 1976 as an economic forum for latin american countries
the organization is expected to reject any foreign intervention in panama, while urging that panamanian military and civilian leaders abide soon with the promise of free national elections, delegates at the meeting monday said
individual nations, including mexico and venezuela, already indicated their opposition to outside interference in panama's affairs, without specifically mentioning the united states by name
noriega, who as military chief also is panama's strongman, was indicted on federal drug trafficking and money-laundering charges in the united states, and president reagan says noriega must go. noriega denies the charges. the reagan administration also has frozen panamanian government funds in u.s. banks, denying this country a supply of dollars, the official panamanian currency
in an hourlong speech monday, panamanian foreign minister jorge abadia arias asked the delegates for support against u.s. ``economic aggression'' which he claimed is meant to keep the panama canal under u.s. control
panama is suffering the most cruel economic strangulation seen on our continent, within a strategy of domination with which the u.s. hopes to replace the wars of annexation that the world thought were long gone,'' abadia said
manuel rodriguez arriaga, mexico's subsecretary of international cooperation, rejected ``any act of foreign intervention to influence the destiny of panama.''
we cannot permit that someone tells us from outside what is good or bad. today it is panama, yesterday many others, and tomorrow anybody,'' rodriguez said. he called for u.s. economic measures against panama to cease
venezuela's acting foreign minister, horacio arteaga, rejected foreign intervention in panama, but reiterated venezuelan support for ``revitalization of democracy in panama.''
we fervently hope that when panama assumes full sovereignty over the canal, its people will have consolidated their democratic institutions,'' arteaga said
he said venezuela would like panama's government to make good very quickly its promise of free national elections
delegates from other countries asked panamana to call for free elections this year rather than next, sources at the meeting said, speaking on condition of anonymity
one delegate, also speaking on condition of not being identified, said, ``most latin americans would like gen. noriega to leave, not to be toppled.'' in general, latin american nations have rejected the interference of the panamanian military in the civilian government and called their ambassadors home for consultations. the meeting was expected to end today. update with 160 soldiers from 7th infantry divison now back, soldiers at base, yellow ribbons and banners; picks up 6th graf, ``the 3,200 ...''</note>
more than 700 members of the army's famed 82nd airborne division staged a dramatic finale to their mission in honduras by parachuting into their home base as wives, children and officers cheered
the paratroopers piled out of seven c-141 transport planes, filling the sky with olive-drab parachutes monday as family members and officers applauded from grandstands
we went down there to do a job, and it turned out they really didn't need us to do it,'' said spec. 4 randy beebe, 24. ``when they decided they didn't, it became business as usual, a training exercise.''
meanwhile, about 160 members of the 7th infantry division, dispatched to honduras with the 82nd after nicaraguan forces chased contra rebels into that country, returned to california as a band welcomed them home with ``the stars and stripes forever.''
the soldiers, clad in full combat gear, marched out of three planes at travis air force base before an honor guard dressed in fatigues
the infantrymen came home today to their base at fort ord about 100 miles south of san francisco, where loved ones welcomed them with yellow ribbons and banners with messages like ``good job, guys'' and ``welcome home, we missed you.''
the 3,200 soldiers from both divisions had been sent to back up the honduran army on march 17, but never got close to the nicaraguan-honduran border as they participated in training exercises with honduran soldiers
a 60-day cease-fire was signed last week between the nicaraguan government and the contra rebels
we were watched by everyone in the world, and everyone was impressed. i want you to know i'm very proud of you,'' lt. gen. john foss, commander of the 18th airborne corps, told paratroopers lined up in formation after the drop
twelve days ago, nicaraguan forces had entered honduras,'' foss said. ``now ... there are no nicaraguan forces in that country and a cease-fire exists.''
honduras, which requested the u.s. troops, had accused nicaragua of crossing its borders in pursuit of the contras. nicaragua denied the charge
at fort bragg, soldiers celebrated their return in joyful reunions with their families
it's great, it's great. oh, god, it's great,'' staff sgt. raymond gates, 29, said after hugging his wife, sharon
his sons, jarrod, 7, and christopher, 2, leaped into his arms while a friend held his rifle
spec. 4 beebe said he got a little nervous early in the stay, ``but this is what you're trained to do. we were ready to go.''
he said the first thing he wanted to do was call his parents in missouri, and ``let them know i'm ok. my mom's the worrying type.''
the paratroopers landed in the base's sicily drop zone, a name recalling the unit's glory days of world war ii. the 82nd made its first combat jump into sicily, and later dropped into france with the 101st airborne division in the normandy invasion
monday's jump ``was a good drop, a beautiful drop,'' said capt. donald m. sensing, a fort bragg spokesman. ``the first paratrooper out was three seconds early, but we're not quibbling with that.''
all 3,200 soldiers are expected to be back by friday, army officials said
the mission ended just in time for 1st lt. steve swimley, who was getting bored
we were doing the same stuff over and over,'' swimley said as he hugged his wife, mary. ``it was clear to me we'd be coming home soon because we had accomplished our objective.''
his buddy, 1st lt. jim cooper, said he was looking forward ``to taking a shower and drinking a few beers.''
i want to tell the nicaraguan people and the world that the combatants are not going to put down their arms until nicaragua is a democracy.'' _ diogenes hernandez membreno, a contra commander, commenting on the cease-fire between the nicaraguan government and the rebels
when there was a lapse of much time between press interviews or news conferences, he would be totally out of the swim on what was in the press and what had happened two weeks ago, and it would be like reinventing the wheel to get him prepared.'' _ former white house chief spokesman larry speakes, commenting on president reagan in his new book
it's great, it's great. oh, god, it's great.'' _ staff sgt. raymond gates, 29, commenting on his return from honduras with fellow paratroopers of the 82nd airborne division. treatment</head>
six people apparently injured by mustard gas allegedly used in iraqi attacks on kurdish villages arrived here today for medical treatment. more than 30 others were to be taken to other cities
dr. gerhard freilinger, department head of vienna's university clinic plastic surgery, said after talking with some of the patients, their injuries appeared to be from mustard gas that may have been mixed with a nerve gas
freilinger, who since 1984 has treated about 30 victims of alleged chemical weapons attacks in the 7{-year-old persian gulf war, said the effects on the lungs of the patients indicated they suffered from the effects of mustard gas
freilinger spoke to reporters at an airport where the injured arrived aboard an iran airlines ambulance plane
it was possible the mustard gas was ``in combination with a light nerve gas, because they all have bad headaches, are dizzy and (some) may have been unconscious,'' he said
mustard gas is heavier than air, which would explain how it seeped into cellars where the patients said they had been hiding during the march 16 and 17 attacks, freilinger said
iran has said the iraq dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three kurdish towns in iraq, killing 5,000 people and injuring 5,000. the attacks on the towns, which were captured in an iranian offensive, occurred march 16-17
freilinger said two of the patients, a child and a severely wounded iranian soldier, were to be placed in the intensive care unit at his university clinic. the four others _ three women and a man _ were to be brought to private clinics in vienna
the remaining kurds on board the plane were to be carried on to geneva, frankfurt, london and then new york
freilinger said about 50 percent of about 30 patients he has treated since 1984 survived, but added that patients only arrived for treatment after 10 or 15 days, meaning that the damage done by the gas could not be reversed
an iranian soldier freilinger had removed from the plane in vienna was originally to go on to new york. however, freilinger said the man's injuries were so severe, that he could not continue the trip
freilinger said poison gas penetrates everything including clothes. ``they can't run away from it because if they do, they breath it in even deeper,'' he said. he said mustard gas causes changes in the lungs that can lead to suffocation. he said it could also destroy the bone marrow and causes burns on the skin
freilinger said in 1984 he had visited areas allegedly bombed with chemical weapons and had taken a sample of the gas for verification and testing
in the past iran has sent soldiers allegedly poisoned by mustard gas to vienna and other european cities for treatment. in july, iranian civilians were brought for treatment for the first time
on board the plane, patients with burns on their hands, backs and faces coughed violently or lay motionless on stretchers
one child of six who iranian and kurdish officials said had lost her entire family in the attack, sobbed constantly and called for her parents
iran's ambassador to austria, hossein noghrehkar shirazi was at the airport when the plane arrived as were representatives of several kurdish groups
in downtown vienna on monday police arrested 60 people at a kurdish demonstration in front of the iraqi embassy against chemical weapons attacks. settlement</head>
women, black and hispanic police officers who said the department discriminated in hiring and promotion practices have been offered $9.2 million in back pay and an upgrade in seniority, officials say
the consent decree signed by the city and the federal government and announced monday by the justice department must be formally approved by u.s. district judge prentice marshall
the settlement, which ended a 15-year legal battle, calls for the city to give back pay to 729 women, blacks and hispanics and to adjust their seniority dates.
attorney richard gutman, who has represented two women in the case since 1974, called the settlement ``recognition that people's rights were violated. ... but even today, there are only 30 female sergeants out of about 1,200 on the force
the current training class will yield only the first female lieutenant in the history of the department,'' gutman added. ``that speaks for itself.''
city corporation counsel judson miner said the settlement was fair
there were many components to this case that had to be tried over a period of years,'' he said. ``one of the priorities of this office has been to resolve longstanding cases and still protect the interests of the city.''
police chief leroy martin will withhold comment until he has reviewed the decree, said spokeswoman jackie kimber
before 1973, women were not hired for the department's patrol force, prompting a spate of individual legal actions. black and hispanic males had charged in similar lawsuits that police department hiring and promotion tests had a discriminatory effect
the federal government consolidated the complaints in 1973, making itself the plaintiff
marshall, who presided over the case, ruled in 1976 that the city violated the equal-opportunity provisions of the civil rights act of 1964
the proposed decree requires the city to establish an interest-bearing fund of $9.2 million for reimbursements to discrimination victims
the decree covers:
_ 233 women on the 1972 policewoman eligibility list who were hired or reclassified as police officers and who passed probation, or who were employed before march 24, 1972, as policewomen or matrons and were subsequently reclassified as police officers
_ 455 black and hispanic men who applied for the 1968 or 1971 patrol officers eligibility lists and were hired from march 24, 1972, to dec. 31, 1978, as patrolmen or police officers from those lists, and who paased probation
_ the first three women promoted to sergeant after march 24, 1972, who served as policewomen or matrons in 1968 or before that time
_ the first 38 black and hispanic men who applied for promotion to sergeant in 1968 and who were promoted to that rank from march 24, 1972, to dec. 31, 1973. film, sted tv movie, sub 2nd graf of 4th item.</head>
kevin costner and james earl jones will star in the movie ``shoeless joe,'' about the disgraced baseball great ``shoeless joe'' jackson, a producer says
the movie is based on a novel by w.p. kinsella about a ghostly return by jackson, said associate producer brian frankish, who produced the ``max headroom'' tv series and the movie ``the boy who could fly.''
we have a really magical film here,'' frankish said at a news conference monday
frankish, gov. terry branstad and dubuque area chamber of commerce officials toasted the film with champagne glasses of dubuque star brewery's erlanger beer
jackson, a chicago white sox player, was kicked out of major league baseball for his part in the 1919 ``black sox'' scandal after an investigation found that the team threw the series to the cincinnati reds on the orders of gamblers
filming in the dubuque area will begin after memorial day, frankish said
the rhine river stopped just short of pouring into a section of cologne today, and two people in bavaria apparently died when another flooded river swept away their vehicle
the rhine stabilized at 32.3 feet. at 32.5 feet, the river would have entered cologne's low-lying old town area. experts predicted the rhine floodwaters will slowly begin to recede
rescue workers searched today for a volkswagen bus with two people that witnesses said was swept away by the flooded main river in the bavarian city of wuerzburg, where streets along the banks of the river were inundated
police said the witnesses reported seeing the headlights of the vehicle in the floodwaters and heard cries for help. the vehicle had disappeared by the time rescue workers arrived in boats, police said
over the weekend and on monday, rising waters in bavaria forced the evacuation of thousands of residents and farm animals. on monday, the danube river burst through dikes in at least five locations, causing the region's worst flooding in 70 years, authorities said
if the death of the two people in wuerzburg is confirmed, the flood-related death toll would climb to five. an elderly man died monday after suffering a heart attack in the flooded upper bavarian town of straubing, and a 61-year-old koblenz man and 3-year-old boy from bamberg died over the weekend
in bavaria, 3,500 residents were evacuated from homes near straubing, 30 miles north of munich, late sunday and early monday
at least 2,500 cows, pigs, and other farm animals were also taken to higher grounds as floodwaters spilled into the farms and pastures of upper bavaria
if the rain does not stop soon, this could get much worse,'' hans voggenreiter, a straubing official, told the associated press on monday. he said residents were evacuated by rowboats, powerboats and ``whatever was available.'' he added: ``most were taken in by relatives and friends. the rest are being cared for in schools and public auditoriums.''
nearly 900 volunteers worked throughout the day monday filling sandbags and shoring up the earthen dams that line the danube near straubing, regensburg and other upper bavarian towns
floodwaters had also entered parts of the ancient city of regensburg, as well as sections of passau, 80 miles to the east
officials said flooding along the neckar and mosel rivers was receding, but the rhine continued to climb
the rising rhine forced authorities to close parts of a major highway between mainz and koblenz on monday, and disrupted train traffic through the valley. travellers reported delays of several hours for some trains, and said others were rerouted away from riverside tracks
riverside sidewalks and some streets in bonn, the federal capital, had disappeared beneath the rhine's floodwaters
residents of the large villas that line the rhine at the bonn district of bad godesberg, home to many embassies and ambassadors' residents, were using pumps to dry out their flooded cellars and preparing sandbags
evening came, and then the people were in the little room apart, drinking wine and reading, drinking and reading for hours that night. it was good wine and good reading
it was not exactly ernest hemingway, but a spirited review of loving parodies of the famed novelist's crisp, masculine style
one of the literary lampoons, chosen from 21 finalists by a dozen well-lubricated judges, won the eleventh international imitation hemingway competition on monday
it was now morning, and he was in the bathroom shaving, shaving for the first time that day, but not the last; no, never the last,'' begins the winning entry, which ends with a groanworthy pun
the parody by gordon ``satch'' carlson of anchorage, alaska, met the key rule of the lighthearted contest: to sound like hemingway and read like hemingway. to ``know that funny is good and very funny is very good.''
carlson, a high school english teacher, newspaper and magazine columnist and self-described ``social gadfly,'' said in a telephone interview that he had no trouble imitating hemingway's distinctive style
actually, i've been accused of writing hemingway parodies when i'm not trying,'' he said
carlson's work continued: ``the hairs kept coming, tiny hairs and black and there was nothing for it, nothing for it at all but shaving ....''
the 350-word parody went on and on, discussing the hirsute portions of a man's body. it then described an estranged woman, then more shaving, drinking wine, and then drinking more wine
the climax came when the man cut himself
she turned, lifting her thin american lip over those thin, white, perfect, american teeth, and that thin american sneer. `it's only a nick, adams,' she said.' ''
nick adams was a character in several of hemingway's short stories
carlson maintains that hemingway's short stories, rather than his novels, are key to the writer's work. he said most of the lines for his parody came from his favorite hemingway story, ``the short happy life of francis macomber.''
carlson, who was vacationing in seattle when he learned he won, gets a round trip for two to italy, with dinners at harry's bar in florence
the other 20 finalists, each straining the language to produce literary lookalikes of hemingway's terse, manly style, were among 2,432 entries from all 50 states and more than a dozen foreign countries
the judges included authors ray bradbury, barnaby conrad and cyra mcfadden and poet lawrence ferlinghetti. it was the first time the contest was held outside los angeles
one would-be hemingway wrote, ``the president looked at the woman he called nancy ... other men also called her nancy.''
sticking to the political season, another contestant told how in the spring, a fellow named gary ``took the young woman to the bahamas, avoiding reporters and living on rum and sun and the catch of the day ... he had not taken his wife.''
another competitor was taken with a large fellow named jose, ``a fellow who could laugh in such a large way when the bird sat on his cigar, (a) cigar the size of a monkey's arm.''
one entry dealt with ``a farewell to arms, legs, feet and neck,'' while another sought glitter in ``a farewell to lunch.''
emmy award-winning writer albert schwartz, who created scripts for such tv and radio shows as ``the bob hope show,'' ``here's lucy,'' and ``gilligan's island,'' died of complications from emphysema. he was 77
schwartz, who died saturday, was part of the original writing team for ``the bob hope show,'' when it went on radio in 1938
his first tv credits came in 1955 for ``the milton berle show'' and ``december bride.''
he later wrote for ``gilligan's island'' and three television movies based on the series. he also wrote for ``petticoat junction,'' ``chico and the man,'' ``good times'' and ``the brady bunch.''
schwartz, nominated twice for emmys, shared the award in 1961 for his work on several episodes of ``the red skelton show.''
he is survived by his wife, mimi, two sons, two daughters, six grandchildren and two brothers. attacks</head>
gunmen killed a japanese nightclub owner today, and the military said it captured two top communist rebel leaders during an early morning raid on a hideout in suburban manila
the military, meanwhile, was on alert to guard against attacks by communist guerrillas marking their army's 19th anniversary
police said akihiro sato, was shot near manila airport. he was taken to a nearby hospital where he died of bullet wounds in the neck and shoulder
police pvt. 1st class bert hipolito said investigators had no idea who sato's killers were. a japanese friend of the victim who declined to be identified told reporters at the hospital that sato, 48, was a native of tsuchiura city in japan's ibaraki prefecture, where he owned a nightclub
the source said sato frequently visited manila on business trips and was to have returned to japan today. he arrived march 20 and was reported to have a filipino wife. the japanese embassy said it was trying to obtain more information and could make no further comment
armed forces chief gen. renato de villa told a news conference today that authorities captured rafael baylosis, secretary-general of the communist party of the philippines, and benjamin de vera, central committee member in charge of operations on mindanao, the country's second largest island
this is certainly a big loss to the communist party of the philippines because these are very high-ranking personalities who have been subject of many manhunts and many operations in the past,'' de villa said
brig. gen. alexander aguirre, overall commander of security forces in the capital, said the two were arrested during a raid on a hideout at the manila suburb of san juan early today
armed forces spokesman col. oscar florendo said the military was on alert today in anticipation of possible rebel attacks. the alert covered five regions, including manila, northern, southern and central luzon and parts of the central philippine visayas islands
president corazon aquino told reporters she ordered executive secretary catalino macaraig to summon the mayors of 13 towns and four cities that comprise the philippine capital to a meeting to plan safety measures
no major rebel attacks were reported today, but reports of attacks in the countryside often take days to reach manila
the 24,000-strong new people's army, part of the outlawed communist party of the philippines, traditionally observes its founding anniversary by attacking government installations and executing ``enemies of the people.'' names of towns reported attacked. picks up 8th graf pvs ``kurdistan is ...</note>
iraq today said its warplanes attacked two supertankers off iran in the persian gulf and threatened to use chemical weapons against major iranian cities
the official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, quoted a military spokesman as saying iraqi warplanes hit two ``very large maritime targets,'' or supertankers, off the iran coast during the night
there was no immediate confirmation of the report, which provided no other details. news of iraqi raids in iranian tankers are difficult to verify because of an iranian news blackout on such incidents
nuri nayef, director of the cairo office of the iraqi news agency, today said an ``authorized iraqi spokesman'' told him ``iraq might choose a number of large iranian cities to be the targets of chemical weapons as a deterrent and punitive measure.''
nayef, who spoke to reporters in cairo, said the unidentified spokesman said iran deployed chemical weapons in iraq's northeastern kurdistan region and that iraq may respond to stop the iranians from doing so again
iran claims iraq dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three towns in kurdistan, killing 5,000 kurds and injuring 5,000. the attacks on the town of halabja and the nearby villages of khormal and dojaila reportedly began march 16 and continued over the next few days
western reporters have seen victims of chemical weapons at hospitals in halabja, which they visited with iranian guides, and in tehran. survivors told them chemical bombs were dropped by iraqi, not iranian, planes
kurdistan is where the majority of iraq's 3.5 million kurds live. most of them have been fighting the baghdad government for autonomy in the mountainous region. they are backed by iran
baghdad has neither confirmed nor denied the use of the outlawed weapons. but a statement by iraq's ruling revolutionary command council on saturday said iraq has the right to defend itself ``with all available weapons.''
on monday, the official islamic republic news agency, also monitored in nicosia, said iran's revolutionary guards had killed or wounded 300 iraqis in the latest battle of an iranian thrust into the kurdistan region
the news agency quoted revolutionary guards minister mohsen rafiq-doust as saying the iranians have overrun 540 square miles of the region
the iranians also have pushed 15 miles into the darbandikhan region, east of iraq's kirkuk oilfields, communiques said
iran claims to have killed or wounded nearly 13,500 iraqis, captured more than 5,000 and destroyed 225 tanks and armored vehicles since march 16
iraq has admitted losing territory in kurdistan
but if the iranian claim is confirmed, it would mark iraq's biggest military setback since the iranians battled to within six miles of the southern city of basra early last year and occupied wetlands east of it
iran also claimed its air force fighters downed two iraqi warplanes in the kurdistan battle zone monday. iraq admitted losing only one aircraft
in another development, rebels fighting iran's government with backing from iraq said monday their national liberation army launched a major offensive on a 15-mile front in iran's southwestern khuzestan province near the town of shush
iran acknowledged the attack, but said more than 1,000 iraqi soldiers and nla ``counter-revolutionaries'' were killed and the advanced was foiled
six people were killed and one was injured when a group of young west german skiers and their guide were buried by an avalanche in the jam valley of tyrol province, authorities said
the accident happened monday morning, but authorities did not become aware of it until late in the afternoon because all electricity and telephone lines to the area had been interrupted by another avalanche, a police spokesman from the area told austrian television
the spokesman said the six people dug out of the snow were already dead and a seventh was injured. no names of the skiers involved were released
a former president of venezuela will fly to panama to ask the roman catholic archbishop to try to mediate an end to the crisis over the strongman-rule of gen. manuel antonio noriega
president oscar arias of costa rica and spanish prime minister felipe gonzalez told a news conference monday they would ask panamanian monsignor marco antonio mcgrath to seek a peaceful solution to panama's devastating political and economic situation
they said former venezuelan president carlos andres perez will go to panama to present the request to mcgrath. no schedule was given
arias, gonzalez and perez met sunday and monday in the resort of guanamara, 220 miles north of san jose
gonzalez is on a four-day visit to costa rica. he said noriega has not sought asylum in spain, but if he does it will be granted with the assurance he would not be extradicted to the united states where he is under a federal indictment in flordia on charges of drug trafficking
the spanish leader told the news conference an ``immediate solution is necessary to end the anguish and the pain of the panamanian people and we believe that if archbishop mcgrath agrees to mediate, it would be a very important point.''
he said he and arias ``are reasonably optimistic that there will be a rapid solution in panama.''
arias said he wanted mcgrath ``to serve as mediator ... not only between the civic crusade and president manuel solis palma but also with all the political parties to find a solution to the crisis in panama.''
the national civic crusade is a coalition of about 200 business, professional, student and union groups. it has been trying since june to force noriega to step down as commander of the 15,000-member defense forces that includes the armed forces and police. arias also said noriega should resign from the post, which the general has used to dominate the government
noriega picked solis palma as the new chief execuive on feb. 26, the day after president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire noriega and instead was ousted from office. delvalle is living in hiding in panama and is still recognized by the united states as the country's legal president
arias won the 1987 nobel peace prize as author of a peace plan signed last august by the presidents of the five central american countries, nicaragua, el salvador, honduras, guatemala and costa rica, designed to end regional conflicts
a day in february when millions of britons wore red clown noses reaped $25 million for british and african charities, organizers said
comic relief day'' was held for the first time on feb. 5, and accompanied by a seven-hour ``laughathon'' on television, which raised the bulk of donations through telephone pledges
two million donors also paid nearly $1 each for a red nose. bankers in pin stripes, school children, secretaries and others wearing the bulbous badge were a common sight. even prince andrew, second son of queen elizabeth ii, posed for photographers in a red nose
organizers on monday said the funds would be used to help famine victims in africa and poor youths in britain
elbert w. friday, deputy director of the national weather service, has been named head of that agency, the national oceanic and atmospheric administration announced today
friday succeeds richard d. hallgren, who has been named executive director of the american meteorological society
the national weather service is the federal agency that collects weather information and issues forecasts and warnings
friday, deputy director since 1981, is a retired air force colonel who previously headed the defense department's office of environmental and life sciences. he holds a doctorate in meteorology from the university of oklahoma
scientists seeking to explain the longer lifespan of rats fed low-calorie diets are not recommending that people follow such a strict regimen, but merely that they eat sensibly
i think the studies support the wisdom of what is commonly referred to as a prudent diet,'' said dr. richard weindruch of the national institute on aging. ``don't overload yourself with calories.''
scientists from a range of disciplines gathered monday at the university of notre dame to analyze a study in which about 200 rats fed 30 percent fewer calories than a similar-sized group lived an average of 20 percent longer. the conference continues through today
while the link between a restricted diet and longer life is long-established, the researchers are trying to find out why diet tends to slow down the aging process
an immunologist suggested suggested lower food intake kept the animals' immune systems strong. other results were less conclusive, but weindruch cautioned against issuing hasty advice
the studies at present do not justify a recommendation to the general public of severe caloric restriction, or even moderate caloric restriction, because there are so many difficulties in translation between the animal model and the human situation,'' he said
immunology researcher dr. yoon kim of chicago speculated that the restricted diet may have exposed the rats to fewer antigens _ or disease-causing agents in the food _ to which the immune system reacts by producing antibodies
in a restricted diet, the tendency is not to use up'' the immune system's ability to fight disease, said kim. ``life, and healthy life, is due to restriction of diet, maintaining the potential of the defense system, not using it unnecessarily.''
thirty-two researchers in the united states and canada were sent tissue samples for analysis from the 400 rats raised at notre dame's lobund laboratory in a study supported by the chicago-based, non-profit retirement research foundation
the study involved 400 rats, half of which were fed 12 grams of food per day, or about 70 percent of normal, with fat limited to 5 percent
animals on restricted diet lived an average of 38 months, an increase of nearly 20 percent above the control group, scientists said
the rats on restricted diets were healthier in their old age and developed fewer cancers of the prostate and liver. the rats also suffered less disease of the heart and brain and had better-functioning immune systems, scientists said
dr. gilbert boissonneault, a clinical nutritionist from the university of kentucky, said he found no difference in body fat content between the two groups of rats
dr. gibbons cornwell iii, a professor of medicine at dartmouth college, found extensive weakening of heart muscle in all rats, but less in the diet-restricted animals
additional studies will look at the glandular system and gastrointestinal tract. coasts</head>
two unarmed tomahawk cruise missiles flew 800 miles over rural florida and alabama in a simulated ship-to-land attack, then parachuted down to a test range, a navy spokesman said
the missiles, 18 feet long and 21 inches around, were fired from navy destroyers in the gulf of mexico, according to bob holsapple, a spokesman for the cruise missile project in washington
these were the eighth and ninth successful tests over the florida and alabama test range,'' he said monday. ``the flight route took the missiles over sparsely and non-populated areas only.''
the exact course of the missiles and the identity of the ships they were fired from was classified, he said
the missiles, fired at 10 a.m. cst sunday and 3 p.m. cst monday, traveled at 500 mph at altitudes varying from 500 to 6,000 feet. it took one hour and 45 minutes to complete the tests, holsapple said
seconds after being launched from the destroyers, the missiles dropped their solid-fuel rocket boosters and switched to their cruise missile engine
they flew ``a fully-guided test flight over approximately 800 miles over portions of florida and alabama and then terminated at the eglin air force base test range,'' he said
the tomahawks were guided to florida's west coast by their on-board navigation system. once over land, their guidance system adjusted course using an on-board computerized ``terrain contour matching system,'' holsapple said
the tomahawk cruise missile, which is designed to fly close to the ground to avoid radar detection, is deployed on destroyers, cruisers, battleships and attack submarines
horacio martinez-baca was a labor union lawyer in argentina when the military took control there 12 years ago. six days after the coup, martinez-baca was arrested and began a four-year nightmare of imprisonment and torture
they laid me down on a table. they tied my arms and legs. they put electric shocks on my genitals and my gums, and they asked who were my friends,'' martinez-baca testified monday
a few feet away in the hushed courtroom sat carlos suarez mason, 64, a former general who oversaw the military prisons in which martinez-baca was held
the prisoners used to call him the lord of death and life,'' martinez-baca said
the former prisoner, testifying in a $10 million lawsuit against suarez mason, said the 90-minute torture session occurred about a month after he was arrested in march 1976 and was repeated several times before his release in april 1980
there were also beatings, freezing showers, death threats, and ``probably the worst torture,'' solitary confinement in an unheated, windowless cell for days at a time, he said
suarez mason, former commander of the first army corps in buenos aires, was arrested in january 1987 at his home in foster city, just south of san francisco, more than three years after fleeing argentina
he faces extradition on charges of 43 murders and 23 kidnappings, allegedly committed by soldiers under his command from 1976 to 1979 during a military campaign against suspected leftists
the civil suit by martinez-baca is one of three by argentinians now living in the united states who say they were imprisoned and tortured, or their relatives were killed, by suarez mason's forces
u.s. courts have allowed suits against foreigners in their jurisdiction for certain types of human rights violations, including torture, prolonged detention and summary execution
u.s. district judge samuel conti declared a default march 15 after the former general failed to respond to the suit or answer pre-trial questions, claiming he had spent his last $100,000 on lawyers in the extradition case. the judge ruled that the trial would be limited to the amount in damages suarez mason must pay
at monday's session, san francisco attorney ray archuleta appeared and said he was representing suarez mason, who declared he was now willing to answer questions. but conti said suarez mason had no right to take part in a hearing after a default and ordered archuleta to the back of the courtroom
martinez-baca, a former local government official in mendoza, argentina, said his nearly blind father, a former state governor, was arrested along with his mother and brother on the day the military took power. six days later, two plainclothes police arrested him in his apartment
he said he was never told why he was beng held
one of the most frightening events of his imprisonment was being flown from one military prison to another. he had heard about other prisoners thrown out of helicopters alive, martinez-baca said. another time, when he was led away for interrogation and torture, his jailers told him to say his last words and acted as if he would be killed, he said
the military finally allowed him to leave the country in 1980 just as argentina's supreme court was about to order his release, martinez-baca said. he arrived at the home of a sponsoring presbyterian minister in berkeley speaking no english, separated from his family and about 70 pounds lighter than when he was imprisoned, he said
though he still fears retaliation from the argentine military, he said, he filed the suit as ``a deterrent for people who think they are the master of life and death.''
president corazon aquino's chief housekeeper died of cancer today with a weeping president at her bedside, the presidential palace announced
mrs. aquino stayed by priscilla ruiz aragon's side for two hours until she died at the suburban makati medical center, according to special presidential assistant flerida ruth romero. mrs. aragon was 55
the president, her eyes swollen from crying, refused to talk to reporters when she returned to the presidential palace from the hospital
mrs. aragon, popularly called fritz, was known for the exacting way she ran the president's household. a wealthy socialite, she was formerly associated with deposed president ferdinand marcos' wife, imelda, but later broke with the marcoses
she was survived by her husband, francisco. the couple had no children. details of closure. no pickup.</note>
the army today sealed the occupied west bank and gaza strip in the toughest crackdown since demonstrations began four months ago. palestinians tossed gasoline bombs and set tires ablaze in protest
the army rounded up palestinians after the three-day closure went into effect, arresting 600, israel radio said. the army confirmed it was making mass arrests, but declined to give figures
israeli troops set up roadblocks to bar nearly all journalists, israeli civilians and arab visitors from the territories, seized by israel in the 1967 war. the army said it wounded seven palestinians on the west bank
the crackdown was seen as a test of the military's ability to control the territories where, according to u.n. figures, 119 palestinians and one israeli soldier have been killed since dec. 8
it was most severe in the gaza strip, where the 650,000 arab residents were ordered confined to their homes from 10 p.m. monday night until 3 a.m. friday. telephone links were also cut
in the west bank, where 850,000 arabs live, the bridges to jordan were left open for incoming traffic, telephones were operating and residents were allowed to travel within their towns or villages. no arabs were allowed to go to jordan, however
the closure, ordered by the cabinet on sunday night, did not affect the 65,000 jewish settlers living in the occupied territories
robert slater, president of the foreign press association, said the group appealed today to the supreme court to overturn the closure order
slater said the association and israel's 2,000 member journalists association had decided not to participate in army-provided news pools into the territories
but an american television network and some israeli newspapers agreed to take part in pool coverage today
one israeli reporter and foreign television crew accompanied the army into the west bank and another into gaza
defense minister yitzhak rabin said the measures were taken to forestall large-scale palestinian demonstrations on land day on wednesday. the day marks the 12th anniversary of a clash over land confiscation. six arabs were shot to death by soldiers on march 30, 1976
many israelis say they believe news coverage of the palestinian unrest gives a one-sided view and hurts israel's image. there have been calls to restrict television coverage by those who contend the presence of tv cameras incites the protesters
in the west bank village of zaita today, 40 miles northwest of jerusalem, hundreds of palestinians threw gasoline bombs and clashed with soldiers, the army said. an army spokesman reported seven arabs wounded by army gunfire
in the gaza strip, violent protests broke out as soon as palestinians learned of the curfew, israel army radio said. in jabaliya refugee camp, troops fired tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse youths who set tires ablaze, the radio said
troops turned away the car of save the children director chris george at a roadblock outside ramallah, despite an army annoucement that the closure would not affect international relief workers
george said the restrictions had seriously disrupted his agency's operations, with half the jerusalem staff of 10 relief workers denied entry into the city
mona rishmawi, an attorney at law in the service of man, a human rights group founded by palestinian lawyers, said israeli troops had forcibly closed the major west bank markets in jenin and jericho as well as in gaza city
in ramallah, soldiers today forced merchants, sometimes at gunpoint, to close their stores
the action was done to defy the plo, which had ordered the stores opened for three hours a day. in earlier protests, the plo had ordered the markets closed. at that time, israeli soldiers forced them open
three days is nothing. we can go three months,'' one 70-year-old man told the associated press as he watched the soldiers. he declined to give his name
lt. gen. dan shomron, the armed forces chief of staff, was quoted by the state-owned israel radio as saying the closure order may be extended beyond three days if necessary
rabin said the territories were declared ``a closed military zone.''
the meaning is (to bar) all those who don't have to be there or there's no vital reason why they have to move around there,'' he told soldiers in remarks aired monday by israel army radio. transportation secretary.</note>
as vice president george bush's grip on the republican presidential nomination tightens, more and more people are asking the no. 2 question:
whom will he choose as his running mate?
bush says it's too early to think about it
former president richard nixon suggests white house chief of staff howard h. baker jr. baker says he doesn't expect to be asked because he wouldn't bring the right strength to the ticket
others propose california gov. george deukmejian. deukmejian says he couldn't accept because he would leave his state in the hands of a democratic lieutenant governor
nixon, in a forthcoming london sunday times political column, says the ideal formula is to pick your principal rival, as president reagan did with bush. but, he suggests, maybe the campaign between bush and senate minority leader bob dole has been too bitter for that
some have another idea: not principal rival, but wife of principal rival. how about former secretary of transportation elizabeth dole?
and so it goes
nixon argues that baker, a tennessean and former senate republican leader, would be helpful in southern states and in dealing with congress
in a recent television interview, baker said, ``george bush needs to find someone who will bring strength to the ticket on a regional and political basis, and i think that is not going to be me.''
he didn't say he would turn it down. ``if someone asked me to do it,'' he said, ``i would have a very difficult time trying to figure out what i was going to say.'' but, he added, ``i do not wish that to happen.''
baker has mentioned former tennessee gov. lamar alexander, deukmejian of california, new jersey gov. thomas kean and former pennsylvania gov. richard thornburgh as good choices for the vice presidential slot
if deukmejian left office in mid-term, lt. gov. leo t. mccarthy, a democrat, would become governor of the nation's largest state. at a news conference in sacramento recently, the california governor said, ``even if they did ask me to accept the vice presidential nomination, i wouldn't be able to take it.'' later, he added, ``that doesn't mean i wouldn't like to be vice president.''
another possibility: rep. jack kemp of new york, who ran as a conservative alternative to bush for the presidential nomination but fared poorly
also mentioned is sen. nancy kassebaum of kansas. she was on a long list of potential reagan running mates in 1980 but took herself out of consideration because, as a freshman senator, she said she didn't have enough experience. she has eight years more of it now
if bush should decide to choose a midwesterner, to strengthen the ticket in a region that could be crucial to republican hopes, another possibility would be illinois gov. james thompson, who endorsed the vice president and campaigned for him in the illinois presidential primary
other names that have been mentioned include sen. alan simpson of wyoming, dole's deputy in the senate leadership; secretary of education william j. bennett; sen. phil gramm of texas, an architect of the congressional deficit-reduction mechanism; and colin powell, the president's national security adviser and one of the top-ranking blacks in the reagan administration
all of this, of course, assumes that the vice president wins the nomination. he is way ahead, and dole said last week, ``i think it's probably a foregone conclusion what's happening on the republican side.''
bush, asked whether he would consider dole as a running mate, said: ``it's too early for me to start thinking about any running mates. that would project a certain arrogance or presumption that i don't want to do.'' agriculture department licensing of genetic vaccine.</note>
another genetically engineered pesticide is jumping through the usual regulatory hoops and the usual opponent of the technology, jeremy rifkin, is throwing up a novel argument against it
rifkin, whose campaign against genetic engineering has delayed some field tests of the organisms, says the proposed biological pesticide will cause a decline in corn yields
the decline, he claims, is an adverse environmental effect and reason to deny the developer, crop genetics inc. of dorsey, md., permission to run field tests
the company says its planned product is unique among biological and genetically engineered pesticides in that it aims to ``vaccinate'' the plant against attack by the target pest _ the corn borer, a kind of caterpillar. it works inside the plant's vascular system, and does not change the plant or the pest genetically
for that reason, the company calls it the ``incide'' technique
in a sign of the increasing importance of genetic engineering techniques in farming, the agriculture department said monday it would license syntrovet, inc. of lenexa, kan., to market the nation's third genetically engineered vaccine to control pseudorabies in swine, a contagious disease that can be deadly to newborn pigs but does not affect humans
james w. glosser, administrator of the department's animal and plant health inspection service, said safety and effectiveness had been shown in field trials on 400 animals in three states, and there is ``no significant impact on the human environment.''
when crop genetics told reporters last week that its organism causes no significant change in yields, ``they lied ... and you can quote me,'' rifkin said
the company's chief scientist, peter carlson, was asked about rifkin's assertion and statements in support of it. carlson said rifkin did not quote the relevant sections of the company's application for testing permits
some tests using the carrier organism without the pesticide have shown crop declines, notably of 17 percent in florida test plots, but the ``usual statistical tests that scientists use show there is not a significant difference'' from untreated corn, carlson said
and even if there is a decline, the company insists that's not an environmental effect or a reason to deny permits. ``if we cause a significant decline in yields, no farmer is going to buy our product,'' carlson said. ``rifkin is grabbing at any argument he can.''
it may well be true that corn will show a small decline in yields, he said. but a farmer might accept that if he could achieve a large decline in costs
the corn borer causes $400 million in crop damage, even after farmers spend about $50 million on chemical pesticides, the company said. the borer can reduce yields 20 percent in some corn belt areas
the company's technique uses a harmless bacterium to carry the toxin that kills the borer. carlson has selected one that's found normally only in bermuda grass _ clavibacter xyli, subspecies cynodontis, or cxc. cows have been eating it for centuries
the toxin is produced by a gene in another bacterium. that gene, using the techniques of recombinant dna, is inserted into cxc. the modified cxc is injected into the seed and will exist in the corn plant's vascular system, its new gene directing the manufacture of the protein toxin in the cell
when the borer eats the corn leaf or stem tissue, it also gobbles the toxin
if the environmental protection agency and the agriculture department's animal and plant health inspection service approve, the company hopes to run field tests in queen anne's county, maryland and at the department's beltsville, md. research station this year. it also has applied to test in france
the company has asked that epa waive some suggested toxicity tests, tests it says are not necessary in the light of results from other tests. rifkin is attacking the application on this grounds too, arguing that all the tests should be performed
in its campaign for public understanding and acceptance of the field experiments, crop genetics has lined up heavyweights on an advisory board that include two former administrators of the environmental protection agency, william ruckelshaus and douglas costle, and elliot l. richardson, a former attorney general and secretary of several cabinet agencies. of other detained journalists. picks up 9th graf, ``we were . ..'</note>
troops firing shotguns, tear gas and water cannon routed thousands of anti-government marchers, then stormed a hotel to arrest opposition activists and journalists
several people were injured and dozens were arrested, witnesses said
monday's march through the city shut down by a general strike was one of the largest protests in months against gen. manuel antonio noriega. about 10,000 people turned the city center into a sea of waving white handkerchiefs, the trademark of those demanding the strongman's ouster
a few hours after the march was broken up, plainclothes agents, army troops and police burst into the lobby of the marriott hotel in the southeast part of the city. firing shots in the air, they came in the front and the back, smashing one of the glass doors
leaders of the opposition national civic crusade, which sponsored the march and has been using the hotel as a headquarters, scattered down hallways and up stairwells. but the troopers caught many of them and hustled them out
the hotel is also the headquarters for most of the international press corps. the security agents forced their way at gunpoint into the offices there of nbc, cbs, abc and cnn. tapes, including footage of the day's march, were confiscated and several journalists were detained
an officer on the scene said about 40 people were taken from the hotel. most appeared to have been crusade members or journalists
richard cole, an ap reporter, was one of eight foreign journalists detained and taken to a downtown military intelligence center. they spent three hours being searched, questioned and then lectured to by maj. felipe camargo
the seven others were abidel vivancos, a mexican with abc-tv; alfredo gudino, a mexican with nbc-tv; thomas haley, a u.s. photographer with the sipa agency; j.b. diedrich, a miami-based photographer with contact photos; maria cortina, a mexican with mexican and spanish radio; and jose manuel pintada and eduardo herrera, mexicans with spanish television
we were all extremely worried because of the military campaign attacking the international press as `disinformers,''' said cole. ``my notes including interviews with pro- and anti-government figures were taken and photocopied.''
the notes were returned upon his release
during the demonstration, the crowd chanted ``justice!'' and ``noriega, tyrant, your end is near!'' as it progressed through the shopping district
more than 90 percent of the stores were closed in support of a general strike now in its second week. the strike's organizers say it will last until noriega leaves the country
about 1,000 marchers had set out from the meeting place, a church in the city center. their ranks swelled rapidly with people from buildings lining the route. those who remained in their apartments leaned out windows waving white towels, clapping and chanting
suddenly, panicked marchers shouted an incongruous warning
smurfs! smurfs!'' they cried, pressing backward, turning and running back down the avenue
panamanian police water cannons are inexplicably adorned with 3-foot-tall depictions of the elfin cartoon character, known in spanish as ``pitufos.''
the vehicles sped toward the crowd spraying a mixture of water and harsh irritant that blinds those it hits for up to 10 minutes and burns the skin. it also provokes convulsive coughing
within minutes, the street was empty except for gas-masked troopers and a few stumbling, sputtering individuals. police fired tear gas and birdshot down the avenue and side streets, even though almost everyone was in flight
a middle-aged woman sitting on the sidewalk called to this reporter. her leg was snapped just above the ankle, the shattered shinbone pierced her skin
a passing taxi was stopped and the woman, who had tripped and been trampled, was placed in it for transport to the hospital. the street was lined with scores of shoes shed as the crowd fled police
denia quintero de morales, another middle-aged woman who had taken part in the march, emerged from an alley a few minutes later, blood dripping from her gashed head. she too had stumbled and been trod on in the panic
witnesses said they saw at least 10 people injured in the stampede. some of the slower runners were beaten with rubber truncheons by pursuing riot troops
the current phase of panama's 10-month-old political and economic crisis began feb. 26, when noriega orchestrated the ouster of president eric delvalle. hours earlier, delvalle had tried to fire noriega
washington continues to recognize delvalle, who is in hiding. the reagan administration has frozen panamanian government funds in u.s. banks, denying this country a supply of dollars, the official panamanian currency
because banks have been closed for almost four weeks, currency has become precious and many people are doing without essentials. some go hungry
nearly 20 crusade leaders were arrested monday, either just after the march was broken up or at the hotel, opposition spokesmen said. they had not been released by midnight. some panamanian reporters apparently remained in detention past midnight
the state supreme court threw out a death sentence against a vietnam veteran because the sentencing trial omitted testimony that the killer of two young girls may have been driven by trauma caused by his wartime experiences
the court ruled unanimously monday that the jury might not have sentenced phillip lucero to death if it had been allowed to hear the assessment of a veterans' counselor
the ruling ordered a new penalty-phase trial with the previously excluded evidence to decide whether lucero should be sentenced to death or life without parole
justice stanley mosk, in a separate opinion, went further and said the court should forbid a death sentence for lucero
as his patriotic duty, he killed our enemies efficiently,'' wrote mosk. ``unfortunately, after returning home he irrationally killed again, this time two innocent children. there is macabre irony in the fact that the society on whose behalf lucero took an undetermined number of lives is now seeking to take his life.''
in the penalty phase of the trial, psychiatrist edward conolley testified that lucero suffered ``post-traumatic stress,'' including flashbacks to incidents in which he killed a grenade-wielding soldier who proved to be an ally and carried rotting corpses from the battlefield
conolley attributed the murders to lucero's mental impairment, compounded by flashbacks that may have been touched off by the sound of police helicopters and the cackling of a goose outside his home, because agitated animals in vietnam often foreshadowed the approach of unfriendly forces
however, then-superior court judge joseph campbell barred testimony by thomas wulbrecht, a veteran who runs a counseling program for vietnam vets at a veterans' hospital. based on a 3{-hour conversation with lucero that did not include the circumstances of the murders, wulbrecht said he would have testified that lucero probably had been driven by the same stress syndrome
justice allen broussard, in writing for the court, said the jury should have been allowed to consider the testimony as an argument favoring leniency. he said it could have been more persuasive than conolley's testimony: the prosecution sought to discredit the psychiatrist as a ``hired gun'' for the defense but could not have used the same attack on wulbrecht, broussard said
the court also ruled that campbell wrongly prevented conolley from answering questions about whether lucero was likely to repeat his crimes or could adjust to prison, broussard said
lucero's is the fifth death sentence the court has reversed out of 16 it has considered since conservatives gained a majority last year. all of the reversals have been unanimous
lucero, now 42, was convicted of murdering 7-year-old chris hubbard and 10-year-old teddy engliman, his neighbors in the town of yucaipa in san bernardino county
the girls were last seen at the back of lucero's lot on an afternoon in april 1980. a neighbor heard lucero's goose cackling and heard lucero tell the girls, as they entered his yard, that the goose would not hurt them. after helicopters were called in and a fire broke out in lucero's house, the girls' bodies were found in a nearby trash container, one beaten, the other strangled
the supreme court upheld the murder convictions, saying lucero's approach to the girls and their accompanying him into his yard would allow the jury to conclude reasonably that the killings were premeditated
after a turbulent childhood, lucero lied about his age, joined the army at 16 and served three tours of combat in vietnam, receiving a purple heart and a combat infantry badge. users</head>
off-the-road users of diesel would be exempted from payment of the 15.1-cent federal tax on april 1 under a senate finance committee amendment offered today
the committee had approved the exemption last week but, because of budget restrictions, made the change effective oct. 1. that would have required farmers, fishermen and other off-road users to pay the tax for six months and then apply for a rebate early next year
most of these users traditionally have been exempt from paying the tax. a 1987 law that goes into effect april 1 requires that they pay the tax and later apply for a refund
in introducing the new proposal today, sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, chairman of the finance committee, said that exempting off-road users april 1 instead of oct. 1 could be paid for by revising the requirements for corporations to make estimated income-tax payments
it is up to the house ways and means committee, where tax bills must originate, to determine whether the diesel provision is changed. that panel has given no indication when it will consider the proposal, meaning there is little chance it could become law by april 1
suspected sikh militants sprayed a wedding party with rifle fire, killing 10 people, and fatally shot seven other people elsewhere in the northern punjab state, police said today
among the victims of the suspected guerrillas were the bride and bridegroom and four children aged 1 to 5 who were with the wedding party, authorities said
five sikhs were slain in attacks in gurdaspur and kapurthala districts, according to police in chandigarh, the punjab capital. two hindus were also shot dead in jalandhar in the attacks late monday and today, they said
four men armed with ak-47 assault rifles opened fire at random monday night on the sikh wedding party of about 20 people in the village of johramadan, 18 miles south of amritsar, police said
the attackers escaped, leaving behind a note that claimed the victims were police informers. it was signed ``khalistan liberation force,'' according to police superintendent izhar alam
khalistan is the name sikh militants use for the independent nation they demand be created in punjab
the latest deaths raised to more than 560 the number of people killed in attacks in punjab blamed on sikh militants since the beginning of the year
the sikhs, whose religion combines hinduism and islam, make up about 2 percent of india's population. they are a majority, however, in the rich farming state of punjab. the militants say they need a separate nation to protect their faith from domination by hindus, who are more than 80 percent of india's people
the execution of a man condemned for murdering a sheriff's deputy can go forward wednesday, an appellate court said, but lawyers for the man said they will appeal to the supreme court
john henry selvage, 37, is scheduled to be executed before dawn. the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals late monday vacated the stay for selvage that was granted friday by u.s. district judge norman black of houston
selvage was convicted of capital murder in the death july 30, 1979, of harris county sheriff's deputy albert garza
black had granted the reprieve while the appellate court reconsiders the appeal of another death row inmate from harris county, leon rutherford king. king is questioning the selection of jurors during his trial
david cunningham, selvage's attorney, said he would appeal to the surpreme court today. he said the appeal will be based on several issues, including instructions to jurors on mitigating circumstances, a matter the court is considering in the case of texas death row inmate donald gene franklin
garza was trying to prevent a robbery at a jewelry store in houston but had not drawn his weapon at the time he was shot
selvage has been granted at least four postponements or stays for scheduled executions
a u.s. attorney said city police officers can be trusted to help investigate charges of corruption on their own force
affidavits released in federal court here last week revealed that fbi informants have accused several new orleans police officers working in the french quarter of crimes including drug dealing, accepting bribes and burglary
some officers will be deputized as federal marshals as part of an effort to investigate the charges, u.s. attorney john volz said at a news conference monday
police superintendent warren woodfork wouldn't say who among his investigators would be deputized. but both he and volz said they were confident the deputy marshals would investigate their own department thoroughly
we have no reason at all to have any lack of trust in the superintendent or in anyone he designates,'' said volz
the affidavits unsealed last week were filed by the fbi over two years to support requests for permission to place wiretaps on businesses and residences of reputed organized crime figures believed to be involved in drug smuggling
in those affidavits, two unidentified fbi informants are said to have accused officers of crimes. one officer is accused of selling cocaine. another is accused of burglarizing a warehouse
an informant also said officers who worked off-duty guard details for businesses sometimes made questionable arrests at the behests of their off-duty bosses. details of sumgait deaths and gerasimov comment.</note>
residents of a disputed region in the republic of azerbaijan shut down their main city for a second day today to protest the government's refusal to transfer the region to neighboring armenia, a newspaper said
my report today will be short,'' p. gutiontov, a correspondent for the government newspaper izvestia wrote from stepanakert. ``city enterprises are at standstill, people are home.''
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov also told a regular news briefing that some workers in stepanakert stayed home from their jobs
certain enterprises are not functioning or are partially not functioning,'' he said
stepanakert is the biggest city in nagorno-karabakh, a region in azerbaijan which armenians want annexed to armenia. activists said a general strike began last wednesday in the mostly armenian area
in a separate report, the afternoon newspaper izvestia provided the first breakdown of casualties in sumgait, an azerbaijani city where ethnic rioting broke out feb. 28. it confirmed the official death toll of 32, and said 26 of them were armenians while six were azeris
activists have claimed the death toll was much higher
gerasimov said residents of yerevan, the armenian capital, went to work as usual. he reiterated that the government would not be forced into appeasing armenian demands to annex nagorno-karabakh
we cannot solve the problem by mechanically transferring this region as some armenian officials want,'' he said. ``the more you study this problem the more you will see the whole thing is not as simple as that, as merely saying nagorno-karabakh must be part of armenia.''
also today, a moscow dissident said police on monday evening broke up a demonstration by more than 50 people who demanded freedom for a jailed armenian activist and carried signs saying, ``we don't believe in perestroika.''
the dissident, tamara grigoryants, said she received her information about the protest in a telephone conversation with members of a committee promoting armenian self-determination in yerevan
police did not interfere with an earlier demonstration monday in yerevan by more than 100 people, but dispersed the second group, she said
she said her telephone call was interrupted and she could not find out other details, including whether there were any arrests
both groups demanded freedom for jailed nationalist leader paryur arikyan, she said
arikyan was arrested in yerevan after being detained by police in moscow, where he had provided information to foreign journalists about events in armenia. dissident sources say they have learned he has been charged under a law prohibiting spreading false information about the soviet union
the signs against perestroika were a challenge to soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and his broad effort to restructure soviet society. the soviet government last week declared armenian agitation for annexation of nagorno-karabakh intolerable but released a plan to improve economic and social conditions in the region
gorbachev has appealed for patience and said that the policy-making communist party central committee will discuss the dispute in an upcoming meeting on relations between the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
officials have pledged a cultural and economic development plan for nagorno-karabakh, apparently instead of meeting the armenian demand to annex the territorty
the newspaper sovietskaya kultura said today the plan would cost up to $640 million
these millions, which are so necessary now for restructuring, the country is giving to karabakh,'' it said in a front-page article tracing the unrest to poor social and economic conditions
sovietskaya kultura backed the soviet leadership's plan to improve conditions, even though armenian activists have said specifically that improvement of education, cultural facilities and economic conditions will not solve the problem
the newspaper said there is almost a complete absence of schoolbooks in the armenian language, no teaching of armenian history and that residents of nagorno-karabakh could not receive armenian television
it said each resident of the area would have a separate apartment or home by the year 2,000 and that the government would build two reservoirs to improve the water supply to stepanakert. soviets denying report of soviet deaths. picks up 5th graf `earlier sunday ...'</note>
a bomb planted in a jeep killed at least four soviets in kabul, and an afghan politburo member narrowly escaped assassination when a bomb blew up a bridge, western diplomatic sources said today
the politburo member was wounded and two of his bodyguards died, the diplomats said
the violence in the afghan capital coincided with reports of clashes in northern and eastern afghanistan between soviet-backed government forces and anti-communist moslem guerrillas, the diplomats said. they spoke on condition of anonymity
in moscow, a soviet spokesman denied that soviets had been killed in the attack sunday
this is not true. nothing of this kind has happened,'' said foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov. the spokesman said he had talked with the soviet ambassador in kabul
diplomats said the bomb blew up a jeep and killed at least four soviets. it also gutted a shop, blew over a tree and hurled debris several hundred yards. the explosion occurred in a shopping district of the afghan capital that is frequented mainly by soviets, diplomats said
earlier sunday, two bombs were defused near the central post office and ministry of communications, the diplomats said. two other bombs were discovered and defused in mid-march in the ministry of the interior, they said
the diplomats said other incidents in the capital indicated a new flare-up of factionalism between the mainly urban parcham wing and the rural khalq wing of the ruling people's democratic party of afghanistan
the sources said a car bomb exploded march 23 on a bridge spanning the kabul river as khalqi politburo member saleh mohammad zeary was driving by, wounding him and killing two bodyguards riding in a separate car
on march 19, national police of the interior ministry and secret police of the state security ministry got into a firefight that killed several interior police, the diplomats said
both forces are charged with maintaining security in kabul but the secret police are aligned with the parchamis of president najib, former intelligence chief, while the national police are predominantly khalqi, as is the military
despite the violence in kabul, the sources said the traditional battlefield in paghman, west of the city, has become quiet as guerrillas apparently have concentrated on resupplying with the spring thaw
the diplomats said it was unclear whether the latest pattern in fighting reflected expectations of a soviet troop withdrawal, which moscow has said could begin in late spring
the soviets sent troops to afghanistan in december 1979 to help the government battle moslem insurgents. some 115,000 soviets remain. sub 5th graf bgng ``a hartford'' to add simon poll figure; sub 14th graf bgng ``the newspaper'' to restore dropped figure to 64 percent</note>
vice president george bush was likely to win handily in connecticut's republican primary today while jesse jackson hoped to give regional favorite michael dukakis a run for his money in the democratic contest
there are 52 democratic delegates and 35 republican delegates at stake in the connecticut contest. voter registrars around the state reported a surge of last-minute registrations before the noon monday deadline
but early reports from polling places indicated light turnout. ``it's very, very slow,'' waterbury deputy democratic registrar gloria keaveney said. state officials predicted about a third of the voters would turn out
dukakis, the massachusetts governor, has won all five new england contests so far
a hartford courant newspaper poll conducted march 9-20 gave dukakis the support of 50 percent of democrats likely to vote tuesday. jackson had 16 percent and paul simon and albert gore jr. each had 3 percent. twenty-seven percent were undecided. the poll of 558 democrats had a margin of error of 5 percentage points
thirman milner, jackson's connecticut chairman, estimated jackson would win at least 24 percent and possibly 30 percent
dukakis has the support of connecticut's top democrats, including gov. william a. o'neill, sen. christopher j. dodd and state chairman john f. droney
droney, who is nominally supporting dukakis, said his loss to jackson in michigan made a strong showing _ 50 percent or better _ even more crucial in connecticut. dukakis rejected the thesis
look _ a victory is a victory,'' dukakis said at a news conference
droney said the results today will depend largely on voter turnout
if you had all 650,000 democrats in the state vote ... then i think dukakis would have 50 or 60 percent of the vote,'' droney said. ``but only 33 or 35 percent of them are going to vote and of that ... a third of them are going to be jackson people.''
bush grew up in connecticut and still retains strong links here. he was the son of a popular u.s. senator from the state and his mother and brother still live in greenwich
bush beat ronald reagan in conecticut's 1980 primary
the newspaper poll showed bush with the support of 64 percent of the 432 likely gop voters tuesday, while sen. bob dole of kansas had 20 percent and pat robertson had 2 percent. the remaining 14 percent were undecided. the poll of republicans had a margin of error of 6 percent
bush has the support of virtually all the gop hierarchy in connecticut, including its four-member congressional delegation and state chairman robert s. poliner
voter registrars around the state reported a surge of last-minute registrations before the monday noon deadline. in new haven, officials said hundreds signed up, while the estimate in hartford was 400 and in bridgeport, 200
voter registration figures provided last week by the secretary of state's office showed that an estimated 648,000 democrats and 430,000 republicans were eligible to vote in today's primary. party leaders estimated that turnout would be between 30 percent and 40 percent
soviet and american doctors participating in an international satellite teleconference differed today on whether cancer patients should be informed of their medical condition
in an exchange between specialists at the national institutes of health near washington and soviet specialists at a studio in moscow, the russian doctors said they believed cancer patients should not be told they have the disease
doctors on the american end of the satellite-linked teleconference strongly disagreed
the soviets presented an informal survey in which soviet citizens repeatedly said they would prefer not to be informed if they are diagnosed with cancer
dr. nikaolai p. napalkov, president of the oncological society of the ussr, said patients usually are not informed in the soviet union of such a diagnosis because of the widespread belief that cancer automatically means death
only in rare cases when a patient refuses treatment does the doctor have an obligation to tell the patient'' that he has cancer, napalkov said
he said generally soviet doctors believe that ``it is hardly a good idea to tell the patient directly that he has cancer.''
dr. natalya peredodchikova, another soviet cancer specialist, said that ``unless there is an acute necessity, such as their refusing treatment, there is no need to tell the patient.''
but dr. steven a. rosenberg, chief of surgery at the national cancer institute, said he feels compelled to tell patients precise details of their condition in order to maintain a solid patient-doctor relationship
the sense of trust that exists between doctor and patient is very important,'' he said
it's improbable for me to imagine treating a patient without that free exchange of information,'' rosenberg said
the television exchange between cancer specialists of the two countries lasted just over two hours and begand with pre-recorded remarks from president reagan and his wife, nancy
mrs. reagan, who has undergone surgery for breast cancer, said that ``cancer is bigger than any one country; it is a problem of all mankind.''
the first lady said that she had ``always thought cancer would strike someone else, another family.''
then her husband and she both developed cacers which were surgically removed
we have been fortunate recipients of advanced medical science,'' she said
reagan struck the same theme in his brief remarks, telling the doctors of both countries, ``we are depending on all of you in your combined wisdom to win the battle over this disease and, in doing so, to improve the length and quality of human life for all mankind.''
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev, in a statement read during the telecast, said cancer is an enemy that is striking humans in countries everywhere
though there has been progress, he said, ``the enemy is far from routed, he is not retreating and is threatening everybody, and the fight calls for vigorous and concerted action.''
a spokeswoman at nci said the cancer researchers wanted to exchange ideas on treatment, diagnostic techniques and methods of prevention
organizers arranged for the conference to be broadcast to about 1,500 u.s. hospitals and health care facilities on the hospital satellite network. the u.s. information agency also arranged to carry the conference on its worldnet system to 57 cities in europe, africa and the middle east. in the soviet union, an edited version of the conference will be broadcast to an estimated 150 million people
a ban on state-funded abortions for poor women has been put off at least until voters decide the issue this fall
the ban had been scheduled to take effect wednesday, but attorney general frank kelley on monday postponed it until after the nov. 8 election
we simply have to accept his decision. we would like to emphasize that the law was a duly enacted law, passed by overwhelming majorities in both houses of the legislature, and we felt very strongly that it should go into effect,'' said barbara listing, president of right to life of michigan
kelley said the law should be delayed because pro-choice forces apparently gathered enough signatures to put the issue on the fall ballot. under the state constitution, getting a law put to a vote suspends it
the signatures aren't expected to be certified until next month, but kelley said because the petitions appear to meet legal requirements, the signatures must be presumed valid
his opinion carries the weight of law, unless overturned by a circuit court
we have to be pleased that there will be no cutoff and that health care for poor women will continue and we're pleased that their health is going to be protected at least until november, when voters go to the polls and settle this issue,'' said judith frey, a spokeswoman for the people's campaign for choice
the measure easily passed the legislature last year, and because it had been initiated by a petition drive, it escaped the gubernatorial veto that has scuttled 17 previous efforts to cut off the funding
after the law was passed, anti-abortion forces contended it should take effect immediately, but pro-choice groups sued, and the courts ruled that it would take effect 90 days after the end of the 1987 legislative session
meanwhile, the pro-choice forces started their own petition drive, leading to the delay until voters decide the issue
michigan is one of 14 states that uses taxpayer money to finance abortions for the poor. in 1986, the most recent year for which a final tally is available, michigan paid $5.8 million for 18,600 abortions
the king county council has approved an ordinance requiring sex offenders give up blood samples, which will provide a ``genetic fingerprint.''
under the law, which was passed monday and takes effect oct. 1, people convicted of sex offenses will be required to surrender a blood sample. police will build a genetic library for future investigations
it will be a huge step forward in our ability to apprehend and prosecute rapists,'' said king county councilman ron sims, one of eight council members taking part in the unanimous vote
a spokesman for the american civil liberties union endorsed parts of the law but urged the council to delay final action
this would be the first in the nation, and we therefore are responsible to be sure all issues are understood and agreed to. take time to analyze. don't be hasty,'' jerry sheehan said
but the king county prosecutor's office urged the council not to be intimidated by being first
the fact that we may be the first jurisdiction (to adopt the genetic fingerprinting legislation) gives us a sense of responsibility, but we should not shy away from its extreme value,'' said jeffrey baird, a deputy prosecutor
baird said identifying offenders is often the most difficult part of prosecuting rape cases. ``this evidence will help resolve the question of identity,'' he said
the ordinance established a technical committee to guarantee the accuracy and reliability of the genetic process. a separate committee will study how to store and retrieve genetic data
