an african national congress official who recently told authorities she had received death threats and was being followed was shot and killed today while entering her office
the body of dulcie september, 45, was found in her northeast paris apartment building, which also served as an office for the group
mrs. september had represented the anc in france, switzerland and luxembourg since 1984. the anti-apartheid group is outlawed in south africa
an anc colleague said mrs. september recently told interior ministry officials that she had received threats and was being followed
no group or individual immediately claimed responsibility for the attack, but anc officials blamed south africa. south africa denied involvement
the french news agency agence-france press reported mrs. september was shot in the face while entering her office about 9 a.m. her body was found surrounded by shells from a .22-caliber rifle
she was holding letters in her hand and a key was in the door of the fourth-floor office, afp reported. sources at the scene said her attacker apparently was waiting when she arrived to begin her normal working day
maurice cukierman, an anc treasurer in the office, said mrs. september had ``informed the ministry of the interior that she had received threats and that she had been followed during the last few days.''
it is with anger that i learned of her assassination, especially since we had advised french authorities that south africa was ready to commit assassinations in europe,'' he said
eddy amkongo, representative in france for the southwest african peoples organization, told reporters at the scene of the killing that he had also been threatened and had requested protection from the french government
but until today we have received no response,'' he said
the interior ministry declined to confirm or deny whether it had received requests for protection from the african groups
police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the assassination looked like ``the work of a professional.''
at anc headquarters in lusaka, zambia, spokesman tom sebina called the killing ``part of a deliberate south african campaign to assassinate anc members and anc leaders.''
without citing any evidence, sebina linked mrs. september's killing to a recent series of attacks carried out by the south african military against what the south african army called anc ``terrorists.''
since friday the south african army has killed 11 people in raids in botswana, near the botswana border with south africa and in the black homeland of venda
sebina said he did not know whether any of the 11 people killed in the raids were affiliated with the anc
south african foreign minister roloef pik botha suggested the death may have been the result of an internal quarrel within the anc
pretoria ``cannot be held responsible for this death,'' the foreign minister said in a statement issued through the south african embassy. ``while details concerning the assassination are not yet known, the (south african) government must stress that serious quarrels exist within organizations which use violence to attain their political objectives.''
the anc, the main black guerrilla group fighting to overthrow the south africa government, maintains a worldwide network of about 20 ``information offices,'' including several in europe, to lobby for support and receive aid
the anc was banned by south africa in 1960 for its anti-apartheid activities. since then, it has waged a bombing a sabotage campaign to wrest control from the government in pretoria
the soviet union is the anc's chief military supplier. anc leader nelson mandela has been jailed in south africa since 1962
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. supporters say. inserts 19th graf, byrd said. removes last 5 grafs pvs to shorten.</note>
the senate met today in an unusual closed-door session called by conservatives who say the soviets are lying about their nuclear forces, but supporters of the u.s.-soviet arms treaty said the charges already have been refuted
we're going to examine the evidence that there are over 1,000 ss-20s, that the cia has attempted to cook the books on the issue, and that the soviets have deliberately falsified their data,'' said sen. steven symms, r-idaho, one of the chief critics of the treaty banning medium-range missiles
but sen. william cohen, r-maine, vice-chairman of the intelligence committee, said the charges are ``the same old stuff'' which has been considered and rejected by the panel as it endorsed the treaty last week
the soviets have declared that they have 650 ss-20s and all those missiles will have to be destroyed when the pact takes effect
but symms and other critics say the soviets have up to 350 ss-20s more han they have declared, and the critics have said u.s. intelligence estimates of the higher numbers have been hidden
in the opinion of this seantor, the cia has cooked the numbers of ss-20s and i'm prepared to prove it,'' said sen. malcolm wallop, r-wyo., another critic of the pact
sen. patrick leahy, d-vt., a supporter of the treaty, said, ``these arguments have been heard and rejected. i don't expect to hear anything i don't know.''
the old senate chamber where the meeting was held has only rarely been used for business meetings since the senate moved to its present quarters in 1859. it was used this time because the regular senate chamber is laced with modern broadcasting and electric cable that could make eavesdropping possible
it is the first secret senate meeting since oct. 7, 1986, and one of six in the past six years
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., said today that the closed-door meeting was sought by conservatives and he noted that senate rules permit such a session at the request of any two senators
supporters of the u.s.-soviet treaty say the senate foreign relations committee is likely to approve it by a margin similar to the 18-2 endorsement given monday by the senate armed services committee
the foreign relations panel is scheduled to vote wednesday on whether to send the pact to the floor of the full senate, where approval is expected next month
when the foreign relations committee finally votes, ``i expect the treaty will be endorsed by a substantial majority,'' said sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the panel
sen. richard lugar, r-ind., a chief treaty supporter among panel republicans, agreed with pell. ``there is strong bipartisan support,'' lugar said
the only opposition votes in the closed-door armed services meeting monday were cast by sens. gordon humphrey, r-n.h., and symms, according to senators who were present
however, armed services chairman sam nunn, d-ga., said there are still a number of questions which should be answered about the treaty
nunn told the foreign relations committee that during his panel's hearings, ``serious concerns were raised that the treaty was unclear on futuristic systems'' and whether they would be banned by the pact
examples of those systems could include laser weapons, particle beam weapons or other advanced technologies, he said
byrd said today that when the treaty reaches the floor, he won't seek a vote until the issue is resolved. ``i think that's a very important matter that's going to have to be settled,'' he said
the treaty bans ``weapons delivery vehicles'' with a range of 400 to 3,400 miles, nunn noted, but ``there was disagreement on what that meant.''
there has not been any final word from the reagan administration on how the united states is defining the term and the armed services committee thinks it is ``critical'' that the question be answered, nunn said. the white house has been asked for a report providing that answer, he said
the senate must be very clear in defining which type of futuristic weapons will be allowed and which will not,'' nunn said
sen. daniel quayle, r-ind., a member of the armed services committee, said the panel thought it was easier to define what weapons or technologies are covered now, instead of waiting until the next decade
sen. john warner, r-va., ranking republican on the armed services panel, said he thought the questions can be answered within two or three days
an elderly chinese catholic priest, who spent much of the last 30 years behind bars for refusing to cut his links with the vatican, has been released on parole, the shanghai catholic association said today
an official of the state-sanctioned assocation, who declined to be identified, said vincent chu, also known as zhu hongshen, was paroled feb. 6 so he could obtain better medical attention. he said chu, believed to be about 72, was generally in good health
the jesuit priest was first jailed in 1955 along with shanghai bishop ignatius kung (gong pinmei), who was convicted of treason and sentenced to life in prison
kung, now 87, was released in 1985. a shanghai court earlier this year ended his parole and restored his political rights
chu was released from prison in 1979 and reportedly resumed his contacts with priests who secretly remained loyal to the vatican
chu and three other elderly jesuit priests were detained in 1981 and charged two years later with colluding with foreign countries and endangering the sovereignty of the state among other crimes
chu was sentenced to 15 years in prison. the other three received sentences ranging from 2{ years to 10 years. the shanghai church official declined comment on the situation of the other three
china severed relations with the vatican in 1957 and set up the chinese patriotic catholic church as the only recognized organization for chinese catholics
the church claims more than 3 million members. an unknown number of catholics remain secretly loyal to the pope, and several still are being held in prison for their religious practices. conference, corrects names and ages of suspects. picks up 12th graf pvs, `the county ....' ^by john flesher</note>
an indian judicial candidate was slain by a youth who blamed him for a romantic problem, not for political reasons, authorities said today. one suspect was jailed, the other committed suicide, they said
julian pierce, a 42-year-old lumbee indian who was running against the robeson county district attorney for superior court judge, was gunned down saturday at his home. it had been speculated that the killing was the work of someone who objected to an indian being a judge in the racially tense county
robeson county sheriff hubert stone said sandy gordon chavis, 24, a lumbee indian, was arrested this morning on a murder warrant. chavis was being held at the robeson county jail
the dead man was identified as john anderson goins, 24, also an indian, whose body was found this morning at his father's home. both men were from pembroke
i think it shows the people that nothing else is involved,'' stone said at a news conference this morning. ``i think the people of robeson county will understand that it's just another murder. i think the tension will drop now that we've made an arrest.''
i can assure the world that there was no political involvement in the case,'' he said
pierce, divorced since december 1983, was dating a woman whose daughter had been involved with goins and the man blamed him for difficulties with the girl, stone said
they (the young couple) started having problems and they broke up,'' stone said. ``two warrants were issued last week by the girlfriend's mother, charging goins with trespassing. goins felt pierce had something to do with it. he got mad and he killed him.''
the sheriff said chavis signed a confession that goins, who had worked as a security guard in raleigh, was the triggerman in the slaying
goins' body was found in a closet at his father's home. he had gone to the house after eluding police who tried to arrest him. goins died from a self-inflicted gunshot wound to the head, said stone. his father was not home at the time
neither goins nor chavis had prior criminal records, other than minor traffic violations
the murder weapon was a 12-gauge, pump shotgun, said stone. the killers came to pierce's home, broke a window pane in the back door and shot him once in the chest and again in the side as he turned, stone said. they then entered the house and shot him a third time
later, goins went to the home of ruth locklear, pierce's girlfriend and the mother of 16-year-old shannon bullard, and talked with her
he didn't tell her he had killed mr. pierce,'' stone said
commissioners in the troubled county had urged the appointment of a special prosecutor to investigate the killing because of fears it was racially linked
in addition, pierce's supporters said they would try to change a state law that would automatically make district attorney joe freeman britt the winner in the may 3 democratic primary
the county of about 100,000 people in southeast north carolina is 37 percent indian, 37 percent white and 26 percent black. the lumbee indians, who are native to the region, are not a federally recognized tribe
anger at what the indians call corrupt local government and entrenched racism boiled over feb. 1, when two lumbees took hostages at the robesonian newspaper in lumberton, the county seat
county commissioners on monday adopted a resolution asking britt to ask the state attorney general to appoint a special prosecutor
pierce's campaign manager, harvey godwin, also said the 25-member committee to elect julian pierce decided sunday to ask gov. jim martin to call a special session of the legislature to delay the primary and extend the filing period to allow another minority candidate to run
state law says if a candidate dies 30 days or more after the filing period closes, the opposing candidate is declared the winner. the filing period for the judicial race ended feb. 1
under the law, britt would be declared the winner. since there is no republican candidate in the county, winning the primary is tantamount to winning the judgeship
governor's spokesman jim sughrue said martin would meet thursday with pierce's supporters. he said martin would not make a decision before consulting with other state leaders
about 15 black and indian attorneys from the area met behind closed doors monday to select a candidate to take pierce's place. after the meeting, godwin said one to four attorneys were being considered
stone said he felt better about the investigation than he did saturday because of the way people were responding to his plea for help and because no violence had erupted
no one's interested in any more violence,'' the sheriff said
ray littleturtle, a lumbee activist, said he urged fellow indians to stay calm
however, he said many were frustrated that pierce's death had hurt their chances of achieving change from within the system
this happens in third world countries, not the united states, political candidates getting assassinated,'' littleturtle said. whitehead-gould. edits below to tighten.</note>
surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould testified today that baby m has a right to see her and would benefit from spending time with her and her family
it's her right more so than anybody's right for her to see me,'' mrs. whitehead-gould told superior court judge birger m. sween on the second day of a hearing to determine how much time she can spend with the child she bore under a $10,000 contract but then refused to give up
speaking calmly, mrs. whitehead-gould, 30, asked for immediate visits at her home and eventual overnight stays with expansion of her time with the child, now 2, to include half the summer and some holidays. mother and child now visit once a week for two hours, supervised at a social services center
mrs. whitehead-gould said she has much to offer the child, now legally melissa stern. she said the child could benefit by the support of mrs. whitehead-gould's family, including her husband, accountant dean gould, and her children by a previous marriage, ryan, 13, and tuesday, 12
she said the visitation schedule initially must be carefully spelled out by the court to make it easier for both sides in the bitter dispute to get along
on monday, the child's father, william stern, 42, in bitter testimony that ended in tears, said mrs. whitehead-gould is untrustworthy and could undermine the child's relationship with him and his wife
in the final legal phase of the baby m case, stern asked the judge to halt visitation for several years, perhaps until her 10th birthday, saying contact with mrs. whitehead-gould could emotionally harm the child
i'm afraid that she will never let melissa be her own person,'' he said in 2{ hours of testimony. ``mary beth is a liar. ... i can't trust her.''
in later testimony, stern's wife, elizabeth, said she and mrs. whitehead-gould were ``poles apart.''
i don't have any respect for her. ... i'd never choose her as my friend. and quite simply, too much has gone on,'' mrs. stern said
stern said he feared mrs. whitehead-gould, who lost a highly publicized custody battle, would exploit melissa to promote her book about the case
the hearing was ordered by the new jersey supreme court in its landmark feb. 3 decision that declared surrogacy-for-pay illegal and restored mrs. whitehead-gould's parental rights, but awarded sterns custody
the sterns paid mrs. whitehead-gould $10,000 to bear them a child because they feared 42-year-old mrs. stern, who suffers a mild form of multiple sclerosis, would suffer complications during pregnancy. mrs. whitehead-gould was artificially inseminated with stern's sperm
under cross-examination, the sterns acknowledged that melissa does not seem to have been harmed by her contact with mrs. whitehead-gould
when the judge asked him what kind of religion melissa would be exposed to, stern, who is jewish and whose relatives other than his parents all died in the holocaust, wept. after composing himself, he said he expects to expose her to the unitarian church. mrs. stern is not jewish
d.j. smith feels he's been placed in double jeopardy because the tv game show ``jeopardy'' won't pay him the $5,000 he won and has banned him from the program
the problem was that when smith appeared on ``jeopardy,'' less than a year had passed since he had played ``wheel of fortune.'' game show rules enacted after a 1958 scandal prohibit contestants from appearing on game shows more than once a year
smith won $1,200 on ``wheel of fortune'' on thanksgiving day, and was disqualified from $5,000 in ``jeopardy'' winnings
i feel like i'm in double jeopardy,'' said smith, 55, a business analyst. ``they won't give me my money, and they won't let me be on the show again.''
a representative for ``jeopardy,'' produced by merv griffin enterprises and broadcast on abc affiliates, invited smith to los angeles in january to play in a seniors ``jeopardy'' tournament
smith said he told the representative: ``that's great! i was just on the `wheel of fortune' a little while ago.''
but no one apparently caught the remark
smith said he mentioned his earlier appearance again when he filled out a registration form for ``jeopardy.''
prizes in the seniors tournament were awarded according to how many rounds each contestant survived. smith said he compiled enough points for a berth in a semifinal contest and an automatic prize of $5,000
but the next day, he said, he was told his appearance on ``wheel'' disqualified him
we didn't enjoy having to do that,'' said george vosburgh, ``jeopardy'' producer. ``even though the network stressed (the rules), it got by him and it got by us.''
game show officials withheld the $5,000 prize, awarding him the $1,000 quarterfinalist prize instead
the networks established the one-year waiting period for game shows in the aftermath of a 1958 scandal in which answers to ``the $64,000 question'' were given to contestants before the show
this is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by associated press bureaus on how the u.s. presidential election campaign is viewed abroad
jesse jackson's surge in the race for the democratic presidential nomination has gained attention in south africa and britain. here are some of the comments of newspapers in those countries:
_business day of johannesburg (pro-business): ``it has ... been a widespread belief that the u.s. is `not ready' for a black president. the support michigan gave jackson on saturday raises the intriguing possibility that this may not be true
it is more than 30 years since brown vs. board of education ended segregation in american schools, and racial causes have steadily declined in influence. could it be that many young americans, nurtured in an environment of equal rights, have outgrown racial prejudice?
 ... jackson probably won't become president this year, but he could be the man who opens the way to the white house for a black american.''
_the daily telegraph of london (conservative): ``mr. jackson still stands very little chance of securing the nomination: he is widely perceived as unelectable in november not because he is black _ america may be ready for that _ but becauppeal even to white hardhats in industrial michigan is to strengthen his claim to the vice presidential spot on the dukakis ticket, or at the very least to a say in pulling mr. dukakis's platform to the left.''
_the times of london (conservative-independent): ``mr. jackson is not unelectable because blacks vote for him. ... he is unelectable because of the kind of whites who vote for him. the entrails from michigan show him with disproportionate support from the sort of voters _ such as those in the state's numerous university towns _ who were for mr. mcgovern in 1972. he was unelectable, and white
sooner or later, a black presidential candidate will emerge in the united states who will campaign, not as a black _ emphasizing links with races and idealogues abroad who have nothing in common with american blacks either in outlook or standard of living _ but as a traditional democrat or republican.''
a man who said he locked his 79-year-old grandmother in her room without food or medication because she wanted to die has been charged with manslaughter in her death, a sheriff's spokesman said
alberta m. bandell probably died between three and four weeks ago, pasco county sheriff's spokesman bob loeffler said monday. her decomposed body was found monday morning after her grandson, richard william jones, 45, called the sheriff's office
he said he couldn't take it anymore, although we're not sure what he meant by it,'' said loeffler. ``we went over and saw a grisly, grisly scene.'' authorities discovered that the woman's dog, which also had been shut in the room and deprived of food, had chewed on the legs of the body, loeffler said. the dog survived the ordeal but was taken monday by county animal health control authorities and was expected to be put to sleep, loeffler said
jones was being held on $30,000 bail today
neighbors in this small town 20 miles northeast of tampa said they smelled something foul emanating from the mobile home, where jones continued to live, for weeks
over a month ago, i said, `god, there's a terrible stink out there,''' david l. sexton said
neighbors said jones had told them his grandmother was visiting friends in orlando and west palm beach
according to the arrest affidavit, jones cashed his grandmother's personal checks and attempted to sell the mobile home to a neighbor for $16,500
in addition to the cashed checks and the deception of his neighbors, detectives said they questioned jones' story of a mercy killing because of mrs. bandell's fairly good health and reports of frequent arguements between jones and his grandmother
he'd lock her in her bedroom different times. he'd curse and yell at her,'' sexton said
the cause of death was not known yet, but loeffler said the woman was a diabetic and required insulin injections
depending on the results of the autopsy, the charge could be changed to murder, loeffler said
a fire was discovered today in the arsenal of the puerto rico national guard and police said it might have been triggered by an explosive device
everything indicates there was a criminal hand,'' police superintendent carlos lopez feliciano said in a statement. ``we are investigating if there was an explosive or incendiary device. it's not conclusive.''
no other details on the cause of the blaze were available
the fire was discovered by an arsenal guard about 2 a.m. when smoke was seen coming out of the second-floor storage room, the superintendent said
when he checked, he saw two people in the interior parking area who jumped the fence protecting the perimeter of the arsenal,'' lopez feliciano said
all national guard facilities were under police surveillance today in case the fire was part of a coordinated attack, lopez feliciano said
we are guarding all the national guard installations in case its part of a series,'' the superintendent said
local explosives experts and officials from the fbi were at the scene gathering evidence
early this moring several fire engines were at the scene extinguishing the fire. there was no estimate of damages to the facility
about 600 members of the puerto rico national guard flew to the panama canal zone this weekend for a training exercise. the move has been criticized by groups favoring puerto rico's independence from the united states, as well as by individual members of the pro-statehood new progressive party and the governing popular democratic party
on monday, national guard adjutant gen. alfredo mora denied the guardsmen were being sent to panama for anything other than training purposes and said the possibility that the guards will see any combat ``is very remote.''
puerto ricans are u.s. citizens with most of the rights of americans, except that they cannot vote for the president of the united states. ^eds: subs 4th graf to restore dropped first reference to lukander</head>
the fbi is investigating the slaying of a 22-year-old navy airman whose decomposed body was identified 10 days after she disappeared from her home
fbi agents and other law enforcement officials met monday at the duval county medical examiner's office to discuss the case, said atlantic beach police chief david thompson. he would give no further details
we don't want to release anything that could come back to haunt us,'' he told the florida times-union and journal
detective dave archer said police were certain anita lukander was murdered, but he declined to reveal how she was killed
the victim was married may 9, 1987, to a naval petty officer who flew home from active duty aboard a frigate after being notified of his wife's disappearance
using dental records, authorties on sunday identified a body found the day before along the intracoastal waterway in jacksonville beach as that of mrs. lukander. the woman had been missing since march 17
archer said dr. peter lipkovic, medical examiner for duval, told police the body had been in the water about eight or nine days
cmdr. richard o'neal said mrs. lukander was a member of the mayport-based helicopter antisubmarine squadron light 42. her husband petty officer 2nd class bill lukander, also is a member of the squadron
mrs. lukander was assigned to shore duty as an administrative clerk in maintenance control, while her husband is an electronics technician who often is at sea for the squadron
mrs. lukander disappeared two days after a navy paymaster, lt. ratish prasad, 24, was slain march 15 aboard the uss hancock in mayport. prasad was shot in the head at close range
navy investigators said $94,629 was stolen from the ship's safe. no arrests have been made in that case
navy spokesmen said earlier there appeared to be no connection between the cases, noting that the ship and the helicopter squadron are in widely separate areas on the huge base
a military court today sentenced two soldiers accused of burying four arabs alive to longer prison sentences than requested by prosecutors, saying their conduct was grave and shameful, israel radio reported
the court sentenced pvt. dror segen-cohen to six months in jail along with a four-month suspended sentence. pvt. yair nissimi was given five months in jail and a seven-month suspended sentence
the prosecution had asked for two months in jail for segen-cohen and 2{ months for nissimi
the soldiers admitted they beat four arabs from the occupied west bank village of kfar salem on feb. 5 after a protest in the village. the soldiers also admitted burying the four arabs in about 25 inches of mud
the arabs survived
the court ruled the soldiers' behavior had tarnished the army's image and put israel in a bad light
a third soldier, sgt. maj. charlie danino, is accused of ordering the burial. he has pleaded innocent and his trial is still underway
five other soldiers are also on trial for violating military orders. one has been charged in the killing of a palestinian in the gaza strip and four others for beating two palestinian detainees after a demonstration in nablus
according to u.n. figures, 119 palestinians have been killed in the occupied territories since anti-israeli protests began dec. 8. one israeli soldier has died
the chairman of the senate governmental affairs committee says he would not allow a proposed amendment to jeopardize passage of a new cabinet-level department of veterans affairs
the statement monday by panel chairman john glenn, d-ohio, improved prosects for the legislation, which passed the house last november after president reagan announced his support for a cabinet-level department
the proposed amendment would allow veterans to appeal any denied claim to federal courts
glenn said he supported judicial review, but would not attempt to add the provision in his committee. judicial review, he said, was in the jurisdiction of the veterans affairs committee, which has tentatively scheduled a hearing on the issue for april 21
the ohio democrat said he believes veterans are treated as second class citizens, because they do not have the same appellate rights as those receiving unfavorable rulings from other agencies
the government affairs committee reported that old-line veterans groups lobbied against judicial review, while groups of vietnam and paralyzed veterans said they favor the provision. the committee said mail was split about 50-50
forestry workers killed a bengal tiger after it attacked and killed a woodcutter, who was believed to be its 17th human victim in five months, police said tuesday
the attack occurred in the sundarbans forest, a national tiger preserve 80 miles southwest of dhaka
authorities believe the tiger had killed at least 16 other people. the attacks had spread fear among nearby villagers and forestry officials, who shot the animal monday
tigers generally are shy animals and rarely attack humans unless they are injured, threatened or facing food shortages. they are protected by law with poaching punishable by up to five years in jail
the nobel foundation, after record-breaking profits, is raising the amount of the annual nobel prizes by 15 percent to $428,000, the head of the foundation said tuesday
executive director stig ramel said the foundation established by alfred nobel's 1896 testament saw its profits rise by 29 percent, yielding $5.6 million to finance the five prizes and the arrangements for awarding them
last year's prize was worth $362,000, up 8 percent from 1986
the foundation administers the endowment which finances the nobel prizes in literature, physics, chemistry and medicine. the riksbank, the central bank, created and funded the nobel memorial prize for economics in 1968
the laureates are chosen independently by the swedish academy of sciences, the academy of arts and letters and the karolinska institute. the nobel committee of the norwegian parliament awards the prestigious peace prize
the prize money is awarded in the currency of the winner's choice according to the exchange rate on dec. 10, the day of the annual award ceremony. the prize is divided if there is more than one laureate in a category. last year nine winners shared the six prizes
ramel told the associated press the jump in the value of assets was largely due to floating the foundation's real estate company on the stockholm stock exchange last year
ramel said the foundation's capital this year ``for the first time is substantially worth more'' than when the prizes were created after nobel's death. the first prizes were awarded in 1901
nobel, who invented dynamite, bequeathed the equivalent of about $150 million in his will to those who ``have conferred the greatest benefit on mankind.''
but nobel stipulated the capital be invested in what he considered safe fixed-income bonds, which later proved unprofitable. for 50 years the foundation lost money and the prize progressively shrank
the foundation lost about two-thirds of the capital,'' he said
since 1953 the regulations surrounding the nobel capital has gradually loosened, enabling the foundation to be more active in the swedish economy
that is why we started the real estate company last year,'' ramel said. ``fortunately we were unharmed by the stock market crash last october.''
the army-run radio station has refused to play a protest song critical of israeli policy in the occupied territories, the director of the station said tuesday
it attacks israeli soldiers,'' col. nahman shai said of ``shooting and crying,'' written and sung by israeli rock musician si hyman
ms. hyman said she wrote the song after hearing about a feb. 5 incident in which israeli soldiers beat four palestinians and buried them alive under two feet of dirt. they survived the attack, which occurred after troops dispersed a protest in the occupied west bank village of kfar salem
they shoot and cry, burn and laugh. when did they learn to bury people alive?'' one verse of the song says. ``when did they forget that our children have also been killed?''
however, shai said the song's accusations were unfounded. he said israeli soldiers ``are doing their jobs in the best possible fashion and deserve our appreciation.''
israel has faced international criticism for its handling of palestinian protests that began in the occupied territories four months ago
state-run israeli radio has not banned the song, but has not been playing it, either
a month-long citywide amnesty has netted 1,563 weapons, including jackknives, axes, machetes and a stun gun that can deliver a 45,000-volt electric shock, scotland yard said tuesday
the national police force said the amnesty was intended to encourage people to hand in knives. however, weapons from pump-action shotguns to brass knuckles were dumped in special bins or handed in anonymously at police stations
police cmdr. walter boreham, who supervised the amnesty, said ``these weapons, some of which could have been used to maim or kill, are now off the streets because their owners have woken up to the fact that carrying a weapon is dangerous.''
the amnesty ended march 9. graf pvs bgng ``alabama democratic...</note>
democratic officials from around the country, some wary of the prospect of jesse jackson heading their presidential ticket, will meet with jackson on wednesday to discuss what one party chairman called ``how to win in november.''
florida democratic chairman charles whitehead said a small group of party officials arranged a meeting with jackson in washington
whitehead would not say who called the meeting or what the specific purpose was, beyond ``how to win in november.''
dissent is building within the democratic party about efforts to strengthen jackson's rivals in the wake of his stunning michigan caucus victory
alabama democratic chairman john baker suggested in a letter to party leaders around the south that they form a group of unpledged convention delegates who will commit themselves to ``the most electable'' presidential candidate
we've got to keep one eye, if not two eyes, on the november general election. i'm tired of the democratic party having a ticket that can't carry but one or two states,'' said baker of montgomery, ala
others were dismayed by baker's effort
the party can't afford that,'' said jim ruvolo, state chairman in ohio. ``jesse jackson is not where he is by some sleight of hand. he got there by winning votes.''
jackson overwhelmed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the michigan caucuses on saturday, winning the industrial state by nearly 2-to-1. that victory stalled dukakis' momentum and boosted talk that jackson could be the first black to win the party's presidential nomination
baker denied his effort is aimed at jackson
i'm not trying to stop anybody,'' he said. but he insisted jackson's views do not fall within the party mainstream
a white candidate espousing what rev. jackson is espousing wouldn't have a chance at being elected,'' baker said. ``he's the most liberal candidate running. i wonder if he were white if he would have any delegates at all.''
baker's move did not get a positive response from john henry anderson, georgia's party chairman
i don't want to look at anything as a `stop jesse jackson' movement. all i want to be looking at is electing a democrat to the white house,'' said anderson, who supports dukakis
and democratic national committee chairman paul kirk would have no part of a ``stop jackson'' movement
i can't imagine that if he runs through the process and comes out on top they could take away from him. i would refuse to be part of that,'' kirk said. ``i haven't heard of one starting, and i wouldn't be a party to it.''
as the party chief, kirk promised to back the winner
we've still got the biggest primaries coming up to settle who the candidate will be, and i'll support that process and its winner whoever it is,'' kirk said
the dnc chairman said jackson has won his victories with a positive message
i think he's earned credibility, trust and respect. perhaps more than any of the other candidates, he has stayed on the high road with a unifying message and appeal for those looking for strong leadership,'' kirk said. ``the success of his candidate offers an opportunity, not a problem.''
ruvolo of ohio called jackson the front-runner in the race and brushed aside questions about electability
you win in the fall by getting the votes of the people, not by justing getting the votes of those in the backrooms,'' he said. ``the professional politicians may worry about electability, but the results so far show the people are not worrying about it.''
rep. richard gephardt, as he left the presidential race on monday, agreed, saying: ``i believe jesse jackson can be nominated and i think he can be elected.''
ruvolo said that the current discussions about jackson are premature. he said the party's nominee could easily be decided by the primary lineup of new york, pennsylvania and ohio in late april and early may
if one candidate wins all three, he is the nominee,'' ruvolo said. if no one candidate does, ``then we'll go to the brokered process.''
a former white house aide said tuesday that the reagan administration either ignored or hid the fact that panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega was dealing in drugs
but assistant secretary of state elliott abrams disputed that assertion, saying the government acted legally against noriega as soon as it could
the former white house official, norman a. bailey, told the house select committee on narcotics abuse and control that noriega and other high-level officials of the panama defense forces had been engaged in drug trafficking, gun running and money laundering since the mid-1970s
bailey, an economic consultant who formerly was a special assistant to the president for national security affairs until oct. 13, 1983, said noriega and the panamanian military have engaged ``in the past in activities which represent and have represented a clear, unquestionable and obvious multiple threat to the national security in a narrow sense, and the national interests in a broader sense, of the united states of america
it is also a story of how clear and incontrovertible evidence was at best ignored and at worst hidden and denied by many different agencies and departments of the government of the united states in such a way as to provide cover and protection for these activities while at the same time assuring that they did the maximum damage to those very interests that the officials involved were sworn to uphold and defend,'' bailey said
bailey said the information available to the u.s. government on noriega and the panama defense forces was not only a ``smoking gun but rather a 21-cannon barrage of evidence.''
but abrams told the committee there has been uncorroborated allegations of illegal drug-related activity by noriega for many years
we were not unaware of these,'' he said. ``until recently, however, there was no substantiated evidence of his narcotics involvement.''
abrams said, however, that when the justice department unveiled evidence against him, noriega was indicted by two grand juries in florida earlier this year. since then, the united states has applied economic and diplomatic pressure to drive noriega from his post as head of the defense forces
abrams said he has heard about general corruption in panama since he came into office in july 1985. ``not only drugs, but anything that can be done for money,'' he said
in answer to a question by rep. benjamin a. gilman, r-n.y., abrams said he would not be surprised to learn that noriega was either a double or triple agent
noriega is loyal to no one,'' he said. ``he has dealt with our intelligence agencies. he has dealt with cuban intelligence. he has dealt with everyone. he took what information he could get and passed it on or sold it.''
following the hearing, abrams told reporters: ``i'm unaware of any documentation (of drug trafficking) during the past five years.''
when asked about bailey's charges, he replied: ``why do you think we're going after noriega?''
the security council will convene an urgent meeting wednesday to discuss the situation in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip, arab diplomats said today
a delegation of arab foreign ministers and the plo called on secretary-general javier perez de cuellar today to schedule the meeting. they also urged the u.n. chief to send another fact-finding mission to the occupied territories
in the toughest crackdown since palestinian unrest began nearly dec. 8, the israeli army today enforced a three-day closure of the occupied lands, barring nearly all journalists, israeli civilians and arab visitors
clovis maksoud, u.n. ambassador for the arab league, told reporters after the delegation met perez de cuellar that the security council would convene wednesday to discuss israel's actions in the occupied lands
the delegation included farouk kaddoumi, head of the political department of the palestine liberation organization; ahmed taleb ibrahimi, algeria's foreign minister; ibrahim massoud, minister of state for foreign affairs of saudi arabia; farouk al-shara, the syrian foreign minister; and chedli klibi, secretary-general of the league of arab states
the delegation, except for the plo envoy, left for a meeting at the state department in washington to express arab views on the palestinian demonstrations in the occupied territories, a middle east peace conference, u.s. efforts to close the plo's u.n. mission and other issues
the security council has held several meetings on the middle east since the heightened palestinian unrest began and each time has condemned israel's measures to put down the protests
a meeting is necessary because of israel's clamp down today, its banning the press and curfew,'' maksoud said
the delegation also asked the united nations to send a second-fact finding mission to the territories. under secretary-general marrack goulding recently visited the territories and submitted a report sharply critical of israel
the secretary-general has called for a u.n.-sponsored middle east peace conference, involving all parties to the middle east conflict, including the plo, and the five permanent members of the security council
tunisia on friday formally requested the security council meeting
price support loans for some old-crop corn and sorghum will be extended for a year longer than their normal maturity dates, agriculture secretary richard e. lyng said tuesday
the one-year extensions were approved for 1984-crop corn and sorghum held in the farmer-owned reserve program, and for 1985 and 1986 corn and sorghum under price support loan, he said. no extensions will be allowed for 1983 and older corn and sorghum loans
lyng said the announcement on 1985 and 1986 corn and sorghum loans reversed a previous decision announced on jan. 29
the change was made ``to alleviate grain movement problems due to a rail car shortage, grain congestion at some country elevators'' and other logistical problems, he said
but the agriculture department will reserve the right to ``call at any time'' the 1985 and 1986 crop loans, lyng said. grain in the farmer-owned reserve program can remain until prices rise enough to trigger its release
the loans are extended to farmers by the department's commodity credit corp., which uses the grain as collateral. if prices rise significantly, farmers usually repay the loans and sell or use the grain as they choose
but farmers have the option of not repaying the loans, in which case ccc takes over the grain when the loans mature, or come due. by extending the loans, farmers continue to own the grain and retain their ccc options
parts of the jan. 29 order still stand, including the decision not to extend loans on 1987-crop wheat, feed grains and soybeans. also, loans that already had been extended on 1985 and 1986 wheat, feed grains and soybeans will not be extended further when those mature
more than 80 percent of americans favor a federal program to provide long-term home care for the chronically ill and disabled, according to a poll released tuesday
the survey by louis harris &amp; associates also found that more than 70 percent would support paying for the program by increasing medicare payroll taxes for people who make more than $45,000 a year
rep. claude pepper, d-fla., released the survey in conjunction with a hearing on his five-year, $25 billion proposal for long-term home care. house leaders have promised him a floor vote on the bill although it has not gone through the usual committee scrutiny
many members have criticized the plan as too expensive to pass this year. rep. dan rostenkowski, d-ill., chairman of the tax-writing house ways and means committee, has said congress cannot enact both pepper's plan and another medicare expansion shielding the elderly and disabled against catastrophic health-care costs
catastrophic-cost bills already have passed both houses and negotiators are working out differences between the two versions
rep. edward roybal, d-calif., chairman of the house select committee on aging and a co-sponsor of pepper's bill, said virtually no medicare or insurance coverage is available to millions of people with a chronic illness
we have long believed we were seeing a rising tide of public support for a federal long-term care program, and the harris poll shows us americans are evne more enthusiastic than we imagined,'' roybal said in a statement
the harris survey found that americans of all ages, professions, party affiliations and income levels supported financing a new home-care program through an increase in the 1.45 percent medicare payroll tax on upper-income workers
more than 70 percent of people earning above $50,000 supported that method of financing although they would bear the brunt of it, the survey found
of those questioned, 82 percent said they could not afford to pay for the costs of providing long-term care either at home or in a nursing home _ including more than 60 percent of those making above $50,000 a year
and nearly 80 percent of those polled said they would prefer long-term home care to care in a nursing home
the harris survey questioned 1,500 adults across the country in telephone interviews feb. 18-23. the margin of error is plus or minus three percentage points
the survey echoes an earlier poll last fall that found americans by an overwhelming majority were willing to pay higher taxes to finance long-term care for the elderly
sixty-eight percent of those questioned in the survey by r.l. associates were willing to shoulder $10 to $60 a month more in taxes to pay for the program
that survey was commissioned by long-term care '88, a coalition of senior citizens groups and other organizations hoping to make the issue a top priority with presidential candidates
on a related matter, a government report released tuesday said the number of elderly americans confined to nursing homes is remaining stable even though the raw numbers are rising because of an aging population
there were 1.3 million nursing home residents at least 65 years of age in 1985, up 200,000 from 1977, when the last nursing home figures were collected
the report by the department of health and human services said the 1985 nursing home population reflected about 1 percent of americans 65-74 years old being confined to institutions and about 22 percent of those 85 years and older. both percentages were essentially unchanged from the 1977 survey
a court tuesday freed the leader of an opposition street theater group serving a two-month jail sentence, but 18 of his supporters were detained by police outside the courtroom, activists said
waldemar ``the major'' fydrych, 34, who heads the group orange alternative, was arrested march 8 as he handed out flowers and sanitary napkins to women to mock official observances of international women's day
leading cultural figures, including film director andrzej wajda, had appealed for the release of the writer, who became widely known for organizing various orange alternative ``happenings'' in which demonstrators dressed up as santa claus, secret policemen and lenten penitents to poke fun at communist authorities
the appeals court in wroclaw acquitted fydrych of causing public unrest after finding that testimony by prosecution witnesses was inconsistent with that given by the sole witness at fydrych's march 9 misdemeanor hearing, said spokesman krzysztof albin
fydrych was released after the hearing, which his supporters were barred from attending, said barbara labuda, another opposition activist in the southwestern polish city
police detained three orange alternative supporters who were carrying models of a major's uniform hanging from a gallows in a morning demonstration outside the courthouse, albin said
at least 15 more supporters, most of them wearing orange-colored apparel, were detained by police while they waited for the verdict in a corridor outside the courtroom, albin said
albin said one orange alternative member, grzegorz francuz, was beaten on the way to the police station
opposition activists in poland are frequently detained for up to 48 hours on misdemeanor charges
rep. james howard, d-n.j., who died last week after suffering a heart attack, was eulogized today as a productive congressman whose contributions can be seen throughout the country
he worked hard and he played hard and he laughed full-tilt,'' said house speaker jim wright, d-texas, who spoke during a roman catholic funeral mass for howard
his candle burned brightly for 60 years and others came and lighted their candles from him,'' said wright
more than 850 people, including four busloads of congressmen and their aides, attended the service at st. catharine's church here
aides to howard restricted access to the church because it could hold about 400 people, and a crowd of about 450 watched from the street as the casket was brought into the church. loudspeakers broadcast the service to those gathered outside
howard, 60, died friday, a day after suffering a heart attack while playing golf in a washington suburb
he represented the state's 3rd congressional district and served in the house for 22 years. he was the second-most senior member of new jersey's congressman behind rep. peter rodino, also a democrat
acting as pallbearers at today's funeral were sen. bill bradley and rep. robert a. roe, both d-n.j., rep. john paul hammerschmidt, r-ark., state sen. frank pallone, d-monmouth, and monmouth county freeholders john villapiano and john d'amico
rep. morris k. udall, d-ariz., also spoke during the service
jim was one of the best, most productive congressmen, most beloved congressmen,'' said udall, who attributed howard's success to his honesty and his enthusiasm
i never saw anyone with a more infectious manner come to the house floor. he was everywhere at once,'' said udall
as chairman of the house public works and transportation committee, howard largely controlled highway and transportation projects nationwide
the handy work and fruits of jim's labor'' can be seen in monmouth county as well as across the nation, wright said
in washington on monday, the house and senate voted unanimously to name the new jersey segment of interstate 195 after howard
howard's staff says it will continue to provide service to constituents, although the district will not have a vote in the house until a successor is elected
gov. thomas h. kean must call a special election to replace howard and has said he will consider holding it nov. 8 as part of the general election
third district voters would be asked to pick someone to finish the final two months of howard's term, and cast a second vote to choose a congressman for a full term beginning in january 1989
officials at a city zoo killed and ate a popular bear cub because they didn't have room for it in the park, a newspaper reported tuesday
the cub, named molly, was 2 years old and was one of visitors' favorites at the skansen park zoo when the lack of space last november forced the zoo to cull the cubs, according to the newspaper, expressen
the bear was served to the zoo's staff
molly was so nice, i didn't take a bite,'' caretaker tina reinhed told the newspaper
because of crowded conditons, the cubs are kept for 18 months before they are either sold or killed, she said
first we naturally try to sell them to other zoological parks,'' reinhed said. ``sadly enough, they also have an excess (of bears).''
zoo superintendent pelle palm said that while people don't like to see ``teddy bears'' eaten, ``it's worse to destroy meat in a world that hungers.''
the withdrawal of u.s. troops from honduras will be completed on thursday, the pentagon said tuesday
spokesman dan howard said the roughly 3,100 soldiers dispatched to honduras on march 17-18 were being removed along with their equipment on a four-day schedule. the first group was airlifted out monday
the soldiers were dispatched as a warning to the leftist nicaraguan government after sandinista troops moved into honduras in pursuit of u.s.-backed contra rebels. the american troops never were sent to the border area where the fighting occurred, but rather staged military exercises with honduran military units
according to the pentagon, the last contingent of men from the 7th light infantry division will return to fort ord, calif., around 2 p.m. est on wednesday. the last unit from the 82nd airborne will return to fort bragg, n.c., around 9 a.m. est on thursday
about 2,000 of the troops were scheduled to depart honduras on tuesday, the pentagon added
the government fired 33 police officers for drug trafficking, armed robbery, accepting bribes and other crimes as part of a corruption crackdown, authorities said tuesday
six officers were dismissed for stealing diamonds in the mining town of akwatia near accra, police said. ten others had smuggled marijuana to neighboring ivory coast by boat
among the fired officers was a deputy police superintendent, but there were no details on where he had been posted
the announcement by the national police council, headed by ghanaian leader flight lt. jerry rawlings, did not say if the officers had been arrested
two weeks ago, 19 officers were fired for armed robbery and drug trafficking in the crackdown aimed at reducing corruption and improving police efficiency and credibility
a gang of 10-year-olds who began stealing golf balls two months ago have graduated to terrorizing members of boca raton's executive country club with knives, officials say
they've also allegedly dug up the fourth green
the women golfers are frightened. the men are angry,'' mary k. werre, manager of the country club, said monday after calling police
they're kids who should know better, but they're very, very nasty,'' said ed lombardi, 77, of deerfield beach
country club members describe the children as clean-cut, well-dressed and about 10 years old
lombardi was playing golf last sunday when some children stole a friend's ball
out on the golf course, we don't want nor expect anything like that,'' he said. ``i chased them into the woods, but they have paths. they can go like deer in there.''
two foursomes, who played saturday, told ms. werre that children had sprung from the trees, swiped golf balls and, brandishing knives, challenged the golfers to ``come and get them.''
a gang of about five 10-year-olds equipped with shovels dug up the fourth green,'' boca raton officer william ehrhardt wrote in his report. ``in addition, the youths were in possession of knives, intimidated golfers and stole their balls.''
country club officials were reluctant at first to report the juveniles' high jinks
whenever we saw them out there we got in our golf cart and went after them, but they ran and we haven't been able to catch them,'' ms. werre said
that was before the children added knives to their arsenal. now, ms. werre said, she will call police whenever the children are spotted
ted wright of lake worth was playing last sunday when he saw some children playing with remote-controlled cars in the sand trap
i told them to get off, we were playing,'' he said
as wright went for one of the cars, the youthful owner said they were leaving, then cursed him
about two weeks ago, the children appeared at night wearing camouflage fatigues, ms. werre said. with their faces blackened, they crept onto the driving range and lifted some golf balls before a worker saw them and shooed them away, she said
country club officials can't figure out a motive
if they're stealing range balls, they really can't do well by selling them anywhere,'' ms. werre said. ``if they're stealing from off the course, you'd think they'd be selling them here, but that hasn't happened.''
common sense and firefighting basics have won a navy achievement medal for an 18-year-old marine
pfc. neil r. wadley won the medal for his idea that could make troops invisible to enemy heat-detecting devices. the award was presented to wadley by gen. a.m. gray, commandant of the marine corps
wadley, of st. maries, idaho, who is stationed at the quantico base, suggested that combatants wear a special lightweight shield that would neutralize the enemy's sensors
he said he got the idea from his work fighting forest fires with the department of lands in idaho before he became a marine. everyone was issued a ``fire shelter,'' a five-pound sheet of material capable of reflecting severe temperatures, he said
wadley said he wasn't prepared for what happened after he wrote a letter to the marine corps gazette, outlining his idea for the poncho-type shield
the editor of the gazette forwarded a copy of the letter to gen. gray, and gray immediately wrote wadley a personal letter:
'' ... i'm really excited by your idea, and am taking the liberty of initiating immediate measures to ensure that its possibilities are thoroughly explored. i ... commend your creative intellect for perceiving an innovative approach to a tough problem. your idea certainly merits further research and development...''
wadley said modestly, ''i don't think i really deserved the medal. it would have been enough just to get the letter and to meet the commandant.''
a criminal court acquitted former foreign minister bernard blamo of conspiring to defraud the government of $575,000 in the purchase of a fire truck and navigational instruments
when the 12-man jury returned its unanimous verdict, there was singing and shouting in the courtroom from blamo supporters and family members. blamo's wife was carried out after she fainted
the government had charged blamo, a former head of the national port authority, of aiding and abetting benny ashun, a ghanaian, in the fraud scheme
blamo said he did not know ashun was defrauding the government
unlikely green thumbs are sprouting at an inner-city housing project where a vegetable garden is fast becoming a model of determination and hope in a depressed area
it all started last november when a team of 38 residents of the nickerson gardens housing project decided to turn an ugly, vacant lot into a haven of leafy foliage and vegetables
the garden in the city's south-central area already has produced enough carrots, onions, tomatoes, broccoli, cabbage and cauliflower to supply residents and just about anyone else who cares to sample the home-grown food
word has spread to transients and gang members alike that the food is available for the taking, just as long as takers ask first
it took awhile for it to sink in, but all the kids and the gang members are letting the garden be,'' said gardener tauheedah karim, 32
it shows you that if you believe in something and you work at it, it can be done,'' said wilma jean powns, 46, co-captain of the gardeners, as she stood among her sprouting cabbages in one of the garden's 20 boxed plots
ms. powns and her neighbors got help from the end world hunger organization and budget rent-a-car, which have sponsored urban gardens in other cities. the groups supplied seeds, training and some supplies, while agriculture advisers from the university of california trucked in rich soil and fertilizer
this comes from love. long as we keep at it, this garden's going to be here a long, long time,'' ms. powns said
neighbors keep a watch from their homes and shoo away trespassers
even local school kids are getting into the act. a class from the housing project's head start program shows up several times a week to help the gardeners water, taking turns using a faucet to fill plastic jugs
the jugs are doing double duty, said ms. powns. when dogs began rooting through the plants last winter, she said she put to use an old trick that her grandmother taught her about vegetable gardening. she filled the jugs with water and ammonia and left them out for the scavengers
we had a few dogs running around sneezing like crazy,`` she said with a laugh. ``dogs ain't a problem anymore.''
when american and japanese children got together tuesday to compare prize-winning inventions, one side brought most of the frivolous, fanciful toys while the other displayed no-nonsense solutions to everyday problems
but in a reversal of stereotypes, it was the japanese kids who brought the marionette and robot on skis, and the americans who produced door guards, portable seat belts and diapers with built-in disposable bags
the meeting was arranged by a program to spur creativity among american students called ``invent america!'' and the japan institution of invention and innovation, which has sponsored competitions for japanese schoolchildren since 1941
the japanese students' inventions included the mechanized marionette of takakiyo katami, 11, of gufu city; a robot that can slalom back and forth on skis by yasushi nishiyama, 15, of nagoya; and an illuminated constellation model made from 2,000 optical fibers by takahiro tsurita, 14, of toyota city
tomoyuki imura, 15, of miki city, japan, came up with a ball retriever that consists of several tennis cans open at both ends and taped together
sally mallison, 12, of wilmington, del., who devised her ``bag-a-diap'' to help her parents cope with messy diapers on car trips, said, ``i think from the japanese i've learned that inventions can be mechanical and they can also be ... like mine where they don't have anything mechanical to do with them.''
yasushi nishiyama, maker of the slalom robot, said through an interpreter, ``after observing all these inventions i notice japanese students' inventions seem to be more like toys, something kids can play with.''
most of the americans' inventions, he added, seemed ``more practical, something in your daily life that you can actually use.''
how does that square with the image americans have of japanese students spending endless hours in school or studying?
there are some people who study hard, but there are some who just enjoy playing,'' nishiyama said. ``they stay away from that work. instead, they try to create something more interesting so they can enjoy themselves.''
two of the young japanese inventors' devices did have a practical tilt. hiroshi aoyagi, 12, of tokamachi, built a door that can slide up or swing out
and yoshitaka tanimoto, 13, of takayama city, won top honors, the prime minister's prize, for inventing a device to help his grandfather regain use of his hand after a stroke. tanimoto's hand rehabilitation machine consists of two crescent shaped handles attached by strong rubber bands that can be stretched apart
the americans, all honored last june in an invent america competition, included maurice scales, 8, of suitland, md., who came up with a plexiglas shield to keep doors from slamming on his sister's fingers; the portable seat belt for school buses by michelle cardin, 10, of fairfield, conn.; an artificial reef to help young fish by brian lloyd, 15, of jacksonville, fla.; and a scheme for solar energy from space by sachin patel, 7, of flatonia, texas
the u.s. patent model foundation launched invent america in december 1986 with corporate financing and moral support from the reagan administration. it expects 8 million students in 35,000 u.s. elementary schools to take part in this year's competition
kazuhiko hoshino, president of the japan institute of invention and innovation, said the visit will help the japanese youths ``develop new ideas and high creativity.''
in order to cope with the current trend toward internationalization, we consider it important for japanese school students to visit overseas at every opportunity,'' he said. to update with more testimony from l'ecuyer.</note>
a witness for gov. evan mecham today told senators considering whether to remove the governor from office that a fund mecham is accused of misuing was not public money nor controlled by state law
political consultant and lawyer robert l'ecuyer testified that mecham's inaugural committee chairman lacked the authority to bind the governor to restrictions on how the money could be used
mecham, a first-term republican, is being tried by the arizona senate on three impeachment counts, including alleged misuse of $80,000 from a protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
the defense has contended the fund, created with proceeds from inaugural activities, was not public money, while the prosecution contends it was
l'ecuyer testified today that because the protocol fund was not public money in his opinion, mecham was not restricted by state laws that govern the use of public funds
he said he thought the loan was ``legal but stupid.''
inaugural committee chairman william long had told the maricopa county attorney's office in a 1987 letter that the fund would be used to either benefit the state or to promote citizen participation in state activities
the june 26 letter from william long to the county attorney was of absolutely no force or effect in relation to the mecham inaugural committee funds'' because the fund already had been turned over to mecham, and long no longer chaired the inaugural committee, l'ecuyer said
l'ecuyer also described a meeting in may 1987 in which he agreed, despite misgivings, to advise the governor on mecham's plans to publish a tabloid touting his administration
the governor and i started off with a shouting match,'' l'ecuyer said. ``the two of us yelled at each other for the better part of the hour,'' he said, adding that if the tabloid was used as a campaign tool to attack lawmakers, ``that could become a violation; people could go to jail for that kind of a violation.'' he did not elaborate
the governor cooperated with l'ecuyer on campaign finance matters after that meeting, the consultant said
l'ecuyer was hired by mecham last fall to provide legal opinions on the propriety of the governor's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan. the consultant said last fall that mecham properly reported the loan by lumping it in with other amounts
mecham faces a charge of concealing the $350,000 loan in both the impeachment trial and criminal court. the senate already has heard testimony on another charge that he tried to thwart an investigation on an alleged death threat
on monday, senators indicated they were taking a dim view of mecham's proposal that they vote now on two of the impeachment articles, concerning the death threat and the protocol fund, against him and promise to drop the third regarding the campaign loan
the chances of that happening are ``about as good of me jumping off the top of the highest building i can find in the neighborhood,'' said senate majority leader bob usdane, who like mecham is a republican
also monday, the governor's lawyer, jerris leonard, said monday that mecham has ``a firm agreement'' to sell the land and buildings of his mecham pontiac dealership for about $4 million
leonard said he did not know who the prospective buyer was, when the deal would be closed, or whether mecham was keeping his pontiac franchise
during his own testimony monday on the protocol fund, mecham angrily disrupted the proceedings after house prosecutor william french compared his actions to embezzlement
i have to make a statement,'' mecham declared, ignoring orders from arizona supreme court justice frank gordon to refrain from comments beyond answering questions asked
i resent so highly the word embezzlement in my presence,'' mecham said. ``i'm insulted by it.''
gordon admonished mecham again, telling him: ``i hope you believe the rules are for you, sir, as well as everybody else.''
mecham responded hotly: ``i have seen no witness who has been insulted as i have been.''
in his testimony monday, the governor suggested that the senate drop the third charge and vote right away on the first two counts
if you want to say we'll call this game at the end of six innings, and do it (vote) then with the fact that that is the game, why, i don't suppose we could argue with you on that one,'' mecham said
however, senate minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, agreed with usdane that it would be ``ridiculous'' to expect the senate to drop the $350,000 loan allegation
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate on any one of the counts is required to convict the governor, automatically removing him from office. a similar two-thirds vote would be needed to change the rules to allow an early vote on the first two impeachment counts
mecham, who also faces a may 17 recall election, is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades
the seventh national conference on humor is no joke
to tell you the truth, it may be excruciatingly boring,'' victor raskin, a purdue university english professor coordinating the weekend conference, said tuesday
there will be one lecture on the peanuts cartoon. i have no idea how that will turn out,'' said shaun f.d. hughes, an associate professor of english who is helping raskin coordinate the conference. ``there will be one on the theory of humor. that tends to be more deadly.''
the theme is midwestern humor. ``there will be some papers on mark twain,'' said hughes. ``there will be one from northwestern university on chicago political humor.''
hughes will ``present a deadly paper. it's called `physician, humor thyself.' it's icelandic medical humor. icelandic people, they say, have no sense of humor and this tends to bear that out,'' he said
raskin said in a recent university statement: ``in the last decade, humor has been increasingly recognized as an essential and universal human facility and as such, has become the subject of high-powered and widely interdisciplinary research.''
the conference, at purdue's west lafayette campus, will be about 80 percent academic, says raskin. the last six such conferences were held at arizona state university _ always on april fool's day
during the breaks, there may be a lot of laughter,'' said raskin. ``then on sunday night, there is a public joke-telling contest. they can tell jokes, juggle, anything to elicit laughter. the winner gets a purse of maybe $60 or something.''
but the point, or punchline, is quite serious
psychologists want to know why we appreciate humor,'' says raskin. ``sociologists are interested in humor's role in society. anthropologists want to know why what is funny to one society is not funny to another.''
luckily, some parts of it will be funny,'' says hughes. ``sometimes they insert jokes into the lecture.''
michigan welfare clients may get free condoms from their pharmacists in a new program to provide birth control and help stem the spread of aids
ohio, wisconsin, illinois, new york and pennsylvania already provide condoms for medicaid recipients by prescription. for accounting purposes, some state rules require prescriptions for many items given medicaid recipients by pharmacists
but michigan apparently will be the first state to provide the condoms without prescriptions, state and federal officials say
the state department of social services is notifying medicaid recipients and pharmacists about the program, scheduled to begin june 1, chuck peller, a spokesman for dds, said monday
the condoms can be obtained by men or women presenting a medicaid card to a pharmacist, peller said
there is no specific budget for the program, the state has not estimated its cost and the dss has ``no idea of the anticipated usage,'' peller said
the latest state budget bill included the requirement for free condoms to medicaid recipients, peller said
richard chambers, a spokesman for the u.s. department of health and human services, said from washington that he knows of no other state that authorizes free distribution of condoms without a prescription
the federal government reimburses states for 90 percent of the costs of family planning services, chambers said
to guard against fraud, including what peller called ``the `black market' possibility,''' a recipient's medicaid number will be recorded each time condoms are picked up. the state will check those numbers periodically, he said
if the dss determines a recipient has obtained an unusual number of condoms, that person will be referred to the agency's recipient monitoring project in which a prescription would be needed for more condoms, peller said
the house republicans' conference in houston last weekend was supposed to be a retreat, but lawmakers joked that it was more like an advance
they led an invading army that included 42 u.s. capitol police officers, police dogs, the house physician, the house clerk, office assistants, reporters, camera crews and the staff of the national republican congressional committee, which helps run their campaigns. many brought their families
they traveled with a legion of lobbyists, many of whom helped finance the three chartered jetliners, lawmakers' hotel rooms and banquets paid for under the auspices of the congressional institute inc., a tax-exempt corporation set up for these occasions
sam richardson, a spokesman for the conference, said the total cost had not yet been calculated. he said one of the banquets _ canceled later because of a bomb threat _ cost $12,000. reporters each were charged $413 for travel and meals, with hotel bills extra
one of the goals of the three-day conference was for the 70 lawmakers attending to let their hair down. but the program listed suit-and-tie or women's business attire for three straight days, even at a tex-mex dinner
they're going to think we're all a bunch of stuffed shirts,'' complained one member, who got no argument from his wife nearby
while in houston, the republicans sought some high-tech themes for their national agenda. they sought camaraderie. they sought a strategy in their marathon battle to take control of the house back from the democrats for the first time in 34 years
the thing they surely found, which isn't in evidence much in washington, was some humor
during the three-day meeting, the gop squad traveled back and forth across the city in bus motorcades. along the way, police blocked side streets and freeway ramps while frustrated local motorists didn't know whom to blame
there is only one thing to do at a time like this,'' one of the gop lawmakers said, staring at a line of blocked traffic
put a big sign on the bus that says `mickey leland re-election committee, jim wright, chairman,''' he said, referring to the local democratic congressman and the house speaker
the house republicans didn't use police escorts at their last get-together a year ago in new york
they had asked the nypd how long it would take to get from their mid-town hotel to federal hall for their meetings
thirty-five minutes,'' was the answer. and if they used an escort?
forty minutes,'' came the reply
at the houston hotel, a lobbyist from one of the regional phone companies was handing out complimentary pens. ``remember, if it breaks, we only fix the outside. you have to go to at&amp;t for the inside,'' he warned
the conference was held in a lovely four seasons hotel. but houston's already summer-sticky weather prompted a reporter to dub it the ``one season.''
perhaps the highlight of the trip was a spectacular laser and fireworks show at the johnson space center
the climax came when the doors of a huge hangar opened up and the spectators wandered into a misty night sliced and diced by lasers stretching across the horizon
i thought a big clamshell was going to open up and we'd walk in and fly away,'' one lawmaker quipped about the eerie scene
another seemed concerned that the laser beams were hitting the nearby hilton hotel
i just can't help but thinking,'' he said, ``that there's some poor salesman up in one of those rooms thinking about fooling around on his wife. and then he's zapped by a green light beam!
he'll never try that again,'' the congressman predicted
by the end of three days, the lawmakers were eager to return to washington, and to finish this year's business early so that they can hit the re-election campaign trail
we have to go home and tell our constituents this mess isn't our fault,'' one explained. comments; picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng, `leaders of.'</note>
house negotiators working on aid for the nicaraguan rebels tried today to resolve a dispute over whether president reagan should be able to command quick congressional action on any military aid request
we still have significant debate over how a future request from the president for military aid would be treated,'' rep. dick cheney of wyoming, chairman of the house republican conference, said after gop congressional leaders met with the president
cheney said one possibility discussed was that instead of spelling out the procedures in the bill, the house would rely on a promise by speaker jim wright, d-texas, that there will be a speedy vote on such a request
i think if the speaker would give his word, we would find that acceptable,'' he said. ``if we can work out an arrangement whereby the speaker would commit in advance to give us timely consideration for the vote and he would bring it up under a fair rule, i think that would solve the problem.''
rep. trent lott, the house republican whip, said, ``we would be willing to take the speaker's word, but we are going to have to have a clear understanding of what that word means.''
when asked whether such a ``gentlemen's agreement'' could be sold to house republicans, lott said, ``it would be very difficult, because while they (the democrats) say they are suspicious of the president's request for ... expedited procedures, we don't trust them either.''
he said, however, that he believed house republicans would support such an agreement if it were worked out between wright and house gop leader robert michel of illinois. wright and michel were in new jersey today, attending the funeral of democratic rep. james howard
lott said reagan ``didn't sign on'' to the idea of such an agreement but ``i know the president has a lot of faith'' in michel, cheney and rep. mickey edwards, r-okla., the principal negotiators
if they can get something that they can accept and work with, i am sure that will carry a lot of weight with the president,'' lott said
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the dollar amounts of aid mentioned in the negotiations, ranging from $30 million to less than $50million, were acceptable to reagan
the issue is not money but how fast we can get it'' to help assure the survival of the nicaraguan contra rebels as a fighting force, fitzwater said. ``we want it as fast as we can get it,'' he said
he added that the issue of an acceptable means of delivering aid to the contras is ``still an open question'' to be worked out by the negotiators, subject to proposals for cease-fire zones in nicaragua
leaders of the chamber worked for five hours monday on the package, and roughed out a six-month, $40 million aid bill that would send strictly ``humanitarian'' aid _ food, clothing, medicine and shelter _ while the rebels negotiate a permanent peace with the country's leftist sandinista government
we reached some general understandings in a number of areas, but there were some stumbling points,'' said house democratic whip tony coelho of california, who added that meetings would resume today
coelho held out hope that an agreement still could be forged in time to bring the matter to the house floor on wednesday and permit the senate time to act and get the aid flowing before easter. he cited reports that the rebels may exhaust their basic supplies within a week or two
the $40 million would keep supplies flowing to the rebels as they wait out the continuing negotiations in cease-fire zones inside nicaragua. the aid would flow at a rate comparable to that provided before feb. 29, when the last u.s. support ran out. the package also would include $10 million to pay the expenses of a commission to verify compliance with the peace accord
for this (peace) effort to work, there's got to be this aid,'' said adolfo calero, a leader of the rebel political directorate, who met with wright and other congressional leaders on the aid package
any new aid for the contras would have to conform to the requirements of a 60-day truce reached last week between the rebels and the managua government
that agreement said the contras would receive only humanitarian aid and that the aid would be routed through ``neutral organizations.'' the cia has delivered past u.s. aid supplies to the contras
calero said he told wright and house minority leader robert michel, r-ill., that the term ``neutral organizations'' meant a commercial transport company acceptable to the rebels, and not a relief organization such as the red cross, which wright had previously mentioned as the delivery agent
other details of the package remained to be determined, such as whether it would include communications gear for the rebels or special programs such as a $14 million effort to help children who are victims of the nearly 7-year-old civil war, which has claimed some 40,000 lives
republicans wary of sandinista promises have sought to give reagan the right to a quick, guaranteed vote in congress on a later request for new military aid to the contras if the peace process breaks down. as expected, that was proving to be the most difficult issue
wright and michel were seeking a compromise that would indicate continued u.s. backing for the rebels during the cease-fire, but would give congress the final say on the nature of any future aid package
after meeting monday with the contra leadership, secretary of state george p. shultz told reporters it would ``certainly be desirable'' to have assurances of quick action on additional aid to the contras if the peace talks break down, and calero agreed
in last wek's agreement, the sandinistas promised a general amnesty for the rebels, which began with the release sunday of 100 prisoners. they also committed themselves to a restoration of the rights of free speech and political participation, in return for the 60-day cease-fire and the relocation of contra forces into special zones
representatives of the two sides are meeting this week to work out the details of a long-term cease-fire, including when the rebels will lay down their weapons. 6th graf pvs, gephardt 47</note>
rep. richard gephardt took an aggressive tack in his democratic presidential bid, but he bowed out of the race in a mellower mood with family and friends at his side. he filed for re-election to his house seat today, declaring himself happy
i have no complaints today;. i'm the luckiest guy in the world,'' gephardt said monday after announcing his withdrawal at an upbeat news conference that contrasted with the grim economic tidings he purveyed in his campaign
we did the best we possibly could,'' he said. ``we made our mistakes and we lost.''
in jefferson city, mo., today, the missouri congressman filed for re-election to the 3rd congressional district seat from st. louis, a seat he has held since 1976
i am very happy to be here. it's a good thing i didn't wait another day,'' gephardt quipped, referring to the fact that today was the filing deadline
gephardt was accompanied by his wife and mother
on monday, he said he intended to be back in the thick of house business on wednesday and, in a variation on his campaign message to the economically disadvantaged, pledged that ``your fight will always be my fight, too.''
gephardt, 47, ran some of the most negative tv ads of the campaign against massachusetts gov. michael dukakis. but he was pushing party unity on monday
i think our candidate is going to come from the people that are running now for the presidency and i think we're going to put a democrat in the white house in 1988,'' said gephardt, who is chairman of the house democratic caucus
he declined when asked to give advice to dukakis, noting the governor's delegate lead and ruefully admitting that ``michael dukakis has sure done a lot better than i did. i don't think it's my place to tell him what to do.''
as for jesse jackson, who trounced both gephardt and dukakis last saturday in the michigan caucuses, gephardt commented: ``i think jesse jackson can be nominated and i think he can be elected.''
gephardt refused to endorse anyone in the race but said he might do so later. asked about the prospects of him running again in the future, gephardt said he expected a democrat to be elected this fall and re-elected in 1992. ``nineteen-ninety-six is so far off i can't even see it,'' he said
most of gephrdt's 167 delegates went into the uncommitted column, but missouri state party rules mandate that the at-large and public official delegates are re-divided among the active candidates when a contender drops out
according to the latest ap delegate count, jackson had 606.55, dukakis 605.55, sen. albert gore jr. 362.8, sen. paul simon 168.5 and uncommitted 515.6
gephardt began campaigning in iowa, the leadoff caucus state, some two years ago on the theory that an iowa victory would translate into momentum and his campaign would take off. he did win iowa, as well as south dakota and his home state, but his candidacy never developed broad appeal
looking back, gephardt attributed the failure to a lack of resources and said that where he was able to get his ideas across, ``we did connect.'' but he added, ``i have no alibis. we lost, no question about that.''
he said he did not blame his defeats on either his position as a house member, a difficult jumping-off place, or press coverage that some considered unduly negative
by and large, the press has been fair to dick gephardt. i didn't like every article that was written, but i'm not supposed to,'' he said
gephardt was a pragmatic consensus builder in the house and many news stories focused on his transition to anti-establishment populist with controversial ideas on trade and farms
gephardt was an insider trying to run as an outsider and he got creamed for it,'' said robert lichter, a media analyst logging all election stories on the three networks' evening news shows this year
gephardt was also vulnerable because he had switched positions on issues ranging from abortion to reaganomics over the years
the well-heeled dukakis ran a television ad showing a man flip-flopping through the air and another with a list of gephardt's corporate contributors. sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee not only attacked gephardt on his changes of heart, but appropriated the same populist theme
after michigan, gehpardt had less than one-third the delegate totals amassed by dukakis and jackson and fewer than even sen. paul simon of illinois, who didn't compete in the 20 contests on super tuesday, march 8. congressional and white house comments; picks up 8th graf pvs, bgng., `burns resignation.' deletes now redundant grafs 16-17.</note>
the no. 2 official in the justice department and the head of the department's criminal division abruptly resigned today amid continuing legal problems for their boss, attorney general edwin meese iii
deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william weld announced in letters to president reagan that they were stepping down, with weld's resignation effective at the close of business today
the first meese knew of their plans was when burns and weld walked into the attorney general's office at 8 a.m. and announced they were stepping aside, said a department source, speaking on condition of anonymity. the news was announced to department officials at the morning staff meeting a half hour later. both have served since oct. 17, 1986
two assistants to burns _ randy levine and boykin rose _ and two assistants to weld _ mark robinson and jane serene _ also resigned
the officials provided no explanation for their sudden actions, but the source said meese's continuing legal problems were ``definitely a factor'' in the resignations
meese has been under criminal investigation for nearly a year
neither burns nor weld mentioned meese's legal problems in their resignation letters
questioned about the resignations, sen. strom thurmond, ranking republican on the senate judiciary committee, said, ``i am greatly concerned about morale at the department of justice as indicated by the resignation of these two men and of four additional officials who i am informed have also resigned.''
sen. dennis deconcini, d-ariz., said he was ``surprised to see them leaving at this period of time'' and added, ``it certainly doesn't signify a great deal of confidence in the attorney general.'' but the senator said he did not know why the officials quit
assistant republican floor leader alan k. simpson, r-wyo., who also serves on the senate judiciary committee, said, ``if you believe in fairness, you have to wait and see'' what caused the resignations
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said white house officials were informed of the resignations on monday. he said reagan accepted them ``with regret'' this morning and thanked burns and weld for serving ``with distinction.''
fitzwater said he didn't believe the two departing officials spoke directly to reagan, and he said he was only aware of the reasons they gave in their resignation letters. the spokesman said reagan continues to have ``full confidence'' in meese and the justice department
fitzwater said the resignations did not cause any particular concern among reagan and his advisers. ``we have people resigning all the time, especially late in the administration,'' he said
burns' resignation is effective april 22. weld's temporary replacement will be john keeney, a deputy in the criminal division
the resignations, combined with the departure of associate attorney general stephen s. trott to become a federal judge, leave a leadership vacuum of major proportions in the justice department
burns' letter to reagan said that ``under your leadership, i believe we have made important contributions to the administration of justice. ... unfortunately, i have regretfully concluded that i must return to private life at this time.''
weld, a former u.s. attorney in boston who has prosecuted a number of important public corruption and white-collar crime cases, told reagan that ``i am grateful to have been charged with the responsibility of seeing that justice be done without fear or favor.''
another department source, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said that neither burns nor weld acted in the belief that meese is about to be indicted
however, said the source, both men are concerned because the justice department's image continues to be damaged due to the ongoing criminal investigation of meese, the nation's top law enforcement officer
terry eastland, a justice department spokesman, pointed out that it is not unusual for political appointees to leave government in the last year of an administration
eastland said that burns, weld and trott, who was confirmed as a judge last week, were sworn into their jobs in 1986 and that ``this is 1988; this happens to be a year when people are leaving and they all happen to be leaving at the same time.''
meese has been under investigation for 11 months. independent counsel james mckay launched the probe last may 11 to look into meese's involvement with the scandal-plagued wedtech corp. the investigation has expanded to include his involvement in a $1 billion iraqi pipeline project
meese got involved in both wedtech and the pipeline through his longtime friend, e. robert wallach
this morning, former national security adviser william clark was testifying before a federal grand jury in connection with the pipeline project. mckay's office is presenting evidence to the grand jury
mckay's probe is in its final phase, say sources familiar with the investigation, but it could continue for at least another month or two
american ambassadors to east asian and pacific nations will meet in hong kong on april 8-10 for an annual discussion of policy and administrative affairs, the state department announced tuesday
gaston sigur, the assistant secretary for east asian and pacific affairs, will chair the session. beforehand he will travel to seoul on april 2-5 and tokyo on april 5-7 for discussions with korean and japanese officials
sigur will meet soviet vice foreign minister igor rogachev in paris on april 25-26. it will be the fourth u.s.-soviet meeting on asian problems, notably the continuing vietnamese occupation of cambodia, since 1985 when president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev agreed to periodic conferences on troubled regions. update with white house comment.</note>
the government's chief economic forecasting gauge climbed 0.9 percent in february, a sharp rebound following several months of weakness after the october stock market collapse, the commerce department reported today
the gain in the index of leading economic indicators was the biggest increase since last june. it followed declines of 1.1 percent in january, 0.1 percent in october and 1.2 percent in november
only a 0.4 percent rise in december kept the index from posting consecutive declines for three or more months, the traditional signal of an impending recession
but with the big february increase, analysts said they believe the leading index is accurately signaling that the economy slowed in the early part of 1988 but the country will avoid a recession this year
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the index ``shows that the economy is very promising.''
the size and broad-based nature of last month's index of leading indicators are encouraging,'' fitzwater said
the 0.9 percent february increase was led by a big jump in applications for building permits, which provided over half of the strength last month
in all, five of the available nine indicators were positive forces on the index. after building permits, the biggest contributors were a drop in new unemployment claims, a rise in stock prices, an increase in the growth of the money supply and higher orders for consumer goods
four of the indicators held the index back. the biggest negative factor was a decline in the length of the average manufacturing workweek, followed by a decline in orders for plant and equipment, a change in raw materials prices and a speed-up in business delivery times, considered a negative because it is often a sign of dropping demand
the various changes left the index at 190.6 percent of its 1967 base of 100
the jump in the february index was one of a string of recent reports showing better-than-expected strength in the early part of 1988
many economists believe the strong reports have all but eliminated the chances of a recession this year
right now the economy is looking a lot better than we thought it was going to look three months ago,'' said david wyss, an economist with data resources inc., of lexington, mass
at the end of last year, economists were worried about a huge build-up of unsold products which they feared would lead to declines in factory orders and rising unemployment as businesses scaled back production plans
while there have been some production declines, notably in the auto industry, employment has risen sharply in the first two months of the year, pushing the jobless rate down to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent in february
these job gains along with other economic reports have eased recession worries, good news for republicans hoping to hold onto the white house this year
the reagan administration is predicting that the overall economy, as measured by the gross national product, will expand at a modest 2.4 percent rate this year, a forecast which is only slightly more optimistic than the predictions being made by many private economists
the government's first look at overall economic growth will not come until next month when the commerce department releases its first estimate of the performance of the gnp during the january-march quarter
michael evans, head of a washington forecasting firm, said he believed the gnp grew at an annual rate of 1.3 percent in the first quarter and will drop to a rate of 1 percent in the april-june quarter before picking up strength in the last half of the year
while this would represent sluggish growth, it is a significant improvement from evans' earlier forecast that the country would be in a recession in the early part of this year
the economy is sluggish but not declining, and by the second half of the year, we should see better growth,'' evans said
journalists have special protection against court-ordered disclosure of notes, photographs and other information gathered on a non-confidential basis, new york's highest court ruled tuesday
in a 6-0 ruling, the state court of appeals formulated for the first time a test to be used when courts are asked to require disclosure. the test, the court said, protects reporters more than other people against divulging information
the autonomy of the press would be jeopardized if resort to its resource materials, by litigants seeking to utilize the newsgathering efforts of journalists for their private purposes, were routinely permitted,'' judge stewart hancock jr. wrote for the court
hancock added that ``because journalists typically gather information about accidents, crimes and other matters of special interest that often give rise to litigation,'' requiring routine disclosure of those materials ``would be widespread.''
the ruling said courts can order journalists to turn over non-confidential information only if it is ``highly material'' to the litigation, ``critical'' to the claim being brought in court and ``not otherwise available.''
the case before the court involved attempts by a man injured in an auto accident at a construction site to sue the contractors. a photographer for the gannett rochester newspapers took 58 photographs of the accident scene, one of which was published in the rochester democrat and chronicle
lawyers for the man sought copies of all the pictures in the process of building its case
gannett refused, but two state courts, state supreme court in monroe county and the appellate division of state supreme court, ruled that since the photographs were gathered on a non-confidential basis, their disclosure wasn't protected under the state shield law
peter danziger, who filed a brief with the court in the case on behalf of the new york state newspaper publishers association and several news organizations, called the ruling ``a tremendous victory for the public and the press.''
danziger's brief was filed on behalf of the associated press, newsday, the new york times, ottaway newspapers, advance publications, capital cities-abc inc., cbs inc. and nbc inc. for us to send military force to panama. adds last 11 grafs, security agents, with further background, quotes.</note>
president reagan's chief spokesman expressed outrage today at violence against anti-government marchers in panama and said ``there are limits to our patience.''
while restating that it has been u.s. policy not to intervene militarily, spokesman marlin fitzwater also said, ``it has always been a principle that we will protect american citizens as best we can.''
meanwhile, ousted panamanian president eric arturo delvalle asked the united states and other democracies to send a military force to panama to remove strongman manuel antonio noriega
delvalle, who has been in hiding since he was deposed from office a month ago, relayed the message through ambassador juan b. sosa, who said he will formally convey the request to the state department
we are all angry at this latest demonstration, at people being beaten and threatened,'' fitzwater said
i just want to express the outrage of all of us about this incident,'' fitzwater said
fitzwater said the noriega regime ``is showing its true colors. it is desperate and afraid of its own people and the free press.''
the people of panama as well as the leaders arrested yesterday have demonstrated their determination to take on the noriega regime, despite these heavy-handed efforts at intimidation,'' fitzwater said
the thousands of panamanians who braved tear gas, skin irritant sprays and birdshot yestrerday show that intimidation will not solve noriega's problems.''
the spokesman said the united states continued to recommend that american citizens defer travel to panama, and that those who do go there avoid political gatherings and exercise caution
we continue to consider options for dealing with the problem,'' he said
i think it's clear that there are limits to the activities of mr. noriega and limits to our patience and our policy endurance,'' he said. ``it has always been a principle that we will protect american citizens as best we can and, while we have said that we don't plan to go in militarily, it's also important to note that there are limits.''
troops firing shotguns, tear gas and water cannon routed thousands of anti-government marchers monday, then stormed a hotel to arrest opposition activists and journalists
several people were injured and dozens were arrested, witnesses said, in one of the largest protests in months against noriega
security agents forced their way at gunpoint into the offices of nbc, cbs, abc and cnn. tapes, including footage of the day's march, were confiscated. eight foreign journalists, including americans, were detained for several hours before being released
when asked if any action was expected today, fitzwater replied, ``i can't say in advance that anything is expected today, but i would remind you that our concern and monitoring is on a daily basis.''
he was asked whether the president had any meetings on the subject today and answered, ``no, not that i can comment on.''
he said the u.s. troops stationed at the panama canal had not been placed on special alert but ``are in a position to respond appropriately.''
they are there and they are our troops and they are available for whatever needs might arise,'' he said
we are certainly concerned by this threat to americans and find it a very difficult turn of events and one that is contrary to assurances that we have received in the past,'' fitzwater said
i do want to say, when i say that our endurance is not unlimited, that we certainly are willing to take a look at all the hard options, but our policy remains the same and our intention that we would not be using military force,'' fitzwater said
declaring that panama is being held hostage by noriega, sosa told a news conference the united states and other nations must join together to force the removal of noriega
we're asking the international community to help,'' sosa said. ``we're paying the price. but we've got no weapons. give us weapons.''
state department spokesman charles redman called the raid on the hotel a ``shocking demonstration of the anti-democratic nature of the noriega regime and noriega's alarming willingness to use brutal tactics as his position in panama deteriorates
he had no comment on sosa's appeal for an international force. in previous days, the administration has sidestepped that issue, declining to say what options it has under consideration. with marlin fitzwater reaction. picks up 16th graf pvs, bgng: writing of.</note>
president reagan looked so old and careworn after he was told of the challenger explosion in which seven space pioneers died that spokesman larry speakes refused to release a photograph of him to the press
speakes' account of the scene in the oval office on jan. 28, 1986, is one of a number vignettes of the reagan white house that the former chief presidential spokesman provides in a new book, ``speaking out,'' scheduled for publication may 1 by charles scribner's sons
a white house photographer rushed in to record the moment,'' speakes writes. ``the president had the saddest look on his face i have ever seen. he also looked extremely old. that photograph was so unflattering that i refused to release it to the press.''
speakes, who became vice president for communications at merrill lynch after leaving the white house in february 1987, writes as an admirer of the president, but adds that he is ``not blind to the man's flaws and weaknesses.''
during the first year or two of the administration, he says, aides failed to keep reagan abreast of what was going on in the news
when there was a lapse of much time between press interviews or news conferences, he would be totally out of the swim on what was in the press and what had happened two weeks ago, and it would be like reinventing the wheel to get him prepared,'' the former spokesman says
he said reagan ``does not read many newspapers thoroughly'' and ``his habit is to read the comics first.''
although the president frequently uses sports metaphors and stories, speakes says reagan is not really an avid fan
he talks baseball at world series time and football at super bowl time but does not follow those sports regularly, and he knows next to nothing about sports other than baseball and football,'' the former spokesman writes
when the iran-contra arms and money affair broke, says speakes, ``my own advice to the president, which i gave him several times, was to admit that he had made a mistake.'' reagan never quite brought himself to do that
discussing whether reagan knew of the diversion of iran arms sale profits to nicaragua's contra rebels, the former white house aide says: ``frankly, i don't believe the man can tell a lie. the man can make a mistake and the man can hear something so many times that he believes something is true when it really isn't, but he simply isn't a liar. i have no doubt that (indicted former national security council aide oliver) north thought the president knew what was going on, but north was wrong.''
speakes has pungent words for members of the president's personal and official families, although in his six years as the principal white house spokesman, he presented a glowing portrait of them and turned aside reports of bickering and dissension
in the book, co-authored with robert pack, he writes of the president's daughter, maureen: ``you didn't want to stir her up. maureen is ... a straightforward, punch-you-in-the-nose type. her husband, dennis revell, seems to live in mortal fear of her. i've seen her cut him down one side and up the other, and he just stands there and takes it.''
of first lady nancy reagan, he writes: ``mrs. reagan is more circumspect, more likely to stab you in the back.''
elaine crispen, the first lady's press secretary, said mrs. reagan had not read the book and would have no comment. susanne rich, an aide to the president's daughter, did not respond to a request for ms. reagan's reaction
speakes' successor at the white house, marlin fitzwater, said reagan heard a number of comments about the book from reporters during a speaking trip to richmond, va., on monday, but ``in an amazing show of discipline and self-determination, the president said nothing.''
i don't think i want to comment on larry speakes' book,'' fitzwater added
writing of john poindexter, north's boss, who also has been indicted, speakes says that when he showed poindexter a message saying the first news of the iran arms deals had broken in the press in iran, ``he maintained a poker face, betraying no emotion at all. in retrospect, he gave an academy award-winning performance.''
of vice president george bush, speakes says ``the popular image may be accurate: that he does not have a strong philosophical base, that he is not decisive, that he is not willing to take stands on the big issues.''
as for former secretary of defense caspar weinberger, he was ``a hardliner, a small man, a whiny type of guy. with a green eyeshade, he would have looked just like an accountant instead of the head of our largest governmental department.''
michael dukakis battled jesse jackson as well as increasing doubts about his democratic presidential candidacy in the connecticut primary on tuesday. vice president george bush coasted on the republican side as vanquished rival bob dole readied to quit the race
massachusetts gov. dukakis and bush both aimed to cement six-state new england sweeps, but their similarities ended there
dukakis led jackson, the man with momentum in the race, as well as sen. albert gore jr. and sen. paul simon with about 50 percent of the vote in one pre-election poll
the governor hoped for a victory big enough to reassure the skeptics after his landslide loss to jackson in the michigan caucuses last weekend and his third-place finish in the illinois primary on march 15
jackson aimed for a strong second-place showing that would embarrass dukakis in his own back yard and give fresh impetus to the campaign that has been the democratic surprise of the year
gore spent an estimated $75,000 on television advertising in hopes of demonstrating strength in the northeast
in contrast to the democratic disarray, bush's super tuesday spectacular showing on march 8 turned his campaign into a stately march toward the nomination. dole, his once-strong tormenter, arranged a withdrawal speech in washington while the polls were open in connecticut
that left pat robertson as bush's only surviving challenger. but he has signaled that he is a candidate in name only, and is spending the time between now and the gop convention developing a network of supporters for 1992
connecticut's primary offered 35 delegates to the republican national convention, and 52 on the democratic side
before the returns from connecticut were read, the associated press delegate count looked this way:
bush had 788 delegates, to 17 for robertson. it takes 1,139 to claim the nomination
jackson and dukakis both had 606.5, with 2,082 needed to gain the democratic nomination. gore had 365 and simon 169
simon made little effort in connecticut, and rep. richard gephardt dropped out of the democratic race on monday
but dukakis was still suffering the effects of wounds received in illinois and michigan. and anything less than an overpowering victory in next-door connecticut would do little to quell the complaints that his candidacy lacks spark
thus, connecticut looked merely like a prelude to bigger democratic battles to come
gore and simon were planning costly television advertising in wisconsin ahead of next tuesday's primary there. jackson was running virtually even with dukakis in polls there, taken before the former civil rights leader scored his michigan landslide
further away were the two big industrial state battles in new york and pennsylvania. thus, despite gephardt's withdrawal, the democratic race seemed as muddled as ever
even before dole's speech, bush had begun turning his attention toward the fall campaign. campaign officials said he had decided to name business executive fred v. malek to oversee his activities at the republican national convention
in a sign of gathering republican unity, former contender jack kemp returned to the campaign to endorse bush at a news conference in wisconsin
dole's withdrawal came less than two months after he handily defeated bush in the lead-off iowa caucuses. but he then lost new hampshire's primary and three weeks later, was shut out in all 17 super tuesday states
the democratic race couldn't have been more confusing
michigan gave the momentum to jackson. but he is a black, liberal candidate whom many party officials believe cannot possibly win the white house, and thus should not be nominated
his enhanced standing in the race prompted an extraordinary public debate among party officials about the possibility or desirability of organizing a stop-jackson movement
jackson campaigned vigorously in connecticut as he tried to build on the momentum he received from his win in michigan. he sometimes seemed to aim his message at the party's bigwigs around the country as well as at the voters of a single state
if at the end of california, we have the most popular votes and the most delegate votes, becoming the nominee is logical and proper,'' he said on monday
he challenged the notion that party leaders could turn to someone else at the convention
they would not have given me the nomination. i would have earned it from the people,'' he said
dukakis had spent considerable energy in recent days constructing a bandwagon designed to carry him to the nomination. he was winning endorsement after endorsement to go with campaign organization and financing that is the envy of other contenders _ and was backed in connecticut by gov. william o'neill and sen. christopher dodd
but his poor showing in michigan prompted several party leaders to publicly question his ability to generate support. and it has raised anew speculation about a deadlocked party convention casting about for a non-candidate to be its nominee
dukakis' aides were confident their man would win connecticut _ but penciled in a few additional campaign appearances on monday after the results of michigan had sunk in
for his part, dukakis was reluctant to take on jackson directly
i'm not running against (jackson) and he is not running against me. we are running for the presidency,'' he told one questioner
gore initially said he hoped to surprise dukakis in connecticut. but he seemed to have shifted his focus to wisconsin and the new york primary on april 19 in his bid to show he can attract votes outside his native south
simon, a favorite son winner in illinois on march 15, decided to stay out of connecticut and point instead toward wisconsin. aides said he might reassess his campaign _ shorthand for withdrawal _ if he did poorly there
some merchants in this beach city say the loss of the richard m. nixon presidential library will hurt tourism so much they may be forced to close
but one historian suggests a museum dedicated to the president who once lived here could be the answer
nixon was here for 11 years and cannot be neglected,'' said san clemente historical society president charles ashbaugh. ``it's not a case of apathy in the city. it's just that everyone has thrown their hands up and said, `what can we do now?'''
a 13-acre blufftop property owned by the lusk co. was targeted for several years as the future home of the library. but it was tied to a private development, and after numerous delays, nixon decided to put the library in yorba linda, where he was born. nixon now lives in saddle river, n.j
with the library and its estimated 40 million pages of official documents, photographs, videotapes, recordings and gifts from foreign leaders went merchants' dreams of tourist dollars
i'm going to close my business,'' said mike lazarus, who has owned a shop called jeans alley for 13 years. ``now that the town blew it and lost the library ... that really killed the town business-wise. the city had expected it to bring anywhere from 300,000 to 600,000 people here a year.''
a group called citizens for a responsive council tried unsuccessfully to recall three city council members after the loss of the library
i think there are some people who are bitter out there, who have invested some time and money into the city becoming a resort center and who thought they were going to make some money on the tourist thing,'' said tom davis, spokesman for the chamber of commerce
the historical society holds such trinkets as presidential matchbooks and playing cards, toothpaste from china and menus from state dinners
meanwhile, ashbaugh is trying to establish a museum in honor of the nation's 37th president, and olen hanson, the city's founder. it would be located in hanson's former home, a 20-room villa called casa romantica
the home's current owner, george welsh, wants to sell, but does not want the estate bulldozed for development. interested buyers include two developers, one of whom would give the house to the historical society and build condos nearby; and the city, which would provide half the house for a museum
the grammy-award winning rock group u2 left for hollywood tuesday to finish work on a film of their lives on tour which leader bono promised will be a ``work of art.''
the four-man irish band, which won grammies for best group and best album this year, is funding the film directed by phil joanou, a protege of steven spielberg
it will be totally unlike any other rock film,'' said bono. ``it will be a work of art _ on the lines of (the beatles' film) `a hard day's night' with a touch of spielberg thrown in
the cameraman followed us everywhere _ on stage, to the bathroom and even to bed. no secret has been left untold,'' he said
most of the shooting has been completed but the film has to be edited, he said
the group grossed more than $26 million on its 1987 tour to promote their album, ``the joshua tree.''
