a former conrail engineer was sentenced today to the maximum term of five years in prison and fined $1,000 for causing 16 deaths in amtrak's worst train accident
rick l. gates, 33, of essex, pleaded guilty feb. 16 to the single misdemeanor manslaughter count and admitted in a statement of facts to smoking marijuana on the train and failing to make several safety checks that might have prevented the accident
baltimore county circuit court judge joseph p. murphy said, ``i didn't think he was under the influence of marijuana.''
but what he did in terms of failure to follow procedures was to show us that he didn't give a damn. he just didn't care,'' the judge said
gates and family members in the courtroom wept as prosecutors read five victim impact statements from relatives of those killed in the crash
in return for the guilty plea, baltimore county state's attorney sandra o'connor agreed to consolidate the names of all 16 victims into one count, which reduced the maximum sentence from 80 years and $16,000 in fines to five years and a $1,000 fine
the plea bargain provoked sharp criticism from families of victims and leaders of a new safe travel lobby group, safe travel america
i am grossly disappointed that he can cause tens of millions of dollars in damage and kill 16 people and still face only five years on a misdemeanor charge,'' said dr. roger horn, whose 16-year-old daughter ceres was killed
mrs. o'connor urged the judge to give gates the maximum penalty
more than 175 people were injured in the jan. 4, 1987, crash when gates missed a track signal and drove three linked conrail locomotives in front of the 660-passenger amtrak train traveling about 120 mph. the impact trapped riders in the wreckage for hours in bitter cold weather
gates was unhurt and his brakeman, edward cromwell, suffered a broken leg
o'connor said at the time of the plea that the manslaughter verdict would ``send a message that transportation workers cannot work under the kind of negligence that mr. gates did.''
the agreement was announced as jury selection for the gates' six-week manslaughter trial was scheduled to begin. cromwell, who had been granted immunity from prosecution, was expected to testify that he and gates fabricated a story to cover up their drug use on the train
tests performed on blood samples taken from both men after the accident showed traces of marijuana and possibly alcohol in their systems, according to a report by the national transportation safety board
however, defense attorneys said no experts could conclude gates was impaired from the marijuana. lawyers also were expected to cite a january ruling by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals against post-crash drug testing
mrs. o'connor acknowledged that prosecutors had considered the court ruling in deciding to accept the plea. the ruling has been appealed to the supreme court. to lead barred from pulpit, show.</note>
evangelist jimmy swaggart today was barred from the pulpit for at least a year and ordered not to appear on his television show for a year in connection with allegations he hired a prostitute to pose naked
the assemblies of god suspended swaggart as a minister for two years, effective immediately, said a church spokeswoman. that means he cannot preach until he has undergone at least a year of rehabilitation and may be required to limit his preaching longer, she said
swaggart was ordered to undergo rehabilitation for two years
the pentecostal church's general presbytery had the final say on the fiery preacher's punishment. its decision was more severe than the three-month suspension recommended by the louisiana branch of the church
gus weill, a spokesman for jimmy swaggart worldwide ministries in baton rouge, la., declined immediate comment
people approved by the church would supervise swaggart's rehabilitation, the rev. g. raymond carlson, general superintendent of the church, said at a news conference. he provided no other details about the sanctions
the rehabilitation period would begin when swaggart agreed to the terms in writing. he has 30 days to respond
carlson said he had notified swaggart of the decision
he thanked me,'' carlson said. ``he expressed thanks, and i had prayer with him over the telephone.''
a member of the general presbytery, h. maurice lednicky, said most of the discussion in its two-day meeting was over the power of the 13-member executive presbytery to impose punishment
the louisiana district had imposed a three-month suspension from the pulpit for swaggart and had refused to reconsider that on request of the executive presbytery, which sought a stiffer penalty. the executive board noted that every other assemblies of god minister who has confessed to moral failure has been barred from the pulpit for at least a year, officials said
at the meeting, it was agreed that the executive presbytery had constitutional authority in the case, and the punishment given swaggart was the same that the executive presbytery had originally recommended, said lednicky, president of the assemblies of god central bible college in springfield
the 206 presbyters present from the 232-member body reconvened at 9 a.m. after working late monday and ended their meeting two hours later
this is not a meeting to determine the guilt or innocence of jimmy swaggart; he has already confessed,'' church spokeswoman juleen turnage said earlier. ``they are here to make a decision on what will be done with his credentials.''
the assemblies of god, the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, is headquartered in springfield
swaggart tearfully stepped down from his baton rouge, la., pulpit feb. 21, admitting unspecified sins. published reports have said he paid a prostitute to pose naked
debra murphree, who says she is the woman who posed, will appear in the july issue of penthouse magazine, a spokeswoman for the publication said monday
from what i understand, the photographs will recreate the precise poses and actions that jimmy swaggart paid for,'' leslie jay, vice president and director of public relations for penthouse, said in a telephone interview from her new york office
jay said she had not seen the pictures or an interview with murphree. she said she didn't know how much murphree was paid
the general presbytery was directed by the executive presbytery on march 3 to take up the swaggart case
three representatives of the louisiana district attended monday's meeting, which was chaired by carlson
mrs. turnage said carlson briefed the presbyters on swaggart's transgession and the presbyters were given documentation. no witnesses were called and swaggart did not appear
czechoslovakia has requested that chancellor franz vranitzky of austria postpone a visit to prague, and there were reports tuesday that a government shakeup was planned
there have been rumors that premier lubomir strougal, a leading advocate of reform in czechoslovakia, is on his way out
vranitzky told austrian journalists monday that the czechoslovak leadership had asked him to postpone a visit set for april 17-20. the austrian press agency reported the reason given for the postponement was a planned government shuffle in prague
the czechoslovak government spokesman told journalists in prague that a bill would be presented at a national assembly meeting april 19 for the abolition of some ministries by merging them with others
however, the austria press agency quoted sources close to vranitzky as saying that austria's charge d'affaires in prague was called to the czechoslovak premier's office monday
the news agency said an official in strougal's office asked that the visit be postponed because the country was in a ``delicate situation'' in view of pending government changes
it quoted the sources as saying the czechoslovak leadership did not want vrantizky to have to meet with negotiating partners when ``we don't know how long they will remain in the government.''
there have been increasing rumours that strougal was on his way out since gustav husak stepped down as communist party chief in december and was replaced by milos jakes. husak retained the presidency
jakes is not seen as a reformer likely to initiate the kind of economic and politial reforms now being enacted in the soviet union, poland, hungary and bulgaria
states seeking to cope with rising prison costs may not seize social security benefits received by inmates, the supreme court ruled tuesday
the court unanimously struck down an arkansas law that permitted authorities to use an inmate's social security benefits for state purposes
similar laws have been enacted in michigan, ohio, oklahoma and tennessee, the justices had been told
the arkansas law allowed seizure of veterans administration benefits as well. although the court's decision did not discuss va benefits, its rationale appeared to bar seizure of those federal payments as well
the justices, in an unsigned opinion, said federal law ``unambiguously rules out any attempt to attach social security benefits.''
noting that the arkansas law allows such attachment, the court said, ``this amounts to a conflict ... that the state cannot win.''
federal laws creating the social security and veterans administration programs bar any legal action aimed at diverting benefits from the designated recipients
the court rejected arguments by arkansas officials that the federal laws do not apply to seizures of prison inmates' benefits because the inmates are being provided with ``care and maintenance.''
the impact of tuesday's ruling has been blunted somewhat by laws passed by congress in 1980 and 1983 withholding or limiting benefits otherwise due imprisoned felons
the decision also does not affect state laws that require prison inmates to reimburse the state _ from sources other than federal benefits _ for some of the costs of their incarceration
for example, the justices were told that six states require jail inmates serving terms for misdemeanors to make such reimbursements. those states are alabama, illinois, kentucky, missouri, nebraska and north carolina
the justices were told that eight states require reimbursement by inmates for certain kinds of state claims _ ranging from medical expenses to expenses incurred by quelling riots. those states are arizona, florida, maine, maryland, mississippi, nevada, north dakota and rhode island
the arkansas legislature in 1981 passed the state's inmate care and custody reimbursement act. under it, state authorities may seek court approval to seize an inmate's estate _ income from any source
former inmate george bennett challenged the law. he was serving 11 years of a 21-year sentence at a pine bluff prison for second-degree murder when he turned 62
bennett started receiving $275 a month in social security retirement benefits, but those payments were confiscated by state officials. he was released from prison in late 1984 but is seeking to recover $3,600 in seized benefits
the arkansas supreme court ruled against him, but tuesday's ruling reversed the state court's decision
reagan administration lawyers had opposed the arkansas law, telling the justices that such legislation ``would seem to validate the attachment of social security and va benefits paid to persons confined in state mental hospitals or in other institutions where they are provided care by the state.'' arrested in rome, but not confirmed; delete 2nd full reference to cheryl hanin bentov</note>
the father of a young woman identified as the agent who lured israeli nuclear dissident mordechai vanunu to his capture says he was startled to hear of his daughter's alleged espionage activities
of course i was shocked,'' said stanley hanin. ``could you picture your daughter involved in anything like this?''
hanin, owner of the allied discount tires chain, spoke to reporters monday after viewing a television program sunday that described cheryl hanin bentov's alleged role in the capture of vanunu, who disclosed details of israel's nuclear weapons program to a british newspaper in 1986
this is the first i've heard of anything like this,'' said hanin. ``i find this totally unbelievable.''
days after the sunday times published vanunu's revelations, he disappeared from a london hotel where he had been living under an assumed name and later surfaced in an israeli jail. vanunu was tried in secret in israel and sentenced sunday to 18 years in prison for treason
vanunu's brother meir, who lives in london, has claimed that israeli secret service agents used a woman named ``cindy'' to lure his brother to rome with the promise of sex. he says agents captured and drugged his brother there and spirited him to israel for trial
the cbs program ``60 minutes'' sunday identified ``cindy'' as mrs. bentov, an agent of the israeli secret service mossad and wife of ofer bentov, a major in israeli military intelligence
hanin said his daughter moved to israel 10 years ago at age 17 after studying there in a student exchange program. he said they are not close and he has not heard from her ``for some time,'' and that he doesn't know where she lives
i would be concerned for her safety if i thought there was a shred of truth to this,'' hanin said. ``but i don't think there's a speck of truth to it.''
lowell boggs, assistant principal at edgewater high school, where cheryl hanin went to school, said she was a good student who spent the final semester of her senior year studying in israel for about five months
boggs said that over the past 1{ years, the school has been visited by two private detectives who asked to see her yearbook picture, a reporter from london and another from miami asking about her, and, last spring, a man with credentials showing him to be from the cia
edgewater principal charles rohrer said the fbi also came by the school to ``go through her records three or four times.''
a 21-year-old woman near delivery with her first child ended up jailed and in handcuffs instead of in a hospital, all over a traffic violation
kimberly taylor was arrested at her home at 5:20 a.m. saturday because she had failed to appear in court march 18 on the traffic charge
i couldn't believe it,'' mrs. taylor said monday, after a visit to her doctor, who said the baby could arrive any time. ``it was so stupid. you'd think they'd have better things to do than bother me on a saturday morning.''
mrs. taylor said her doctor told her the stress from the incident with the police may be prolonging her labor. she said the sac of water surrounding the baby broke saturday about an hour before she was arrested
police said officer brad maerz was near the end of his shift saturday when he knocked on the taylors' door, told her to get dressed and took her to the police station
mrs. taylor said she was in a holding cell when she overheard maerz tell another officer he made the arrest because ``i was bored.''
police chief henry smith said the taylors had filed a complaint
there will be an internal investigation to look at the circumstances and determine whether good judgment was used in the matter,'' smith said. ``we'll look at any possible violation of procedure.''
smith said mrs. taylor was arrested on a bench warrant from jefferson county court for failure to appear at a hearing. she was cited jan. 21 for driving a car with expired license plates and not having a valid driver's license
mrs. taylor said that when she was taken from the police department to the county jail, ``they didn't want anything to do with a woman whose contractions were coming about 15 minutes apart.''
as she was being released from the county jail, she said she was taken from her cell to the release area in handcuffs
mrs. taylor's husband, paul, said his wife just didn't have her driver's license with her that day
as for the expired plates, ``we had just bought that car, and we were waiting for the title to get new plates,'' he said. ``we have that all taken care of now, but we forgot about the court date because we've been dealing with complications with the pregnancy for the last month. we've been worried about that, and we spaced out the court date. but we think the whole thing has been handled unfairly and unprofessionally.''
the case of a 4-year-old boy adopted in two states by sets of warring relatives after his father killed his mother came nearer resolution tuesday when the indiana court of appeals upheld the voiding of the adoption here
the court unanimously affirmed an april 1987 grant county circuit court decision invalidating the adoption of phillip taylor by his paternal grandparents, everett l. and jean k. taylor, of marion
the boy has since been adopted by celeste benigno white, sister of the boy's mother, and her husband, jefferson white, of the new york city borough of staten island
a legal fight over the child followed the nov. 11, 1984, murder of his mother, teresa benigno taylor, in new jersey. her husband, dr. kenneth taylor, was convicted in 1985 of first-degree murder and sentenced to life imprisonment
after the murder, a new jersey court granted joint custody of the child to the whites and the taylors with the taylors to have custody in july and august and during the week after christmas each year. the whites were to keep the child the rest of the year
in late 1985, the whites filed a custody petition in new york, and in january 1986, the taylors filed an adoption petition in grant county. the taylors had earlier filed an adoption petition that wasn't acted on in new jersey
as part of their indiana petition, the taylors filed kenneth taylor's consent to the adoption. however, according to court records, the whites weren't notified of the proceeding, and the petition didn't mention that the boy's father had been convicted of murder or that a new jersey court had acted on the child's custody
during a visit to indiana in august 1986, phillip was formally adopted by the taylors. in a telephone call to mrs. white, mrs. taylor said that ``the taylors had adopted phillip and that the whites would never see him again,'' court records said
the whites challenged the adoption by arguing that their consent and that of the new jersey court was required
the taylors contended that because they had the consent of their son, phillip's only living parent, they needed no one else's consent
the lower court held and the appeals panel confirmed tuesday that consent of all parties involved _ including the other court and custodial parents _ must be obtained before indiana law permits an adoption
a decree of adoption may be entered only if the required consents were obtained,'' judge william garrard wrote for the court. ``as the taylors failed to obtain all the required consents, the judgment of the adoption was voidable.''
the taylors have not said whether they will appeal tuesday's ruling to the indiana supreme court. conflicts</head>
west virginia university administrators set up a committee tuesday to explore the ethical obligations of students who do ``corporate espionage'' for companies under the auspices of the university
the announcement, made by frank franz, vice president for academic affairs, comes one week after the wall street journal reported that graduate students in the business school divulged sales and inventory figures gained in a study to competitors of the businesses they surveyed
the article points out that the confidentiality of respondents was promised but not observed,'' franz said
the key problem is that the students were put in a very unfortunate position by the sponsors of the project and i think inappropriate things were asked of them.''
franz said the seven-member committee will consider whether students should be required to disclose routinely the sponsor of a study, its purpose and who will receive the information obtained
he said the committee also will suggest ways to avoid conflicts of interest in internships, research projects and other opportunities that arise through consulting performed by faculty members for private companies
the journal reported that two groups of students who conducted competitive analyses for two caterpillar heavy-equipment dealers were asked by the dealers to identify the competitors they interviewed
several students said they did. one of those involved likened the work to ``spying.''
representatives of two of the dealerships interviewed for the 1987 study said they would not have given out the information if they had known the students were working for other dealers
i feel the way they went about it was very underhanded,'' gary clark, executive vice president of clark co., one of the companies in the study, told the daily anthenaeum, the student newspaper
now i will probably be on my guard whenever i talk to students. but i don't blame the students. i blame the professor.''
terry wilson, professor of the marketing 321 class, told the journal that the students ``should not have divulged confidential information to their clients.''
franz said there is no evidence that wilson, who is a consultant for caterpillar, encouraged the students to give the information to the dealerships
wilson, who is on a yearlong sabbatical from the university, did not return telephone messages left with his office
the plo lifted its ban on a meeting between arabs from the occupied territories and u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz, a palestinian said tuesday
u.s. officials said they hoped such a session, expected to take place next week in jerusalem, would help breathe life into a u.s. peace proposal for the region
the shift in policy came after shultz met three days ago with two palestinian-americans linked to the palestine liberation organization
that meeting was great. it was a big step forward and paved the way for us to meet with shultz next week,'' said said kenaan, a prominent nablus businessman
the plo issued two declarations this week, one via a plo representative in cairo and the other from its headquarters in tunis, approving palestinian attendance at a meeting with shultz next week, kenaan said
but kenaan said arabs from east jerusalem and the occupied territories would not attend the jerusalem meeting unless the plo approval was well- publicized and plo chief yasser arafat came out publicly behind it
otherwise we fear for our lives,'' he told the associated press in a telephone interview
shultz is to arrive in jerusalem on sunday and also will visit jordan, syria, saudi arabia and egypt
we want a chance to discuss our grievances, and to tell him the plo must be a party to peace talks on equal footing with all other parties,'' kenaan said
when shultz visited the region in february, palestinians from the territories heeded a call from the plo and refused to meet him. the refusal was viewed by american officials as a setback for u.s. peace proposals
the climate has changed because of shultz's meeting saturday with edward said, a columbia university professor, and ibrahim abu lughud of northwestern university
both men are members of the palestine national council, the plo's self-described legislative body
israeli officials, including prime minister yitzhak shamir, denounced the talks as a violation of a u.s. commitment not to meet with the plo
but other officials close to u.s. efforts to start negotiations in the region said the meeting was intended to pave the way for further involvement of the palestinians in the peace process
shultz has always viewed palestinian participation as very important,'' one u.s. official said privately. ``it was hoped that this move would improve chances for that involvement and thus for the success of the u.s. peace plan.''
in tripoli, libya, hardline palestinian leader george habash urged palestinians to boycott the shultz peace mission
i call upon the revolutionary leadership and plo leadership to boycott the shultz visit as they did the first time,'' said habash, leader of the marxist, syrian-backed popular front for the liberation of palestine, which is affiliated with the plo
if the american administration is sincere in finding a just solution for the middle east it must recognize the plo as the sole legitimate representative of palestinian people ... it must recognize legitimate rights of palestinian people, that is self-determination and an independent palestinian state and reject the nation that we're a second class people,'' he told a news conference
the proportion of women enrolled in schools for health professions has skyrocketed in recent years, according to a federal statistical analysis issued tuesday
the most striking increase was in dental schools, where women made up only 1 percent of enrollment in the 1971-72 school term. by the 1985-86 term, the figure was 25 percent
enrollment of women in medical schools jumped from 11 percent to 33 percent over the same period, and in pharmacy schools from 24 percent to 56 percent
those are among figures contained in the 207-page ``health united states 1987,'' a report issued annually by the department of health and human services
most of the figures were released previously as they were being compiled by one or more of the dozens of agencies within hhs, and tend to lag a year or two behind the volume's publication
the national center for health statistics, an arm of the centers for disease control, organizes the material into an annual report _ as required by law _ to provide a central storehouse of statistical data
the 1987 volume documents that life expectancy at birth has increased dramatically since 1900 for all americans, regardless of race or sex
for example, a black female born in 1900 could expect to live only 33.5 years compared with 62.7 years for one born in 1950 and 73.5 years for one born in 1985
although there have been life expectacy gains across the board, the smallest increase _ 25 years _ was among white males. a white male born in 1900 could expect to live 46.6 years compared with 71.9 years for one born in 1985
some other highlights:
_infant mortality declined only 2 percent between 1984 and 1985, the smallest drop since 1965. the black infant mortality rate, 18.2 per 1,000 live births, is almost twice as high as for white infants, 9.3 per 1,000
_births to unmarried mothers doubled between 1970 and 1985, from 11 percent to 22 percent
_between 1970 and 1985, mortality from cancer, the second leading cause of death, increased slightly overall. however, lung cancer deaths among women more than doubled. heart disease remains the no. 1 killer. delegate count, picking up in 7th graf pvs, in new, and subbing 1 graf for grafs 22-23 pvs, that gave ... 515.6.</note>
republican sen. bob dole quit the presidential race today, three weeks after being buried in george bush's super tuesday landslide, calling himself ``bloodied but unbowed, as the poet says.'' on the democratic side, michael dukakis sought a connecticut primary victory to slow jesse jackson
dole offered his congratulations to bush, who beat him in a solid majority of primaries and said, ``keeping the white house republican, that's the bottom line.''
flanked by his wife, former transportation secretary elizabeth dole, and his daughter robin, dole said, ``i know, and my family knows, that i'm a fighter, and i don't like to lose.''
i've been beaten before and no doubt will again. but i have never been defeated and never will be,'' the kansas senator said, as supporters and fellow senators applauded
white house chief of staff howard h. baker jr., a former presidential hopeful himself as well as a former senate colleague of dole's, said he'd talked to dole earlier, and ``i told him i've been there. i know how it feels. i told him there'll be life after this, political life, that he has a major role to play.''
among the democrats, rep. richard gephardt filed for re-election to his house seat one day after dropping his own presidential bid. he told reporters in jefferson city, mo., ``i am very happy to be here.''
after updating based on final michigan results and a redistribution of some of gephardt's delegates, dukakis held a slim seven-delegate lead over jackson. the massachusetts governor hoped to add to his lead today with a win in neighboring connecticut
in new york meanwhile, sen. albert gore jr., took a few apparent swipes at jackson, an ordained minister known for his ringing speeches
in remarks to the association for a better new york, gore was applauded when he said that in the campaign, ``we're not choosing a preacher, we're choosing a president.''
the oval office is a whole lot more than a pulpit,'' gore said
referring to jackson's calling himself ``a tree shaker, not a jelly maker,'' gore asserted that ``in the oval office, some jelly must be made. only a president who knows how big government works can turn soaring rhetoric and lofty goals into programs and policies.''
among the republicans, even with dole nominally still in the race, bush was overwhelmingly favored today in his almost-home state of connecticut. but he said he didn't want to ``project an arrogance.''
dukakis was also expected to do well in the primary, with 52 delegates at stake. but jackson has been drawing big, enthusiastic crowds in the state
there's nothing more powerful in the world than the people whose hope has been raised,'' he said as he stumped in connecticut on monday
jackson's stunning weekend win in michigan's caucuses put dukakis under mounting pressure. connecticut's democratic state chairman, john f. droney, said that in light of jacson's gains, dukakis had to poll better than 50 percent in the primary to reassert himself
dukakis disputed whether he had to land such a knockout punch just to stay in the ring. ``look _ a victory is a victory,'' he said
jackson, meanwhile, was drawing admiring comment from both sides of the political aisle on monday. bush, campaigning in wisconsin, which holds its primary a week from today, went out of his way to praise him
the man's racking up delegates, and that's how you get elected,'' the vice president said. ``what he has done is very admirable.''
bush's comments came at a news conference in milwaukee, where he picked up the endorsement of rep. jack kemp, a former rival. kemp, who quit the presidential race earlier this month, said he would actively campaign for the vice president
gephardt also praised jackson as he was closing the book on his own democratic candidacy. he refrained from making any formal endorsement, but said: ``i believe jesse jackson can be nominated and i think he can be elected.''
gephardt, whose campaign slid downhill after an initial win in iowa's democratic caucuses, said he was hampered by a lack of funds. but he added: ``i have no alibis. we lost, no question about that.''
gephardt's loss was his rivals' gain. most of his 167 delegates went into the uncommitted column, but missouri state party rules mandate that the at-large and public official delegates are re-divided among the active candidates when a contender drops out
according to the latest ap count, dukakis had 611.55, jackson 604.55, tennessee sen. gore 364.8, illinois sen. paul simon 169.5 and uncommitted 508.6
jackson, who leads in the popular vote totals, said he expects to emerge as the democratic nominee if he wins the most pre-convention delegates
appearing on abc's ``nightline'' on monday night, he said if he were the leader going into the convention, he did not expect that party leaders would use the votes of ``super delegates'' _ elected officials and party professionals _ to keep him from getting the nomination
if they used their power in that way, it would be unwise. it would not be right,'' he said
on the republican side, bush was far, far ahead of either dole or former television evangelist pat robertson, with 778 delegates to dole's 178 and robertson's 17
even so, bush said he didn't want to get overconfident
one of the best things that happened to me was getting my brains kicked out in iowa,'' he said. ``everybody had me dead and buried. we were resurrected ... so people say now things are going pretty well for you, and they are.''
the government is considering charging space shuttle customers up to $245 million a flight for carrying their cargo into space, a congressional panel was told tuesday
up to now, the national aeronautics and space administration has charged $87 million maximum for use of the cargo bay, billed to users according to how much space they used
dale myers, nasa's deputy administrator, confirmed that the $245 million figure was discussed last week by a panel connected to the senior interagency group for space, a top-level advisory committee for the president
that is not the final decision,'' myers told sen. william proxmire, d-wis., at a senate appropriations subcommittee hearing on nasa's fiscal 1989 budget request. he did not dispute proxmire's contention that nasa lost an 8-1 vote for the $245 million figure in the interagency group
the total cost of a shuttle flight has varied, according to the frequency of flights within a given fiscal year. a 1985 estimate _ a year before the challenger disaster _ priced each flight at $150 million, at a rate of 14 launches a year
nasa has never pressed for full recovery of its costs. in the first flights of the shuttle, beginning in 1981, the cost for launching a satellite from the cargo bay was about $10 million
the agency then instituted a pricing policy of $71 million for a full cargo bay, meaning that a satellite owner might pay $23 million-plus if his cargo was launched along with two other satellites. the charge per cargo bay rose to $87 million per flight in october 1985
myers explained during the hearing and afterward that the $245 million was `'sort of an upper limit of all the costs.''
it's an estimate that includes everything including the kitchen sink, all the overhead, manpower required for checkout, all the hardware, all the fuels, all the contingencies that might occur due to delays in flights,'' he said
but asked if that were the amount the space agency would seek to recover from cargo bay users, myers said: ``no, it is not in our view a number that would make any sense at all. i can't really talk too much about it, because this is internal planning.''
a staff member of the appropriations subcommittee called the $245 million ``a non-subsidized, real-world total number for a flight on the shuttle, if you want to buy it.''
the senior interagency group for space includes representatives of nasa, the cia and the commerce, transportation, defense and state departments
the soviet union stops or delays mail to put pressure on dissidents, former moscow activist vladimir slepak told a congressional subcommittee tuesday
the goal of the soviet authorities is to isolate people from any contact with the outside world. this is an effort to break our spirit and determination,'' slepak said
telephones, mail and telegrams are all cut off or interfered with, slepak told the house post office and civil service subcommittee on postal operations. the subcommittee is investigating complaints of returned and undelivered mail sent to the soviet union
the problem is not the bad work of the soviet post office. it is because of the order of the kgb or other authorities,'' said slepak
he cited his five years in exile in siberia, when he regularly received mail from other countries. upon his return to moscow in 1982, mail was cut off, he said
slepak was allowed to leave the soviet union last year following a pair of hunger strikes by himself in moscow and his son in washington
rep. benjamin a. gilman, r-n.y., noted that the subcommittee first started looking into the problem in 1977
with better international relations there may be hope for improvement, gilman said, but ``we must not be lulled into believing that the problem has been or is close to being resolved.''
assistant postmaster general william t. johnstone said in prepared testimony that the rate of returned parcels has declined in the past year. yet, he added, ``while fewer parcels apparently are being returned, the practice remains a troublesome one.''
the soviet union has a long and complex list of unacceptable goods, johnstone said
another problem exists with registered mail, which many people use because the item must be signed for, he added
unlike the united states, where the person receiving the mail must sign, soviet policy is for a postal official to sign the receipt, johnstone said
we plan to exert every effort to try to persuade the soviet union to change its policy,'' he said
one new problem will be arising shortly, johnstone added
starting may 1, the soviet union will require customs declarations on parcels to be written in either french or russian
it is common practice to require declarations in either french or the language of the receiving country, he said. but in the past the soviets have made exceptions to allow english
they announced the change to only french or russian early in 1987, but postponed implementation twice to accommodate the united states, johnstone said
sen. bob dole, his white house hopes crushed by george bush, today ended his republican presidential bid, saying, ``you come to trust your instincts to tell you it's over.''
i'm a fighter and i don't like to lose,'' dole said, surrounded by house and senate colleagues. ``i make no apology for that. it's simply the way i am.''
but he said he also was an optimist. ``i've been beaten before and no doubt will again. but i've never been defeated and never will be.''
dole, who has been without a primary win for more than a month, tipped his hat to bush
the one thing you learn how to do pretty well in our business is to count. you come to trust your instincts to tell you it's over. in my heart i know that time is now. i congratulate george bush and wish him well in november,'' the kansas senator said
dole's remarks showed none of the bitterness that has characterized his attitude toward bush in the past. when dole took the microphone, he cracked, ``we're not going to say anything mean about anybody.''
dole, whose last weeks as a candidate were marked by bruising defeats at the hands of bush, said he looked forward to his return to the senate and his duties as minority leader
i return to the senate as the republican leader eager to engage the issues that confront america ... doing all i can for our nominee, george bush,'' he said
dole recalled his official entry to the race on nov. 9
nearly five months ago i went home to russell, kan., to declare my candidacy for the highest office the american people can bestow. it was only natural i should begin my campaign on main street, among those from whom i have always drawn my strength and my identity. today here i am, bloodied and unbowed, as the poet said,'' he said
dole sent one message to bush, the inevitable gop nominee:
my campaign has been an appeal for all republicans to recognize and celebrate the diversity of america. no party can govern that is not truly representative of this nation of nations.''
the senate minority leader made a fast start out of the gate, overwhelming the vice president in the iowa caucuses feb. 8. but he stumbled a week later in new hampshire's primary. dole rebounded with a pair of wins in south dakota and minnesota on feb. 23, but bush stunned the republican field with a 16-state primary sweep on super tuesday
dole never recovered. though he made an effort to revive his campaign in illinois, he lost heavily there and appeared to be merely going through the motions after that
dole campaigned last week in wisconsin, where he hoped to make a comeback, but public opinion polls indicated a 2-to-1 bush lead. by week's end, dole told a washington audience that he thought bush's nomination was ``a foregone conclusion.''
i can read the numbers and i probably know what's happening,'' he said
we need to keep a republican in the white house. that's where i'm coming from,'' he said. ``and if it can't be me, it will be george bush.''
on monday, he delivered a speech that stopped short of a withdrawal but looked and sounded like a last hurrah. joined by his wife, elizabeth, and daughter, robin, he said he wanted to thank his campaign workers and outline his vision for the future of the gop
dole's second campaign for the republican presidential nomination _ the first, in 1980, also ended in failure _ was flawed all along by internal disarray. the senate leader was not inclined to delegate authority. he finally brought on former labor secretary bill brock last november to run the campaign. but it may have been too late
bush's well-oiled campaign machinery had been in place for years, and dole struggled uphill against a rival who ran as a front-runner and made few mistakes
dole tried repeatedly to stir voters into resentment against bush and his upper-class background, but dole's argument that he was ``one of us'' apparently won over only iowans. dole also lashed out often at bush for his still-murky role in the iran-contra arms-for-hostages affair, but republican primary voters didn't buy it
bush also had a trump card that he played often _ ronald reagan. bush ran successfully as the loyal vice president to one of the most popular presidents in modern history
i'm sort of running against the ghost of ronald reagan,'' dole said recently
surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould testified tuesday that both sides in the baby m case should put aside their bitterness and let the child grow up knowing her birth mother
life is too short,'' said mrs. whitehead-gould in the second day of a visitation hearing. ``i don't know what life is going to bring. but there's a chance that she will never know me, that i'd never know her.''
mrs. whitehead-gould, 31, visibly pregnant in a blue and white maternity dress, spoke calmly and quietly in 2{ hours of testimony. her voice sometimes wavered, but she did did not cry
the child's father, william stern, and his wife elizabeth, sat grim-faced through much of the testimony. mrs. stern smiled occasionally, however, when mrs. whitehead-gould spoke of the mannerisms of the 2-year-old girl legally known as melissa stern
the sterns, who have custody of melissa at their home in tenafly, in their testimony called mrs. whitehead-gould a liar who could undermine their relationship with the child and possibly exploit the girl in the media
mrs. whitehead-gould, of east brunswick, is seeking more liberal visitation with melissa. she wants to see the child two days a week for a total of 16 hours at her home immediately, with the schedule eventually expanded to include overnight stays, half the summer and some holidays
the sterns are seeking to have visitation cut off for several years, perhaps until the child is 9 or 10
the hearing before superior court judge birger m. sween was ordered by the new jersey supreme court, which on feb. 13 restored mrs. whiehead-gould's parental rights but left intact a ruling that gave custody to the sterns
stern, a biochemist, and mrs. stern, a pediatrician, have said they turned to surrogacy because mrs. stern feared that her age and her mild form of multiple sclerosis would make pregnancy dangerous. mrs. stern is now 42
mrs. whitehead-gould agreed to bear them a child for $10,000 by being artificially inseminated with stern's sperm. but when the baby was born, she changed her mind, sparking the dispute
mrs. whitehead-gould, who has remarried and is pregnant with her current husband's child, asked for reconciliation with the sterns in the emotional tug-of-war over the child
i'm willing to meet them more than half way,'' she said
much of mrs. whitehead-gould's testimony answered charges made by the sterns
she said she felt no anger toward the sterns and did not blame them, as stern said monday, for the breakup of her 14-year marriage to richard whitehead
i let go of custody a long time ago,'' she said. ``i want to be a mother. i want to share in raising her in any way i can. but i don't want to undermine the sterns in any way.''
she said that her current visitation schedule of two hours a week under supervision wasn't ``meaningful.'' mrs. whitehead-gould said the child could benefit by contact with her new husband, new york city tax accountant dean gould, and her two children from her previous marriage, ryan, 13, and tuesday, 12
floodwaters swept away two people as they cried for help from their submerged van tuesday and thousands along the swollen danube river prepared to flee amid warnings more dikes could break
the latest apparent drownings brought to six the number of dead in bavaria's worst flooding in 70 years
the rhine river on tuesday crested inches short of the top of a flood wall protecting cologne's historic old town. the danube, mosel, and other major rivers already were receding, but forecasters predicted more flood-threatening rain through easter weekend
rescue workers were searching tuesday for the volkswagen van with two people that witnesses said was swept away by the main river in the bavarian city of wuerzburg, where riverside streets were flooded
witnesses reported seeing the vehicle's headlights in the floodwaters and hearing cries for help. but the van was gone by the time rescuers arrived in boats
the danube river has burst through dikes in several places since sunday, forcing 3,500 people to evacuate
officials, meanwhile, worried about forecasts for more rain. ``we're not giving the all-clear signal yet,'' said ruediger beiser, an official with the office for water and river transport in mainz
rhine floodwater covered nearby sidewalks and some streets in bonn, the federal capital. residents of large villas lining the river in the bonn district, which house many embassies, were preparing sandbags and using pumps to dry out their flooded cellars
in a section of cologne's old town area, residents spent the night building mortar-and-brick walls around their homes, clearing out their basements, and placing elevated planks on their sidewalks
the rhine rose to 32.3 feet at about 3 a.m. and stayed there, dramtically stopping just short of the top of a 32{-foot flood wall
all the same, some water had seaped through the barrier and was being pumped out of cellars
unfortunately, the wall is not totally watertight,'' said eckehard link, head of anti-flooding efforts for cologne, a city of 1 million people
the justice minister has resigned after a former policeman said the minister headed a secret anti-narcotics police that sold confiscated drugs and weapons
minister jose manzo gonzalez's resignation was effective monday. he had been justice minister since 1984
he was replaced tuesday by pedro torres agudo, former head of the technical judicial police, venezuela's principal investigative police corps
the newspaper, el universal, reported tuesday that gonzalez resigned to aid a police investigation and to take legal action against people who allegedly injured his prestige
manzo's resignation came on the same day as the resignation of his counterpart in colombia, alfredo gutierrez marquez. gutierrez stepped down after reports that an airstrip at his brother's ranch was used by drug runners linked to colombia medellin cartel
the cartel smuggles most of the cocaine reaching the united states, the u.s. drug enforcement administration says
in a videotape played two weeks ago before the investigations committee of the venezuelan congress, former police roberto eduardo dipucci ponti said manzo set up a secret police unit to infiltrate narcotics rings in venezuela
dipucci ponti said the unit captured drugs and weapons from narcotics traffickers and then resold them
the former officer said he was a member of the secret force and that he made the videotape because he feared for his life. dipucci reportedly is in hiding in venezuela
the president of the investigations committee, paciano padron, called for manzo's removal after initial investigations indicated the existence of the secret unit and irregularities in its activities
the committee began its investigations in february after a leftist politician claimed venezuela's political parties were financing their presidential campaigns with drug money
padron also maintained the police unit itself was illegal since it depended directly on manzo rather than one of the official venezuelan security forces
manzo has said that the secret force existed between 1982 and 1986 but claimed it was a military agency
defense minister eliodoro guerrero gomez has denied the unit ever operated within the military
the military said its troops stormed a capital suburb tuesday and captured six communist guerrillas, including three top leaders, as rebels marked the anniversary of their struggle
chief of staff gen. renato de villa hailed the arrests in the manila suburb of san juan as ``a big loss'' to the communists. he said those captured were ``very high-ranking personalities who have been the subject of many manhunts and many operations in the past.''
troops in manila and five other regions had been placed on heightened alert in anticipation of rebel attacks on the anniversary of the 24,000-member new people's army, a communist group that began fighting the government 19 years ago
the top leaders were identified as rafael baylosis, secretary general of the communist party of the philippines; benjamin de vera, a party central committee member; and new people's army chief of staff napoleon manuel. a military report says de vera also heads the party's commission in charge of operations on mindanao, the country's second-largest island where the rebels have been strong
no major rebel attacks were reported tuesday. however, such reports often take days to reach manila from the countryside
a japanese tourist was shot and killed near the manila airport by an unidentified gunman who escaped, police said. akihiro sato, 49, died from bullet wounds in the neck and shoulder
police said they had no idea who the killer was
military leaders also announced tuesday they had determined that rebels from the alex boncayao brigade, the manila branch of the new people's army, were responsible for monday's ambush on suburban manila mayor prospero oreta. seven of his bodyguards were killed and the mayor, a distant relative of president corazon aquino, was wounded
officers said those captured tuesday might not have been directly involved, but they definitely came from the same organizations
in general, the (oreta) case is solved,'' said brig. gen. alexander aguirre. ``all we have to do is to arrest the people who perpetrated it. but we are happy to say now that we did not only arrest the (people) that did the hitting but the leaders who are orchestrating these assassination activities.''
the rebel leaders were arrested tuesday in two separate raids. an ak-47 rifle, grenades, computers, radio equipment, and underground documents were confiscated in the raids, aguirre said
he said mrs. aquino had been informed about the arrests and ``she was elated, she was glad.''
on monday, the alex boncayao brigade admitted responsibility for sunday's murder of bus driver ruben saulog. they accused him of ordering the killings of two unions leaders
nigeria's estimated population of 100 million will double in the next two decades unless nigerian women have fewer children, the health minister said tuesday
the news agency of nigeria quoted health minister ransome-kuti as saying the military government's new population policy was aimed at preserving the health of the ``mothers and their children'' rather than simply reducing population growth
the government has adopted a policy calling on women to limit themselves to four children each. womens' groups and christian churches say the policy is unfair because it would allow polygamous men to have many children and favors the moslem religion
ransome-kuti, in detailing the policy, said efforts would be made to counsel men on their responsibilities to their spouses and children
he said the government would make family planning services available nationwide, but would not try to force couples to limit births
couples will be encouraged to have the number of children they can adequately care for,'' he said
ransome-kuti said the government hopes to persuade women to marry after age 18 and to space births at least two years apart
he said the policy seeks to reduce annual population growth from 3.3 percent to 2.5 percent in 1995 and 2 percent by 2000
nigeria is africa's most populous country
harold thomas was back in his shack tuesday alongside the chicago river after a failed journey to new mexico in search of a new life, but he said he was trying to find work and a decent home
i've been trying to get me a decent place to stay and i got an interview about a regular job tomorrow,'' he said. ``i feel like i've got to make something out of myself some way or other, because so many people were concerned
and besides, i owe it to myself,'' said thomas, who hopes to find a construction job with a former employer
since his return from portales, n.m., a week ago, thomas has divided his time between a girlfriend's apartment and the wood-and-tarpaper shack he and friend tommy ray built late last year on a vacant, bottle-strewn lot in the shadow of the city's glittering downtown
i go by and help clean it up, and i stay there sometimes,'' he said of the makeshift shelter by the chicago river. ``tommy and them are sort of my people, like family
and that's the place where it all happened.''
thomas' sojourn to the southwest began when a new mexico couple, roy and ethel gilman, read an associated press story describing his life in the open shack during sub-zero weather
they offered him a job and a place to stay
thomas arrived in portales on jan. 17 and spent two months with the gilmans, receiving room and board in exchange for work at the couple's wrecking yard
but thomas said he was paid no wages until reporters raised the issue and the gilmans put $300 in a bank account for him
thomas withdrew the money and bought a bus ticket home
they were hard-working, good people, but the money situation disappointed me,'' said thomas
a man needs a regular wage, he needs to be able to buy himself a cup of coffee or a sandwich. and i think the gilmans got tired of all the attention that came with me,'' he said
one thing was simplified by his brief fling with celebrity: reinstatement of the $154 a month in public assistance and food stamps he had been receiving before he went to new mexico
when he attempted monday to pick up his march check, thomas was told he would have to furnish proof he had worked the two previous months, and that his job had ended, said social worker clara collins with the non-profit travelers and immigrants aid
he went back to the shack and brought them his newspaper clippings,'' ms. collins said. ``at first, they said there were plenty of harold thomases, but i guess they finally gave in.''
so tuesday, $154 richer and buoyed by the prospect of a job interview, thomas picked up some italian beef sandwiches and headed for the hovel he still calls home sometimes
there, ray, 37, and 62-year-old arthur haymond, another of the five or six men who share the rotting, often-leaky shack, waited eagerly for his arrival
it's funny,'' said ray. ``after people first read about us, they came by with a can of coffee, or a loaf of bread to help out. or talk about where we might find work
but since then, hasn't been much but the gang kids throwing stones and busting us up
i guess,'' said ray, rubbing his chin and pulling up closer to the fire burning in an oil drum, ``people just got short memories.''
president reagan on tuesday hedged his assertion that oliver l. north is a hero, with the president confining his contining praise to the marine's combat record
reagan also said he believes north, a former white house national security aide charged with conspiracy in the iran-contra arms and money affair, hasn't gotten the benefit of a fair trial before being presumed guilty by many
reagan, saying he wanted to ``augment'' comments he made last week after north's criminal indictment, said, ``i think i was too short in my remark.''
the president was referring to his defense of north as a hero and his prediction that the marine lieutenant colonel will be found innocent of iran-contra charges along with rear adm. john m. poindexter, the former national security adviser to the president and north's superior
reagan did not reiterate that prediction, but he adjusted his definition of north's heroism
i should have augmented that, and said why, and that is: look at the record and at the honors and the medals that have been awarded to him for bravery in combat,'' reagan said in a white house interview with regional reporters
i have to say those were heroic actions and he is a valid hero,'' the president said
north, who intends to retire from the marine corps in may, received a silver star and two purple hearts in the vietnam war
reagan said the allegations about north and poindexter raise a ``sore point with me about a lot of things that have been going on with regard to people in our administration.''
someplace along the line, many of us have forgotten that you are innocent until proven guilty beyond a reasonable doubt,'' the president said
what has a happened, i think, in the case (of north and poindexter) is it's just everyone is accepting guilt on the basis of accusation,'' reagan said. ``i say they've got a right to be presumed innocent until someone proves them guilty of the charges.''
north and poindexter were named march 16 in a federal indictment accusing them of defrauding the government in the sale of u.s. weapons to iran and the diversion of profits to the nicaraguan contras at a time when u.s. aid to the rebels was banned
in addition to north and poindexter, several other past or present members of the administration _ including some of reagan's closest confidants _ have been accused of improper behavior
former aide michael deaver was convicted of perjury regarding his lobbying activities, and reagan's onetime political director, lyn nofziger, was found guilty of illegal lobbying
attorney general edwin meese iii has been the subject of independent counsel investigations. meese has continually denied wrongdoing
north said after his indictment that he might attempt to subpoena the ``highest ranking'' government officials to testify in his defense
reagan declined to say if he would testify on north's behalf. ``i don't know what his situation will be, with regard to giving testimony or not,'' reagan said. cases</head>
the equal employment opportunity commission mishandled hundreds of age discrimination complaints partly because congress failed to give it enough money, eeoc chairman clarence thomas said tuesday
in testimony to the house government operations subcommittee on employment and housing, thomas said there was no excuse for agency offices having let the two-year statute of limitations expire on some 1,600 complaints from oct. 1, 1986, to jan. 31, 1988
but he said that in order to prevent such situations from recurring, the agency needs more money
i have been through the budget process seven times now, and each time, congress has appropriated less than what was requested by president reagan,'' thomas said in his statement
for example, he said, the agency sought $193.4 million this year but received only $179.8 million, and it has been told its prospects for receiving a requested $194.6 million in 1989 do not look good
if eeoc is held to a 2 percent increase over the fiscal 1988 appropriation, we will lose 244 positions and the pending inventory of charges will grow by 20,000,'' thomas said
subcommittee chairman tom lantos, d-calif., said a recent panel investigation of the national labor relations board found that 92 percent of unfair labor charges are fully investigated within 30 days
if the nlrb regional offices can meet a 30-day time target, why does it take eeoc regional offices more than two years to perform similar investigations?'' lantos said. ``we should not need repeated hearings and legislative action to ensure and to restore workers' basic civil rights which have long since been established in law.''
in his statement, thomas said the regional offices attributed their problems to, among other things, short staffing, complex and unprecedented cases, poor case tracking, heavy workload and charges filed six months to 18 months after an alleged violation
he said the worst offender was the philadelphia regional office with 241 charges that expired, followed by los angeles with 222; baltimore with 175; new york with 150; chicago with 137; and detroit with 105. san francisco had no instances, while atlanta and charlotte, n.c., had one apiece
helen mcdonald, representing the american association of retired persons, said the eeoc must give people realistic advice about whether their cases will be pursued and tell them clearly about the two-year deadline
she also said the eeoc should change its policy of refusing to notify people who might benefit from a class action, even when the agency already has determined an employer has discriminated. currently it is the responsibility of potential members of the class action to find out about the complaint and join it
the house on tuesday passed a bill extending the statute of limitations another 18 months for people whose cases expired without eeoc action. the senate already has passed a similar measure
fed up with dog bites, mail carrier jim codner made his rounds in the company of two dog catchers from the city's animal control department when he delivered mail tuesday at a housing project
unlike monday, when three dogs were taken into custody, there wasn't a canine in sight as codner delivered the mail with his companions, who were armed with dog snares _ three-foot and five-foot sticks with rubber-coated wires at the end to catch any pooch on the loose
at least if the dogs come out, they'll have a few more targets,'' codner said, when he resumed deliveries. ``usually it's just me and the hallway.''
mail delivery to 240 households at the orient heights rojects was suspended march 12 after codner, who has delivered mail there for seven years, was attacked for the fourth time this year by one of the dogs roaming the halls
for the two weeks codner didn't bring any mail, it was left at a post office more than half a mile away
it was really hard for the elderly people who needed their mail and couldn't get it,'' said jackie thurston, who lives in the project
it feels good to have jimmy and the mail back,'' said connie durbano, another resident
the escorted service will last a week. if codner's customers don't get the message by then, the postal service has threatened to deliver mail to a single drop instead of door to door
steven o'donnell, the city's chief dog catcher, said he has eight inspectors and two trucks _ one currently broken _ to cover a city of 65,000 dogs. o'donnell complained that the city won't invest in better dog control. he also has proposed stiffer fines for violators
the city requires dogs to be restrained at all times. but while the dog owners are fined $50 if their pets are caught defecating on the sidewalk, they are fined only $25 for dogs picked up roaming free
in other carrier battlefronts of massachusetts, mail delivery was suspended temporarily in parts of medford a few years ago to protect carriers, and a carrier bitten in the face by a dog in winthrop last weekend may need plastic surgery
every day, somewhere in america, a mail carrier is probably being bitten, said delivery supervisor phil auciello, codner's boss
the navy on tuesday formally awarded a $724.4 million contract to the newport news shipbuilding &amp; drydock co. to begin the process of building two nuclear-powered aircraft carriers
the award had been expected since late last fall, when congress agreed to amend the fiscal 1988 budget to purchase two carriers at once in a cost-saving move
newport news shipbuilding, which is based in the virginia city of the same name, is a division of tenneco inc. and the only shipyard capable of building the huge nimitz-class nuclear carriers
the contract awarded tuesday covers ``long lead time material and effort'' to get construction started and will be followed before the end of the fiscal year with a full construction contract, the navy said
congress has budgeted $6.3 billion for the two carriers
president chun doo-hwan's younger brother denied tuesday that he stole millions of dollars from a semi-official development agency, but prosecutors said they had enough evidence to try him
a close associate of chun kyung-hwan, 46, tried to kill himself while under interrogation and arrest warrants were issued for five other people in the growing scandal
he keeps denying all charges, passing the buck to his subordinates, but it would not work. we have enough evidence,'' senior prosecutor lee chong-chan said of chun
twelve hours after questioning, prosecutors gave no indication whether he would be put under formal arrest. officials had said monday he was not likely to be released
prosecutors said their initial investigation indicated chun embezzled or otherwise pocketed the equivalent of $14 million belonging to the saemaul (new community) movement, which he headed for seven years
the semi-official organization is dedicated to urban and rural development. chun kyung-hwan was its director from 1981 until he resigned last year after reports that he had links with the underworld
according to the prosecutors, he is suspected of using the money allegedly taken from saemaul for such purposes as speculation in land and stocks
legal experts say charges being contemplated in the case could result in more than five years in prison if chun is convicted
chun was summoned by prosecutors tuesday morning for questioning about allegations that he abused power to get government funds for saemaul and cash donations from business executives
when chun arrived at the prosecutor general's office, a man rushed from the crowd yelling an insult, hit him in the face and fled
a ranking official of saemaul, hwang hung-sik, 37, made two suicide attempts during interrogation, once by trying to jump from a fifth-floor window, officials reported
hwang is accused of keeping secret ledgers on transactions involving money chun allegedly embezzled
about 200 government officials and business executives have been questioned about allegedly helping chun either to amass a fortune or cover up the activity
opposition parties demanded tuesday that the former president cut short a trip to the united states and state whether he was involved in the scandal
chun doo-hwan was succeeded last month by roh tae-woo, who won the presidential election in december
roh, a former general who helped put chun in power with military backing in 1980, has promised to root out and end official corruption
a veteran antarctic researcher announced findings tuesday indicating that the depletion of the earth's ozone layer could threaten the world's food supply
professor sayed el-sayed of texas a&amp;m university said increased amounts of ultraviolet light, which a thinner ozone shield permits through to the earth's surface, supresses biological activity in microscopic marine plants in the antarctic
el-sayed said his findings, the first of their kind, confirm strong suspicions of biologists that ultraviolet light might mean trouble for fish, animal and other life in the southernmost part of the world
on the other hand, ``i never underestimate the resilency of nature,'' he said
el-sayed said it is impossible now to say whether the plankton _ microscopic single-celled organisms called ``the grass of the sea'' _ and the organisms that feed on them might adapt to increased ultraviolet radiation, and much work remains to be done
plankton and the tiny shrimp-like creature called krill that feed on them are the primary food source for the whole web of life in the antarctic, including fish, penguins and whales. a baleen whale may eat three tons a day
if anything happened to the krill population, the whole ecosystem probably would collapse, and you can say goodbye to the whales and the penguins and the seals and the fish,'' el-sayed told reporters at briefing arranged by the world resources institute, a washington environmental research organization
several nations are studying plans to harvest krill, a 550-million to 770-million ton reservoir of protein. a 10 percent annual harvest would almost equal the current world fish catch
the ozone shield over antarctica already thins greatly in springtime, with the depletion reaching a record 50 percent last year. scientists attribute the destruction of ozone to man-made chemicals called chlorofluorocarbons, or cfcs
the environmental protection agency estimates that a 1 percent drop in ozone means a 2 percent increase in ultraviolet light and a 4.8 percent to 7.5 percent increase in the most common skin cancers
the national aeronautics and space administration on march 15 said a depletion of ozone at mid-latitudes of the northern hemisphere since 1969 was in all likelihood the result of those chemicals. the du pont co. said last week it plans to stop making them
epa administrator lee m. thomas told reporters over lunch tuesday that the epa and nasa would try to speed up the first scientific review under last fall's treaty by 31 nations calling for a cut in cfc production by 50 percent by 1998
thomas said he would not support bills in the senate, subject of a hearing wednesday, calling for an early 95 percent cut in u.s. production
a u.s. cut beyond international agreement might take the pressure off other cfc-producing countries to act further, thomas said, and would add little to ozone protection
sayed, a biological oceanographer, was supported in his work last fall on anvers island near palmer station by the national science foundation. he and the foundation wanted to see if he could extend earlier german findings that decreases in ultraviolet enhance plankton growth
the overseas press club sent a letter to gen. manuel antonio noriega on tuesday protesting what it described as ``harsh treatment'' of foreign journalists in panama city
the organization of journalists said in a letter addressed to the defense forces commander in panama that the arrests of eight journalists in panama on monday violated united nations rules on human rights
the journalists were arrested along with 20 opposition leaders when troops raided the marriott hotel, which serves as the headquarters of panama's opposition and the foreign press. the journalists were released tuesday
the letter, signed by norman a. schorr, chairman of the club's freedom of press committee, called on noriega to protect the rights of journalists to do their work ``free from harassment, intimidation and physical harm.''
a time bomb in a sack of onions being taken to market exploded on a rural bus tuesday, killing 10 sinhalese farmers and critically wounding 15, police reported
a spokesman said nine of the dead were blown to pieces
police blamed the explosion in north-central sri lanka on tamil militants who have fought since 1983 for a separate homeland for the ethnic minority in the northern and eastern parts of the island
the bomb went off as the bus neared ratmalagawewa, a village near anuradhpura city, about 100 miles northeast of colombo, police reported
nine persons were blown to bits in the blast and one died in the hospital. fifteen more are in critical condition,'' said a police spokesman at anuradhpura. ``all are sinhalese farmers taking their produce to towns nearby.''
he said, speaking on condition of anonymity, that the bomb was the work of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the most powerful rebel group. eelam is what the tamils would call a separate homeland in the parts of sri lanka where the ethnic group is dominant
more than 135 people, most of them sinhalese, have been killed in the eastern and north central provinces in the past 29 days, since the latest round of violence began. residents of anuradhpura said large numbers of soldiers were moving into the area for a ``cordon and search'' operation
in the southern region, a police sergeant was reported killed and a constable seriously wounded by a man who opened fire with an automatic rifle monday in tangalle, a town 90 miles southeast of colombo
police in tangalle said the gunman was from the outlawed people's liberation front, a sinhalese organization opposed to an indian-sponsored peace accord intended to halt the tamil civil war
the agreement, signed last july, gives some autonomy to tamil areas. sinhalese nationalists say it makes too many concessions
at least 220 killings have been blamed on the radical sinhalese group, which has vowed to kill anyone who supports the agreement
sinhalese, most of whom are buddhists, make up 75 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people. tamils, about 18 percent, are predominantly hindu and claim discrimination by the sinhalese, who control the government and army
at least 7,000 people have been killed in the five years since the tamils began fighting. india became involved as a peacemaker because its 800 million people include about 60 million tamils, most of whom live in tamil nadu state just across the narrow palk strait from sri lanka
cia director william h. webster told the senate intelligence committee on tuesday that he has reorganized the spy agency to improve counterintelligence and strengthen security at u.s. embassies around the world
webster told a closed session of the committee that he has ``reorganized the counterintelligence function within the cia and appointed a senior official to head it,'' said a statement issued by sens. david l. boren, d-okla., and william s. cohen, r-maine, the chairman and senior republican on the committee
boren and cohen did not name the official appointed by webster and the cia did not immediately return a telephone call concerning the reorganization
boren and cohen said webster informed the committee of ``several new initiatives within the cia and the intelligence community designed to strengthen security at u.s. missions abroad and to improve counterintelligence in the cia.''
the reorganization ``will also combine the critical resources needed to combat the threat to u.s. personnel and to facilities overseas,'' the senators said
in addition, webster announced formation of a new, independent office ``which will report to him in his capacity as director of central intelligence,'' the senators said
boren said creation of the independent office ``grows out of recommendations on embassy security'' submitted to president reagan by webster and secretary of state george p. shultz in april 1987
reagan asked for the recommendations after reports of widespread security leaks and espionage at the u.s. embassy in moscow
the report recommended that the director of central intelligence certify the security conditions of all existing embassies and of all new facilities before they are put into operation
an earlier report by the senate intelligence committee cited a need for ``cia initiatives to improve both its counterintelligence efforts and its career opportunities in counterintelligence.''
that report, issued in november 1986, stressed what it called ``the added requirements for counterintelligence support in intelligence collection programs.''
utah's attorney general has blasted independent counsel lawrence walsh for asking judicial officials around the country for help in the iran-contra case, but others appear unconcerned about walsh's activity
i wasn't going to give lawrence walsh's people the time of day,'' david wilkinson, the utah official said, commenting on a letter he received from the independent counsel's office
jeffrey toobin, an associate in walsh's office, sent a letter march 15 to u.s. attorneys and attorneys general in 50 states seeking information about other cases involving immunity
james wieghart, walsh's spokesman, said monday the letter was a routine request to ensure that prosecutors are up-to-date on the most recent case law
the letter asks judicial officials for ``anything you think might be helpful _ established procedures, transcripts, briefs or even informal office lore.'' the existence of the letter was first revealed on the editorial page of the wall street journal
defendants in the iran-contra case are expected to challenge walsh on immunity because they received such grants from congress in exchange for testifying about the iran-contra case last summer
former white house aides john m. poindexter, oliver l. north and businessman albert hakim were granted immunity, but richard v. secord, hakim's partner, was not. the four are charged with conspiracy and theft in the iran-contra case
walsh cannot use any information from the congressional hearings in court, and he must prove that his data was gathered independently. walsh has hired former federal judge herbert stern to supervise the handling of legal challenges
u.s. district court judge gerhard gesell has set april 12 for a hearing on the immunity issue. attorneys in the case must file their papers by april 7
wilkinson, who provided the associated press with a copy of the toobin letter, said he considered it a ``little bizarre that an independent counsel would be seeking help from the state attorneys general.''
wilkinson, a republican, noted that there is a constitutional dispute over the existence of the independent counsels, which were created by congress under the 1978 ethics in government act
the supreme court is scheduled to hear arguments on april 26 on a lower court decision that struck down the constitutionality of the special prosecutors
wilkinson said his ``sympathies are with the executive branch, not the legislative branch.''
but not everyone was as perturbed as wilkinson about the letter
leroy zimmerman, the gop attorney general in pennsylvania, has directed his staff ``pass along any information or experiences which would be helpful'' to walsh's people, according to bob gentzel, his spokesman
attorneys in the office of travis medlock, south carolina's attorney general, are still reviewing the letter, according to mark dillard, his spokesman
alan ashby, spokesman for california attorney general john van de kamp, said he didn't know if his boss had received the letter. but he said the state and federal judiciary have a ``pretty close working relationship'' on many issues when the jurisdictions overlap
the wisconsin presidential primary comes at a crossroads for the democratic candidates, with michael dukakis trying to wrest momentum from jesse jackson and long-shots albert gore jr. and paul simon trying to keep their campaigns alive
the results of michigan have increased the importance of wisconsin,'' tony tsakakis, a national campaign aide to dukakis, said tuesday
after his loss to jackson in saturday's michigan caucuses, the massachusetts governor has stepped up his campaign schedule in wisconsin ahead of the state's primary next tuesday, tsakakis said
dukakis won an endorsement tuesday from former wisconsin gov. patrick lucey, who said the wisconsin primary and its 81 democratic delegates ``is every bit as significant as it was for another massachusetts candidate, john f. kennedy, in 1960.''
we've always felt every state is a must state,'' tsakakis said, noting however that wisconsin now has added significance for dukakis' candidacy
dukakis' third-place finish in illinois behind simon and jackson and his second-place showing in michigan have tossed uncertainty into the democratic race
we're looking to wisconsin to continue our ever-broadening base of support,'' said jackson aide bob burns. ``if we have reasonably good back-to-back showings in large industrial states, it will give us a head of steam going into new york'' on april 19
polls indicate the race is a dead heat between jackson and dukakis
jackson has won compliments from wisconsin's gop governor, tommy thompson, and even from vice president george bush
his campaign was diminished in the beginning by a lot of sophisticated observers, politicians,'' bush said in a wisconsin campaign appearance monday. ``they never gave him much of the time of day, and he's doing very, very well taking his case to the people.''
bush should literally walk away with the 47 republican delegates. rival bob dole quit the race on tuesday. the only remaining gop opponent, pat robertson, has made no effort here
colorado's caucuses on monday, a day before the wisconsin primary, are also shaping up as a jackson-dukakis fight
the worst jackson will do is finish second. but i think he has a good chance of winning,'' said mike stratton, a denver democratic consultant who ran gary hart's 1984 colorado campaign. stratton said jackson's liberal, anti-establishment message was attractive to many former hart supporters
in wisconsin, simon badly needs a good showing in wisconsin to keep his campaign alive. after his win in home state illinois two weeks ago, simon said he was pinning his hopes on wisconsin
gore also has campaigned heavily in wisconsin and has flooded television airwaves with his advertisements
gore's father, former sen. albert gore sr., said tuesday his son needs a ``respectable showing'' in wisconsin, which he defined as a ``strong third.''
american builders will be allowed to bid on japanese construction projects under a new agreement aimed at ending a trade dispute that has soured relations between the two countries
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter told a joint news conference tuesday he was pleased that the prolonged, on-and-off talks had reached ``a fruitful conclusion,'' proving that the two countries through negotiations are able ``to manage difficult bilateral trade disputes.''
japanese chief negotiator ochiro ozawa said he hopes u.s. construction companies will take full advantage of the agreement ``by taking concrete action to obtain construction licenses in japan and actually participating'' in the japanese construction boom
ozawa, deputy chief cabinet secretary for prime minister noboru takeshita, headed the talks as the personal representative of the prime minister in accordance with takeshita's agreement with president reagan in january that the construction dispute would be solved amicably, he said
it is my great pleasure to see a settlement that is amicable, mutually satisfactory and fruitful,'' ozawa said
yeutter's deputy, michael smith, said the agreement provides for the japanese government to facilitate the admittance of american firms to the bidding on japanese projects
it is up to the u.s. firms'' to take advantage of the agreement, he added
smith said the accord provides for u.s. participation in construction of the kansai international airport and some other projects on which the two governments had basically agreed last year
added to it were procedures for bidding on other public works projects financed by the central government, he said
smith said a third category being opened to u.s. bidders was local public construction as well as private projects franchised or approved by the central government
these include airport terminals which u.s. builders said they have been prevented from bidding on despite very competitive standards
the agreement means it will be easier in the future for them to enter the bidding, smith said
deputy u.s. commerce secretary w. allen moore told reporters, ``our side feels fairly good about the outcome of these talks, but the real proof of access will be in the future.''
moore said commerce secretary c. william verity next week plans to call heads of major u.s. construction companies to washington and ``urge them to take advantage of what we sincerely believe is a real opportunity.''
officials said that besides the multibillion-dollar kansai airport project off osaka the agreement specifically covers entry of u.s. builders into the bidding for work on such projects as the tokyo bay causeway, the new headquarters of nippon telegraph and telephone public corp., the tokyo haneda airport, coastline development, a new hiroshima airport, the tokyo bay redevelopment project, the akashi straits bridge, the ise coastal road south of nagoya, the new port 21 planned for yokohama and a new kansai research city planned for the osaka-kobe area
first lady nancy reagan, who underwent successful breast cancer surgery last october, received a surprise ``courage award'' from the american cancer society on tuesday for encouraging other women to seek early detection of the disease
i can't say this is an award i dreamed of getting when i was growing up, but if you can help other people deal with this problem, that makes you feel good,'' she said. ``i hope that's what has happened.''
mrs. reagan received the award during a rose garden ceremony for 60 award winners including actress jill ireland, who is the society's honorary fund-raising chairman
mrs. reagan and the actress both had a breast removed because of malignant tumors. the society said the president's wife was honored for her example of ``strength and courage'' in overcoming breast surgery and encouraging other women to use mammography, an x-ray technique for early detection of breast tumors
president reagan told the ``courage award'' winners they had proved that ``fear was not the end for you but a challenge'' to triumph over cancer and help others confront the disease
people need to know that cancer isn't something to run and hide from, but cancer is a fact that must be faced and dealt with,'' he said
reagan said he and his wife learned that ``good medical supervision, early detection and prompt treatment were the keys to victory over cancer.''
reagan underwent surgery in july 13, 1985, for removal of a small, malignant polyp from his colon. doctors found another, larger cancerous polyp that was removed the following day along with two feet of intestinal tract. they said the cancer had not spread beyond the tissues that were removed. grafs for 7th graf pvs, dole's withdrawal</note>
republican bob dole ended his campaign for president tuesday, saying he was ``bloodied but unbowed'' by the series of bruising primary losses that finished his candidacy
dole withdrew before a supportive audience of senate and house colleagues and offered congratulations to george bush, the all-but-anointed gop nominee
my friends know that i am a fighter; i don't like to lose,'' the senate republican leader said. ``i have been beaten before, and no doubt will be again. but i have never been defeated and never will be.''
dole, the kansas senator, had signaled for days that he was ready to bow to the inevitable
one thing you learn how to do pretty well in our business is to count,'' he said in his withdrawal announcement. ``you come to trust your instincts to tell you when it's over, and in my heart i know the time is now. ..
so i return to the senate as the republican leader ... ready to do all i can to elect republicans in november and doing all i can for our nominee, george bush.''
bush, in wisconsin, said he had telephoned dole to thank him for a ``very generous statement.'' he added, ``it's been a hard-fought campaign and i respect the tenacity of bob dole.''
pat robertson, in a statement distributed from his headquarters in chesapeake, va., praised dole as ``a magnificent competitor.'' the former television evangelist, with almost no delegate support, conceded ``it seems obvious'' that bush will be the nominee but said anew that he won't withdraw from the gop contest
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said there was no change in president reagan's policy of neutrality, despite dole's action
dole made his exit before an audience jammed into the senate caucus room, a historic room where john f. kennedy launched his presidential bid and site of the senate watergate hearings 15 years ago and the iran-contra hearings a year ago
surveying the crowd and hearing an effusive introduction by sen. strom thurmond, r-s.c., dole began by saying: ``maybe i ought to change this.''
his withdrawal came on the day of the primary in connecticut, one of several home states for bush where another dole loss was certain. dole had for a time hoped to hang on until next week's primary in wisconsin, but his outlook was hardly better there, and bush's delegate lead appeared insurmountable
dole's candidacy took off in iowa's caucuses, a farm state where he benefited from his rural roots in neighboring kansas. he won the lead-off delegate event, leaving bush stunned with a third place finish behind former television evangelist pat robertson
for almost a week dole looked like a good bet for the gop nomination. but his chances were frozen in new hampshire
he relied on a surge in popularity there built on his iowa success. however, in what he later conceded was a tactical mistake, he didn't counter tough bush television ads suggesting dole would raise taxes. new hampshire dealt him a loss from which he could not recover
dole's campaign was beset by internal divisions and vacillation. critics said it was a reflection of dole himself, calling him a consummate legislator but lacking in executive experience and unable to delegate authority
his campaign was in turmoil after his new hampshire loss, and the division between campaign manager bill brock and two conservative campaign consultants broke into the open. brock fired them in full view of reporters, ordering them off the campaign plane
dole's strategy for winning the white house was based primarily on winning the first two contests, and when he fell short in new hampshire his candidacy collapsed
he found himself far behind bush in the southern primaries on super tuesday three weeks later. unable to focus his energies on his best opportunities, he lost everywhere
dole couldn't turn the race around in illinois and was effectively out of the running
he campaigned last week in wisconsin, but public opinion polls indicated a 2-to-1 bush lead. by week's end, dole appeared to be weary of waging a campaign that was only going through the motions
i can read the numbers and i probably know what's happening,'' he said
we need to keep a republican in the white house. that's where i'm coming from,'' he said. ``and if it can't be me, it will be george bush.''
dole, the 1976 vice presidential nominee in gerald ford's losing re-election bid, ran for the presidential nomination in 1980. that quickly ended in failure as ronald reagan won
eight years later, dole was frustrated by a feeling that he still had to run against reagan. bush, reagan's loyal vice president, inherited many of the president's supporters despite dole's best efforts
i'm sort of running against the ghost of ronald reagan,'' dole said recently
dole attacked bush as lacking leadership qualities, as having a full resume but no real experience, and for involvement in the reagan administration's major disaster, the iran-contra affair
none of it stuck
dole tried repeatedly to stir resentment against bush and his patrician background. but dole's argument that he himself was ``one of us'' apparently won over only iowans
he was always dogged by a reputation for meanness, begun in the public's mind when he played the hatchet-man role on the 1976 ticket. although he tried to soften that persona, he sometimes revealed bitterness
the night of his new hampshire loss, he accused bush of ``lying'' about the dole record during a joint live television interview
fiery evangelist jimmy swaggart was ordered tuesday not to preach from the pulpit or his television show for at least a year while he is rehabilitated from ``moral failure'' that reportedly included paying a prostitute to pose nude
in announcing its decision, the assemblies of god elders disregarded a more lenient three-month suspension recommended by the church in louisiana. the national church included provisions for two years of rehabilitation and counseling to begin when swaggart has agreed to rehabilitation in writing
louisiana district officials refused comment, as did the jimmy swaggart worldwide ministries in baton rouge, la. but a spokesman said swaggart's ministry would have a statement wednesday
swaggart is the latest evangelist to be forced from the pulpit. his accuser, marvin gorman, was forced from the assemblies of god when he admitted to an immoral act with a woman. and jim and tammy bakker were forced from their ptl ministry in a scandal that included a sexual encounter between bakker and young female follower
it is hoped that jimmy swaggart will agree to this program of rehabilitation and that such program will be redemptive and restorative in the life and ministry of our brother,'' the rev. g. raymond carlson, the church's general superintendent, said in a statement
people approved by the church would supervise the rehabilitation, carlson said. he provided no other details
if he does not accept, then the executive presbytery would take action to dismiss him,'' carlson said at a news conference
under the terms of rehabilitation, swaggart would be barred from his pulpit for at least a year and would have to stop distributing videotaped services that have enabled him to build a worldwide congregation
he will not be in the pulpit and he would not participate in that kind of ministry _ he would not address his congregation, per se,'' carlson said at the news conference. ``i believe we are asking him to be absent from television ministry.''
church officials say swaggart confessed to them in detail but they have refused to make his transgression public. reports have linked him to a prostitute who says he paid her to pose naked
carlson said he called swaggart on tuesday to inform him of the church's decision, but the two did not discuss whether swaggart would accept rehabilitation
he thanked me,'' carlson said. ``he expressed thanks, and i had prayer with him over the telephone.''
swaggart has 30 days to appeal to the 13-member executive presbytery, which serves as a board of directors and which set the terms of rehabilitation
church spokeswoman juleen turnage said church elders, who have been grappling with the case since swaggart stepped down from his pulpit feb. 21, are unlikely to change their decision
the louisiana district had recommended that swaggart be barred from preaching for three months. national officials say every other assemblies minister who has confessed to moral failure has been barred from preaching for at least a year
the louisiana district refused requests from the executive presbytery to reconsider, and apparently also questioned the national leadership's authority to determine discipline
h. maurice lednicky, a general presbytor and president of the assemblies central bible college in springfield, said the question of authorities was the focus the presbytors meeting monday and tuesday
in the end, the 232-member general presbytory, an oversight body, decided that the executive presbytory had authority to discipline swaggart, said carlson, a member of the executive presbytery. the presbytors later endorsed, on a voice vote, the terms of rehabilitation
robert s. king, a member of the louisiana district council from lafayette, said he disagreed with the decision
i feel his (swaggart's) ministry is unique and much depends on it. i feel god has forgiven him, he has asked god and men to forgive him and we ought to forgive him. ought to restore him to the pulpit quickly,'' he said
but lednicky and other general presbytors in springfield said they supported the executive presbytery. ``i think it helps not only the ministers but the general public to feel that there is integrity,'' he said
frank martin, a general presbytor representing the tennessee district, said the decision ``showed mercy.''
after swaggart's tearful confession to an unspecified sin, debra murphree, who has a record of arrests on prostitution charges, said he paid her to pose naked in a hotel room
in a related development, the national religious broadcasters on friday recommended terminating swaggart's membership, the organization's executive director said tuesday. termination doesn't become final until approved by the group's board of directors, which meets next february
`if they can't show the code and the logo like the good housekeeping seal of approval on their programs it should affect their donations,'' said the rev. benjamin l. armstrong, executive director of the 1,400-member organization. inserts 2 grafs after 6th graf pvs, there was ... updating with missile attack, claim two iraqi jets downed. picks up 7th graf pvs, nuri nayef ... with minor editing to trim</note>
iraq accused iran on tuesday of using poison gas in its kurdistan offensive and threatened to attack iranian cities with chemical weapons
iran, which accused the iraqis of using chemical bombs in the same area last week, said revolutionary guards were moving deeper into iraq territory in the northern campaign
baghdad's official news agency said iraqi warplanes raided two ships off iran in the persian gulf overnight, but there was no independent confirmation. about 500 vessels have been attacked by both sides since the war began in september 1980
iranian rebel groups based in iraq, said to include women fighters for the first time, appeared to have pushed into the oil-rich khuzestan province of southwest iran, around the town of fakkeh
there was no independent confirmation of the operation by the national liberation army of iran but the iranians, who claimed monday the offensive was repulsed, said their warplanes bombed ``enemy forces'' tuesday in the fakkeh region
on monday the rebels said several thousand fighters with tanks moved into khuzestan in their biggest offensive yet. alireza jafer-zada, a spokesman in baghdad, claimed on tuesday they had killed or wounded thousands of iranian soldiers
tehran radio, monitored in nicosia, said iran fired two missiles tuesday into mandali, 70 miles northeast of baghdad. iraq did not report the attack
iran's official islamic republic news agency said nine civilians were killed in iraqi air raids on four western and southern iranian cities. tehran radio said iranian fighters shot down two iraqi warplanes in a dogfight. iraq denied it
nuri nayef, head of the iraqi news agency office in cairo, said tuesday an iraqi government spokesman told him the military ``might choose a number of large iranian cities to be the targets of chemical weapons as a deterrent and punitive measure.''
he said the spokesman, whom he did not identify, declared that iran used chemical weapons in kurdistan last week and iraq may respond in kind
iran says iraq dropped chemical bombs march 16-17 on halabja, dojaila and khormal, three kurdish towns in iraq captured by iranian troops in an offensive that began march 16. iran said 5,000 people were killed and 5,000 wounded
western correspondents taken to halabja by the iranians last week reported seeing hundreds of dead civilians unmarked by wounds
most of iraq's 3.5 million kurds live in the northeast. kurdish separatist guerrillas, now backed by iran, have been fighting iraqi governments for decades, and halabja was the scene of a kurdish rebellion last year
baghdad has not confirmed or denied employing chemical weapons, but the united nations has said four times since 1984 that iraq has used poison gas bombs or artillery shells
iran has accused the iraqis of more than 100 chemical attacks in that period
on saturday, iraq's ruling revolutionary command council said it had the right to defend itself ``with all available weapons.''
at the united nations in new york, iraq criticized a u.n. decision to send two experts to to investigate the iranian reports and urged that another team be sent to check on reports of murder and torture of iraqi prisoners of war in iran
iran said its warplanes were in action tuesday to support revolutionary guard units it claims have penetrated about 15 miles into the darbandikhan region of northeastern iraq since march 16
the iranians say the invasion force has killed or wounded nearly 13,500 iraqis, captured more than 5,000 and destroyed 225 tanks and armored vehicles
iraq has admitted losing territory in kurdistan but has given no details
if the iranian claim is confirmed, it would be iraq's worst military setback since iranian forces drove to within six miles of basra, the southern regional capital, early last year
the house narrowly rejected a bill tuesday that would have awarded the states title to abandoned shipwrecks of historic significance lying within their waters, a proposal strongly opposed by sport divers and some commercial salvage operators
the house defeated the measure, 263-139, which was five votes short of the two-thirds majority required for passage. the bill passed the senate by voice vote on dec. 19
opponents complained that the bill was brought to the floor under parliamentary ground rules usually adopted for abbreviated debate on non-controversial bills, with no amendments allowed
the bill's supporters, led by rep. charles e. bennett, d-fla., were expected to try to return the measure to the house floor under different rules which would allow opponents to introduce amendments and would require only a simple majority for passage
rep. norman d. shumway, r-calif., complained that under the bill, ``there is no legal, binding or enforceable way ... to ensure that the sport divers' right to dive on these wrecks, even for purely recreational purposes, will be protected by states.''
rep. e. clay shaw jr., r-fla., countered that ``its passage will go a long way toward preserving these archaeological treasures,'' although he agreed with shumway that the bill may discourage private exploration for undiscovered shipwrecks
without the bill, said rep. bruce vento, d-minn., dynamiting and other abuses by some reckless treasure hunters ``would absolutely guarantee for future generations that these shipwrecks, these valuable pieces of history, (would) be lost for all time.''
vento said guidelines to be published by the national park service under the bill would protect historic shipwrecks in state waters while permitting orderly access by sport divers, fishing enthusiasts and others
the bill would give states title to the estimated 5 percent to 10 percent of the shipwrecks in state waters that are considered historically important. all others having no historic interest, plus all shipwrecks lying beyond 3 miles offshore would be governed by federal admiralty law
admiralty law awards shipwrecks and cargoes to the finders and permits salvage operators to claim a major portion of the cargoes they raise
under the bill, admiralty law would not apply to the small number of historically significant shipwrecks in state waters, and indian tribes would have title to shipwrecks on their lands. the federal government would retain title to any abandoned wrecks on public lands
until now, both states and federal admiralty courts have claimed jurisdiction over abandoned historic shipwrecks in state waters
the submerged lands act of 1953 gave the states ownership of all natural resources and submerged lands up to 3 miles offshore but did not cover artificial objects such as shipwrecks on those lands
secretary of state george p. shultz failed on tuesday to persuade the arab league to support his proposal for mideast peace talks
but a spokesman for the 21-nation group, which also includes the palestine liberation organziation, said the reagan administration seemed to be more sensitive to the arab viewpoint
the 90-minute meeting at the state department was part of shultz's preparation for his trip to the region beginning sunday night. he will try to nudge israel and a mixed delegation of jordanians and palestinian arabs to open talks may 1
shultz met with syrian foreign minister farouk al-shara', algerian ambassador mohammad sahnoun, saudi arabian ambassador bandar bin sultan and other league representatives
the league spokesman, clovis maksoud, said they disagreed with shultz on several issues, including the league's demand for a seat at the negotiating table for the plo
we think the plo should be represented on an equal footing,'' maksoud said
shultz met saturday with two members of the palestine national council, the legislative arm of the plo. but state department spokesman charles e. redman said monday this did not conflict with the u.s. policy of not dealing with yasser arafat's organization
both the united states and israel consider the plo a terrorist group. shultz has demanded it recognize israel's right to exist and disavow terrorism as conditions for u.s. acceptance
maksoud said the league and shultz also disagreed on the scope of a peace conference on the middle east. the arabs want the united states, the soviet union and the three other permament members of the u.n. security council _ china, britain and france _ to play an active role in arab-israeli negotiations
shultz would restrict the conference to launching direct peace-making talks. the soviet union and china do not have diplomatic relations with israel and provide modern arms to syria and saudi arabia, respectively
i cannot say we reached any conclusive agreements,'' maksoud said
still, he said ``the secretary of state showed a measure of openness'' to the league's views. ``we found the united states perhaps more sensitive to some of our concepts.''
shultz has called for an israeli withdrawal from at least some of the west bank and gaza, which jordan and egypt lost in the 1967 six-day war. maksoud said the league wants the israeli-held territories evacuated completely
house speaker jim wright has filed amended financial disclosure statements covering the past seven years to list assets he held with a fort worth business partner, including stocks, real estate and ``precious and semi-precious stones.''
wright filed the disclosures, required by house reporting forms, after failing to do so since he and developer george a. mallick and their wives formed the venture, mallightco inc., in 1979. the name of the business is a combination of the two couples' last names
in the past, the texas democrat has listed the company on his disclosure forms with an aggregate value category, but never has detailed the underlying assets of the venture. in some cases, the total values given in the new forms conflict with those filed previously
an aide to wright, marshall lynam, said the speaker had been simply unaware of any requirement for disclosure of the corporation's assets until his attorneys told him about it last year while preparing to put the assets in a blind trust
the corporation's holdings at that time were detailed in the blind trust announcement, but the new disclosure filings are the first public record of the trust's holdings and activities for previous years
on march 18, wright filed amended reports with the house clerk's office detailing those holdings for the years 1980 through 1986. the speaker's office did not call attention to the filings, and the existence of the amended forms was disclosed tuesday by rep. newt gingrich, r-ga., who has harshly criticized wright for alleged ethical shortcomings
in each of the seven years, the amended forms show mallightco's total value at between $100,001 and $250,000. the forms require disclosure of values only in broad ranges, so it is impossible to tell precise amounts
in 1980, the first year in which mallightco appears on wright's disclosure statements, wright's one-half share of the company included savings accounts and ``fixed assets'' worth less than $5,000 each; stocks and bonds worth $50,000 to $100,000; and notes receivable owed by wright (under $5,000), his wife betty ($15,001 to $50,000) and marlene mallick ($15,001 to $50,000)
the stocks included tandy corporation, gulf oil, american quasar petroleum and first national bank of weatherford, valued at less than $5,000 each, and supron oil, delphi oil and western co. of north america, each valued at $15,001 to $50,000
the value of the venture's stock portfolio declined over the next three years as values dropped and some stocks apparently were sold. at the same time, wright's debt to the partnership climbed to the range of $15,001 to $50,000
in 1983, the disclosure form adds ``precious and semi-precious stones'' worth $15,001 to $50,000 to wright's share of the assets. also added to the assets list is a $5,001 to $15,000 note receivable from the mallick company
wright apparently paid off part of his debt to the business in 1985, and his debt dropped to the range of $5,001 to $15,000
in the final year for which an amendment was filed, 1986, the assets list is enlarged to include ``real estate near orlando, fla.,'' with a value in the range of $50,001 to $100,000
the total values for mallightco were increased in the amended forms for the years 1983 and 1984, when previous filings had put the value in the range of $50,001 to $100,000
mallick has figured in news reports about wright's efforts to get a federal grant for the renovation of fort worth's stockyards, a project in which mallick was involved. wright said he had been unaware of his associate's involvement when he was seeking the grant
after criticism about those financial dealings and others mounted last fall, wright put his assets in a blind trust and said he had instructed his attorneys to sell his interest in mallightco
wright's attorney, charles m. levy, put the total assets of the speaker and his wife at the time at $187,317, not counting their house in mclean, va., personal retirement funds and 57 acres of property in arkansas. robertson comment; adds 4 grafs on mccloskey's lawyers asking for court costs</note>
former rep. paul mccloskey jr. said tuesday he is considering suing pat robertson to recover $400,000 in legal fees he incurred when the republican presidential candidate sued him for libel
mccloskey said his lawyers believe they can be prove that robertson made frivolous use of the court system in suing mccloskey over his statements about robertson's korean war record
at a national press club luncheon, mccloskey repeated the story he has told for years about being in marine officer training school with robertson and then being shipped to korea in 1950. mccloskey contends that while he and others were sent off to combat, robertson ducked combat duty using the influence of his father, the late sen. a. willis robertson, d-va
mccloskey said he and others recall robertson boasting about how ``i'm going to call my daddy to get me out of this thing.''
robertson dropped his legal suit against mccloskey earlier this month, citing a trial opening set for march 8, the date of the critical super tuesday series of presidential primaries and caucuses in 20 states. he said the trial would force him to choose between his campaign and the legal case
however, mccloskey contended tuesday that robertson dropped the lawsuit because the evidence supporting the former california congressman's story was unbeatable
he said 21 former marines were ready to testify on his side and that letters from robertson's father supported his case
the evidence that robertson brought suit frivolously is in a letter written by robertson to a california politician in 1985 in which robertson said that mccloskey believed he was telling the truth but that his memory was faulty, the ex-congressman said
that would negate the veracity of a suit claiming mccloskey willfully lied about the former television evangelist's record, mccloskey said
now we have enough to sue him for misusing the legal process,'' he said
robertson, however, insisted he could have won the case
every testimony that was to be was already in the record. the record was closed. the record was complete. in the record, i won,'' robertson said at a news conference tuesday in chesapeake, va. ``unfortunately, the judge gave me a hobson's choice that i could not abide with.''
a federal judge dismissed the case on march 7 after robertston agreed to pay court costs, but not mccloskey's $400,000 in legal fees
u.s. district judge joyce hens green signed the order dismissing the case ``with prejudice,'' which means that mccloskey was legally the victor in the case
mccloskey's lawyers, meanwhile, asked robertson to pay $42,845 in court costs now that the libel suit has been dismissed
in a bill of court costs that was made public tuesday in u.s. district court, mccloskey's lawyer george lehner aksed for, among other things, $15,794 to cover the cost of taking depositions from witnesses and $19,458 for photocopying documents
lehner said this figure included $16,000 to make large-size trial exhibits of 30 to 35 documents
robertson's lawyer, douglas v. rigler, who has 11 days to file any opposition to the bill declined to say if he would make any objection. ``i would want to discuss that with my client, but just on first glance it looks extravagant.'' 4; corrects list thruout to show ties in 14th, 20th, 26th, 46th, 52nd, 56th, 63rd, 68th and 79th places, and to correct order of items 70 to 73. no pickup.</note>
