m.s. ``bud'' rukeyser, nbc's executive vice president for communications, said tuesday he is leaving the network to go into business for himself, giving ``advice and counsel to media companies.''
rukeyser, 56, has been at nbc for 30 years, the last 15 as the network's chief spokesman
for 15 years, i've been whispering in the ears of four different chief executive officers. i thought if i was ever going to do something else, try something on my own, it was going to have to be now or never,'' rukeyser said
he said nbc president robert c. wright reacted to the news by saying nbc would be rukeyser's first client
asked if he would be working with his former boss grant tinker, now head of gtg entertainment, rukeyser said he had had no such discussions with tinker, but added, ``i certainly would hope so.''
betty hudson, now head of publicity for nbc, will become spokeswoman for the network, rukeyser said
rep. richard gephardt said tuesday he regretted not doing better in the democratic presidential race but was determined to work in congress toward the same goals of his campaign for the white house
reflecting on his failed white house bid after filing for re-election to his st. louis congressional seat, gephardt said he knew his campaign was in trouble march 8 when he lost 19 super tuesday states and won only missouri
super tuesday was the hard night because that was when you really knew you were on the ropes,'' gephardt said. but he added there was a positive side to being out of the race
there's always a bittersweet in everything in life. we're disappointed, and yes, we wanted t  the 47-year-old congressman said he was somewhat relieved he and his wife ando do this.''   their three young children would not be thrust into the public life of a president's family
we couldn't go to a movie or a drugstore without an entourage,'' gephardt said. ``their lives would never be the same (because of) my choices, my success. so now we can go to the drugstore and the movies and be fairly normal.''
gephardt repeated words he had said monday in washington when he formally withdrew from the race and called himself ``the luckiest guy in thefuel-tax exemption for farmers
the senate finance committee agreed tuesday to grant a fuel-tax exemption for farmers and other off-the-road diesel users on april 1 and to make corporations foot the bill
however, the future of the proposed relief remained in doubt because the house ways and means committee, which must originate tax bills, has scheduled no action on the diesel proposal. backers of the legislation are holding out hope that the house panel will approve a bill this week before adjourning for easter week
farmers, fishermen and others who use diesel for off-the-road business purposes traditionally have been exempt from the tax, which finances highway construction. but under a 1987 law aimed at preventing cheating, they must begin paying the tax on april 1 and then apply for a refund when they file their income-tax returns next year
the finance committee voted last week to grant these users relief from paying the tax at all but, because of budget restrictions, it acted to provide the exemption on oct. 1. at the direction of the committee, sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, the chairman, introduced an amendment tuesday that steps up the relief to april 1
the committee is getting around the budget problem by tightening collections of corporate taxes. this would cost corporations an extra $508 million from 1988 through 1993, with the bulk of the additional money coming from expedited collections this year and next
under the change, a corporation that shifts its method of calculating estimated taxes from one quarter to the next would have to make up in the subsequent quarter 96 percent of the reduction achieved in the previous period. this change would be phased in over two years
providing the diesel-tax relief for off-road users will cost about $615 million during the same six-year period. another part of the package is a ``taxpayer bill of rights'' aimed at reducing internal revenue service powers in some disputes with taxpayers. these changes would cost about $517 million through 1993
other provisions would double the gas-guzzler tax on inefficient cars, mainly expensive imports, and limit the abilities of distilleries to dodge part of the whisky tax through what is known as a wine credit
the net revenue effect of the package would be to raise taxes by $104 million over six years
tom king, britain's minister for northern ireland, met tuesday with leaders of the main roman catholic political party in an effort to resolve a political stalemate in the troubled province
king and leaders of the social democratic and labor party (sdlp) conferred for about two hours on the political situation and new surge of sectarian violence in northern ireland
sdlp leader john hume said after the meeting, ``we are ready to sit down and talk with anyone,'' including the ulster unionists who represent the protestant majority
hume said the negotiations would have to be about ``how we solve the problem in our society'' rather than who wins power. ``we believe we should be talking face to face with the unionists. the sooner we get there the better,'' he added
hume recently met with gerry adams, leader of sinn fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed irish republican army. the unionists denounced that meeting, saying the sdlp was giving credibility to terrorists
the predominantly catholic ira has been waging a violent campaign since 1969 to unite northern ireland, where protestants outnumer catholic 3-2, with the overwhelmingly catholic republic of ireland
five people have died this month in murderous rampages at two ira funerals. the killings climaxed two weeks of rising tension after british commandos shot dead three unarmed ira guerrillas in gibraltar
hume said his delegation told king of their party's desire to see all factions work together to create stability in the british province, where more than 2,600 people have been killed in sectarian violence since 1969
a british government statement said the meeting ``had been arranged to consider the possiblity of moving to a wider dialogue, involving the constitutional parties, about the future government of northern ireland.''
the british broadcasting corporation reported king and the party leaders discussed setting up of some form of power-sharing administration involving protestants and catholics
hume said his talks with adams were not mentioned at the meeting with king
the hume-adams talks had drawn speculation of a possible temporary cease-fire. but irish nationalists insisted the ira had no intention of halting its campaign and hume told independent television news he was only interested in discussing a permanent truce
sen. albert gore jr. said tuesday that jesse jackson has a ``complete and total lack'' of experience to be president and criticized what he said was jackson's ``notion that there's a moral equivalence between israel and the plo.''
he also said of jackson, an ordained minister known for his ringing speeches, ``we're not choosing a preacher; we're choosing a president.''
jackson, campaigning in east harlem when told of gore's remarks, said, ``the senator should not discriminate against someone because they are a preacher, a priest or a rabbi.''
i assume that he is stimulated by his own status in the campaign to attack me. i am stimulated to keep hope alive,'' jackson said
addressing jewish audiences in new york, gore also criticized another democratic presidential rival, michael dukakis, for ``naive legalism'' in his approach to foreign policy and ``an exaggerated faith in the united nations.''
gore said he was dismayed by jackson's ``embrace of'' palestine liberation organization leader yasser arafat and cuban leader fidel castro
venturing where other democratic candidates have feared to tread, gore sharply criticized jackson's foreign policy views and contrasted his own experience and beliefs with those of the civil rights activist
other democratic candidates have shied away from attacks on jackson, apparently assuming he won't win the nomination and wanting to pick up his supporters. but there had been speculation that that would change after jackson's victory in last week's michigan caucuses solidified his position in the forefront of the democratic race
gore credited jackson with having ``energized millions of voters'' and having offered ideas on drugs and the economy
but i part company with him over his opposition to such mainstays of our national defense as the f-15 and the cruise missile,'' gore said. ``i categorically reject his notion that there's a moral equivalence between israel and the plo. and i am dismayed by his embrace of arafat and castro.''
as for dukakis, gore pointed to his disagreement with the massachusetts governor over a recent letter signed by 30 senate members. gore said he was asked and declined to sign the letter, which disagreed with israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir's opposition to exchanging occupied land for recognition by arab states. dukakis, he noted, said he would have signed the letter
gore, in appearances before a civic group and a coalition of jewish organizations, said the democratic race was far from over and that jackson's sudden ascendancy could be as fleeting as gary hart's had been
when gary hart got back into the race and he rocketed to the top of the polls, a lot of people expressed a sense of panic,'' gore told reporters at a breakfast of the association for a better new york. ``this race changes from day to day.''
later, answering questions after a speech to the conference of presidents of major american jewish organizations, gore said he hasn't been afraid to criticize jackson
i have sharp disagreements with jesse jackson,'' the tennessee senator said. ``i (have) talked about his complete and total lack of experience in the national government. he hasn't served a single day in the national government, or had a single day's experience in foreign policy
he has said, `i'm a tree shaker, not a jelly maker.' well, some jelly has to be made in the white house, so to speak. if you need brain surgery, you're going to want to know if the surgeon has gone to medical school or has had experience practicing that particular line of work
we need a president who is prepared to tackle some of the toughest problems we have ever had in our foreign policy and our domestic policy, and we need a president who has the experience to do that job well.''
gore was applauded for his criticism of jackson
in his speech to the jewish group, gore contrasted his support of israel with jackson's recognition of the palestine liberation organization. he also said he was ``deeply troubled'' by a report of chinese weapons sales to saudi arabia and urged steps by the united states to discourage such trade
the tennessean said the new york primary on april 19 would be a critical test of his candidacy, but he did not say he had to win it _ only ``do extremely well.''
new york will send 255 delegates to the democratic national convention
reporters were allowed into the chinese legislature's small group meetings for the first time tuesday, but saw a limited amount of the free and lively discussion that has been ballyhooed by the official news media
in the tibetan room of the great hall of the people, seat of china's government, 19 delegates from tibet gathered for what was supposed to be an example of democracy at work
foreign and chinese reporters crowded the room in anticipation of observing delegates engaged in a free exchange of ideas
but many soon left as one delegate after another to the national people's congress read lengthy, prepared speeches, praising economic reform and china's open-door policy and calling for unity and perseverence in the ``great work of socialist construction.''
western reporters who attended other provincial discussion groups said the action was a little livelier as delegates interrupted each other to add remarks or to disagree
the reporters said they were surprised that their presence seemed not to deter delegates from criticizing the implementation of policies in their areas
but most speakers prefaced critical remarks by saying they agreed with china's policies of reform and with the report presented by acting premier li peng at friday's opening session of the congress
china has given lavish publicity to what it says is the increasingly democratic nature of its government. for the first time this year, there were more candidates than seats in elections for local people's congresses
the media portrayed the small group discussions as being the heart of the democratic exercise. the national tv evening news for two days has devoted nearly half its domestic news to showing delegates in animated exchanges
but in the tibetan room, 20 minutes passed before the first delegate spoke out of turn, and then it was to support his colleague's statements
at the 2{-hour meeting, delegates were seldom interrupted and no one expressed disagreement or a differing viewpoint
most delegates seemed disinterested, smoking absently and staring into space. through much of the session, the panchen lama, tibetan buddhism's second-highest leader and a vice chairman of the national people's congress, carried on a private conversation with his neighbor ngapoi ngawang jigme, chairman of the tibetan people's congress
western reporters said delegates in other groups took a more active role in discussions. ``there was a certain amount of give and take,'' one reporter said
in the liaoning province group, a rural school teacher found fault with government education policy and delegates frequently interrupted one another to disagree
the tibetan delegates and those representing china's other minorities used the discussion groups to cite what they said was the lower standard of living in many minority regions and to say they wanted more favorable minority policies. 4,000 palestinians in detention centers; edits thereafter to tighten.</note>
israel's army isolated the occupied territories tuesday, but palestinians threw gasoline bombs at patrolling soldiers and the israelis opened fire and wounded eight of the demonstrators
the unprecedented crackdown on the 1.5 million arabs in the occupied west bank and gaza strip was aimed at halting four months of unrest and at preventing mass demonstrations by palestinians on wednesday's 12th anniversary of land day, when israeli soldiers killed six arabs protesting land confiscation
foreign relief workers were barred from entering the occupied lands. thousands of police were mobilized tuesday evening to enforce curfews in arab towns in israel
arabs reported that demonstrators took to the streets in some areas, throwing rocks and gasoline bombs, and that israeli troops fired at the curfew violators. the eight arabs were wounded in the village of zaita, 40 miles northwest of jerusalem, the army and the palestine press service reported
among the protesters reported wounded was 13-year-old girl
in ramallah, small children tossed rocks at each other in the streets. they called the game ``jews and arabs.''
hundreds of protesters have been wounded since riots began dec. 8 in the west bank and gaza, which israel captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war. the death toll stands at 119 palestinians and one israeli soldier, according to u.n. figures
defense minister yitzhak rabin and lt. gen. dan shomron, israel's military chief of staff, threatened for the first time tuesday to close the territories for an extended period
for now, the decision to close the areas is for three days,'' rabin said on israel radio. ``but i've always said we have to adjust our measures to confront every eventuality.''
in an israel television interview, rabin said more than 4,000 palestinians arrested in the months of violence are being held at army detention centers. he said that number included prisoners served with administrative detention orders
closing the occupied lands is intended to quell the violence by imposing collective punishment on palestinians and to keep out journalists, whose reports the israelis claim feed the rebellion
although general access for journalists has been withdrawn, u.s. television pools were allowed into the west bank and gaza on tuesday and some individual journalists managed to get past roadblocks
particularly harsh restrictions have been put on the gaza strip. the rebellion began there and the 6-mile-long mediterranean coastal area is easier to isolate
no human beings are on the streets,'' said rashad al shawaa, who was deposed by israel as mayor of gaza city in 1983. ``it's like a cemetery. the army announced over loudspeakers: `anyone who leaves their home will be shot'.''
he told the associated press by telephone he saw soldiers fire on a few palestinians who went out in his neighborhood
shawaa said the telephone call was the first he had received in 26 hours. telephone service to gaza was cut monday and it mostly remained out tuesday night
bernard mills, the u.n. relief and works agency director in gaza, told u.n. officials by radio: ``you have 650,000 people under house arrest.''
unrwa cares for palestinian refugees in the territories. about 650,000 palestinians live in the gaza strip and 850,000 in the west bank
foreign journalists asked the supreme court to overturn the order banning them from the territories, the first in more than 20 years of israeli occupation
robert slater, president of the foreign press association, said it refused army offers of news pools, but u.s. television network pools went into gaza and the west bank with an army escort
israel radio said the army made mass roundups of palestinians as soon as the territories were closed, arresting 600
according to the arab-run palestine press service, 120 were jailed under special powers permitting six months of detention without trial. the army confirmed making mass arrests, but did not give numbers
at west bank roadblocks, troops turned away a u.n. official and save the children director chris george despite an army announcement that the closure would not affect international relief workers. the army refused comment
both organizations said they would protest. ``it's a full-time job now to raise our complaints with the israeli authorities,'' said u.n. spokesman bill lee
george said half the 10 people on his agency's jerusalem staff were denied entry to the city
an ap reporter saw soldiers force merchants in ramallah to close their shops and confiscate the identity cards of some. the aim was to break the authority of the palestine liberation organization, which ordered arabs to open their stores for three hours daily
we won't allow another body to run things,'' military government coordinator shmuel goren said on israel television
israeli troops forcibly closed major west bank markets in jericho, nablus, jenin and ramallah, as well as in gaza city, said mona rishmawi of law in the service of man, a human rights group founded by palestinian lawyers
said kenaan, a nablus businessman, said by telephone that the army kept food trucks out of the city and, ``when stores tried to open, troops threw food on the ground and destroyed it. i saw it myself.''
the supreme court on tuesday granted a stay of execution to john henry selvage, who had been scheduled to die in texas after midnight
by a 6-3 vote, the justices granted the stay pending action by the court on a formal appeal by selvage
the dissenters were chief justice william h. renquist and justices byron r. white and sandra day o'conner. `soviet officials' and edits below to conform and trim</note>
workers stayed home again tuesday in a region of the caucasus whose armenian majority is trying to force the soviet bureaucracy to reverse a decision it made about local rule 65 years ago
my report today will be short,'' izvestia correspondent p. gutiontov wrote from stepanakert, the largest city of the disputed nagorno-karabakh region. ``city enterprises are at standstill, people are home.''
about 75 percent of nagorno-karabakh's 157,000 people are ethnic armenians, but the kremlin assigned it to neighboring azerbaijan in 1923. most armenians are christians. azeris, the indigenous people of azerbaijan, are predominantly moslem
izvestia, the government newspaper, also gave the first breakdown of armenian and azeri casualties in feb. 28 rioting in the city of sumgait in azerbaijan, and denied reports that children were killed
a curfew was imposed on sumgait after the riots but pravda, the communist party daily, said it was lifted tuesday because ``life in the city ... has returned to normal.''
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov told a news briefing some workers in stepanakert stayed home and ``certain enterprises are not functioning or are partially not functioning.''
telephone calls to stepanakert from moscow did not go through or were cut off
izvestia also reported monday that residents of stepanakert stayed home. dissident sources say the strike began last week, but their reports could not be confirmed
soviet officials, who have announced a costly program to improve social and economic conditions in nagorno-karabakh, will not bend to pressure from activists to allow armenia to annex the region, gerasimov said
we believe that problems have to be solved ... on the basis of realism and without undue emotion,'' gerasimov said. ``one cannot solve these complex problems with demonstrations only.''
we cannot solve the problem by mechanically transferring this region as some armenian officials want,'' he said. ``the more you study this problem the more you will see the whole thing is not as simple as that, as merely saying nagorno-karabakh must be part of armenia.''
gerasimov said the situation had improved but not enough for the government to allow foreign journalists to travel there
sporadic strikes and protests have been reported in nagorno-karabakh since feb. 13. the latest labor trouble is said to have begun last wednesday
izvestia quoted investigators as confirming the previously announced death toll of 32 in the sumgait riot. it said 26 of them were armenians and six were from azerbaijan. previously, officials had said the 32 dead were of various nationalities, and that the rioting was not necessarily an ethnic dispute
armenian activists had claimed the death toll was much higher and that most of the dead were armenians
it has been firmly established with evidence that during the disorder in sumgait not one child suffered,'' izvestia quoted investigators as saying. ``there were not 400 or 500 deaths, but exactly 32 people, as said in a published statement by the soviet prosecutor. included in these 32 were 26 armenians and six azerbaijanis.''
armenian activists have claimed that small children were thrown from the windows of maternity hospitals during the riot
izvestia said the strike would not help stepanakert residents, and accused activists of lack of concern for the region's welfare
its article tuesday and a report it published monday were part of a new, more detailed look at the nagorno-karabakh dispute
soviet media are being encouraged under communist party chief mikhail s. gorbachev's policy of glasnost to be more open about social problems, but initial reports on the nagorno-karabakh dispute were slow in coming and lacked detail
sovietskaya kultura said tuesday the government's plan for nagorno-karabakh would cost about $640 million
these millions, which are so necessary now for restructuring, the country is giving to karabakh,'' it said in a front-page article tracing the unrest to poor social and economic conditions
moscow dissident tamara grigoryants said police broke up a demonstration monday evening in yerevan, capital of soviet armenia, by more than 50 people demanding freedom for jailed armenian activist paryur arikyan
she said they carried saying, ``we don't believe in perestroika,'' a reference to gorbachev's effort to restructure soviet society. ...'' to update with final passage; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``the panel ...''</note>
the house armed services committee voted deep cuts tuesday in president reagan's request for star wars anti-missile spending and his plan to put multiple-warhead mx missiles on western railroads
the decision came shortly before the democratic-controlled panel voted 48-4 approval of a bill authorizing the pentagon to spend $299 billion in the fiscal year starting oct. 1
the overall pentagon budget had been set in december during negotiations between the white house and congress over a budget deficit reduction package
the panel slashed to $3.7 billion reagan's request for $4.5 billion in star wars funds
the panel also voted to approve $500 million for research into putting the mx aboard trains, $300 million less than reagan had sought. at the same time, the panel increased reagan's request for spending on the single-warhead midgetman missile from $200 million to $500 million
as it worked on the bill, the committee also:
_voted 43-8 to spend $1.4 billion for a new trident submarine instead of using the money for two more aegis-class destroyers. that vote reversed a decision last week by the seapower subcommittee
_voted 46-6 to permit the united states to sell aegis-class destroyers to japan, as long as reagan certifies that the system is protected against espionage. aegis is the navy's secret, high-tech defense system for ships and the administration is considering selling four of the $1.2 billion ships to japan
the star wars decision confirmed the budget choice made last week by the armed services research and development subcommittee, and will result in a deep reduction from original plans. the $3.7 billion figure would mean that star wars spending next year would remain at about the current level
last year, pentagon budget plans called for seeking $6.2 billion in star wars money for fiscal 1989, but that was reduced to the $4.5 billion level by defense secretary frank c. carlucci as part of a package of reductions he ordered in response to a white house-congressional agreement in december that set next year's defense budget at $299 billion
that agreement has calmed the congressional debate about defense spending, but opened new fights about how to best allocate the overall total
the $3.7 billion figure for the strategic defense initiative, as star wars is known formally, was approved tuesday after the committee was unable to agree on four other proposed sdi amounts ranging from $3.1 billion up to the full $4.5 billion figure
the committee later voted to overturn a decision by the research and development subcommittee which had halved the pentagon's sdi budget request for research into an interceptor rocket that would be used to slam into soviet nuclear missiles at high speed to destroy them
known as the space-based interceptor, the program is consuming an increasingly large share of the pentagon's sdi budget. plans next year call for spending $330 million on that program, but the subcommittee had cut that in half because of fears that the technology is not as promising as other weapons that could be part of a defensive shield
the dispute over the midgetman and the mx involves a pair of nuclear weapons that have been central to a seven-year-old fight over reagan's plans for building up america's nuclear arsenal
congress has approved building 50 of the mx weapons for deployment in land-based silos, but the pentagon is now seeking 50 more of the weapons and plans call for putting the second 50 aboard trains. meantime, the pentagon has been lukewarm toward the midgetman, a weapon that has been a favorite of congressional critics of the mx
carlucci told congress last month that he thought the midgetman should be eliminated, but said he had included $200 million at the request of congress so the program could be kept alive until reagan's successor makes a decision next year
meantime, carlucci said $800 million should be spent for research into the rail-based version of the 10-warhead mx
the research and development subcommittee said last week that each weapon should be given $500 million and that subcommittee decision was ratified tuesday after several unsuccessful attempts to change it
three bombs exploded within minutes of each other tuesday in three movie houses, spreading panic in the downtown cinema district and injuring two federal policemen and two other people, officials said
the officers were trying to deactivate one bomb when it exploded in the second row of the normandie theater on lavalle street. bombs also hit the nearby atlas lavalle and sarmiento theaters, police said
a bomb was found at a fourth theater but experts defused it. three other movie houses received telephoned bomb threats but searches turned up nothing, police said
the explosions caused panic along the street, which is reserved for pedestrians only, federal police chief juan angel pirker said. theaters and businesses emptied. ticket-takers ran into the street shouting for ambulances
leaflets scattered at one bombing site read ``o.a.s.-m.r.p.,'' initials of a group that claimed responsibility for most of the 18 bombings and bomb attempts in argentina this year. it is not known what the initials stand for
hurt the worst in tuesday's bombings was a police inspector who had one hand blown off, officials at churruca hospital said. the other policeman also was badly hurt, they said
the officials spoke on condition of anonymity
two movie-goers, a man and a woman, were injured while watching ``the last emperor'' at the atlas lavalle, police said. the bomb exploded near the front of the theater, where about 250 people were seated
they (the bombers) placed the explosive devices in sites where they knew there were going to be civilians injured,'' said pirker
similar o.a.s.-m.r.p. leaflets were scattered earlier this month at the site of bombings in a downtown apartment building and a roman catholic church. some reports suggest the bombings stem from a rightist terrorist group linked to rebel leader aldo rico, a former lieutenant colonel
last year, rico led a brief easter week uprising at three army camps. the mutineers demanded an end to prosecution of officers accused of human rights abuses during the 1976-83 military regime
rico and other leaders of that rebellion and a similar one in january are held at magdalena military prison, 60 miles south of buenos aires
the supreme court meanwhile ordered freed four admirals accused of human rights abuses under the military regime at the naval mechanics school, a notorious detention center in northern buenos aires
the court ruled the four were among about 270 officers with the rank of brigadier general or below who could benefit from last year's ``due obedience'' law passed by congress. the law says only top-ranked officers who ordered human rights crimes now face prosecution, not those of lower rank who obeyed orders
at least 9,000 people vanished during the military regime's ``dirty war'' against suspected leftists, the government says
raul alfonsin was elected president in 1983, ending the military's nearly eight-year rule. editing ton conform. picks up penultimate graf, `on monday...'.</note>
a convicted killer scheduled five times to die for murdering a sheriff's deputy won another last-minute reprieve tuesday by a 6-3 vote of the u.s. supreme court, which has heard but not decided a similar case
attorneys for john henry selvage filed an appeal with the high court a day after an appeals court monday vacated a stay granted by a federal judge
selvage was sentenced to die for the shooting death of harris county sheriff's deputy albert garza, who was killed july 30, 1979 _ his 48th birthday. garza was trying to prevent a houston jewelry store robbery but had not drawn his gun
the appeal covered several issues, but selvage's strongest case for a reprieve stemmed from his use of the same argument the supreme court heard march 1 in texas inmate donald gene franklin's case, said attorney david cunningham
franklin's attorney argued that texas' capital punishment law keeps jurors from giving full consideration to ``mitigating circumstances'' suggesting life in prison as more appropriate than the death penalty
the supreme court granted a stay of execution to the 37-year-old selvage after he was moved from death row at the ellis i unit outside huntsville to a cell near the death chamber at the walls unit in huntsville, texas department of corrections spokesman charles brown said
by a 6-3 vote, the justices granted the stay pending action by the court on a formal appeal by selvage. the dissenters were chief justice william h. renquist and justices byron r. white and sandra day o'conner
in february, another texas inmate, calvin williams, won a stay from the supreme court about 90 minutes before he was to be executed. he used the same argument as in the franklin case, which the supreme court has not yet decided
the scheduling of selvage's execution on wednesday, shortly after midnight, marked the fifth time selvage faced lethal injection. each time he won stays
on monday, the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals in new orleans vacated the stay granted to selvage on friday by u.s. district judge norman black of houston
the texas attorney general's office argued that black should not have granted a reprieve because the appellate court is reconsidering the appeal of another death row inmate from harris county, leon rutherford king, who like selvage questioned the selection of jurors during his trial
vice president george bush won the connecticut primary tuesday night and moved virtually uncontested toward the 1988 republican presidential nomination. his major opponent, sen. bob dole, withdrew from the race earlier in the day. 0476</first> ...'' and adds 2 grafs at end to update with vaughn comment.</note>
teachers' unions are ``standing in the hallways and blocking up the doors of reform'' in places like chicago with troubled public schools, secretary of education william j. bennett said tuesday
bennett, who has said chicago schools are in an ``education meltdown,'' toured two public schools there last wednesday at the invitation of jacqueline vaughn, president of the chicago teachers union
bennett said afterwards that ``two schools do not a system make. facts remain facts, and the evidence suggests very serious problems.''
mrs. vaughn responded that ``what stalls education reform are not teachers or teachers' unions, but the cutbacks in funds from his administration
mr. bennett appears to have a personal vendetta against our union, because every time we challenge him to produce the so-called facts he throws around, he insults us,'' she continued
in an interview with the associated press on tuesday, bennett said teachers' unions have been an impediment to school reform in some places
he said the american federation of teachers has been more open to accountability and choice than its larger rival, the national education association, but he said aft affiliates like the one in chicago ``can be as intransigent and mindless as the nea.''
we sat there together in a press conference and i said, `why don't you admit what everybody knows, which is there are a lot of teachers ... who have no business in being in classrooms?''' bennett said
he said vaughn replied, ``we don't think there's such a thing as an incompetent teacher. there's only a teacher in need of assistance or help, a sabbatical or something.''
bennett called that ``just utter nonsense or drivel. but that's the party line.''
i was struck and kind of put off by the party line,'' he said. ``every time i met with the chicago teachers union, every time they appeared, they appeared as a committee, and there were five or six of them, and they would say these things which are obviously the approved way of speaking. it was kind of scary.''
they're standing in the hallways and blocking up the doors of reform, as is the bureaucracy there. it's an urban school situation and the children are suffering,'' he said
bennett added that the ``intransigence of special interests'' such as teacher unions remains the biggest obstacle toward improved schools
mrs. vaughn said bennett's comments show he is ``uninterested in fair and objective appraisals. every system has good and bad in it, but he seems to like to single out ours.''
she also said the chicago union had a history of proposing innovative reforms. 1 graf after 8th pvs, bgng: once i, to include second interview with fried saying his departure not the only outcome of his deliberations</note>
solicitor general charles fried said tuesday the resignations of two top-level colleagues at the justice department are leading him to reconsider his future in the reagan administration
this development implicates every sort of question,'' fried said in the second of two interviews with the associated press. ``the possibilities include my departure, or that this is just a tempest in a teapot or many other things as well.''
fried, who represents the government in the supreme court, said he learned about the resignations on monday, the day before attorney general edwin meese was told
i got a heads-up, a courtesy call to let me know in advance,'' fried said of the departures
deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william weld, who heads the department's criminal division, announced their resignations tuesday. two personal assistants to each man also quit
told that acquaintances had said he might join the pair in leaving, fried replied, ``they seem to know my mind better than i do.''
he said he was home with the flu on tuesday and had a supreme court argument scheduled wednesday morning
i want to get through tomorrow and then i've got to think it through,'' fried said. ``i don't know the significance of these departures
once i get through tomorrow, i plan to think it through,'' he said in the first interview
fried, after the initial interview, called back to stress that his departure was by no means the only possible outcome of his deliberations
the 53-year-old former harvard law school professor became solicitor general in late 1985, succeeding rex lee
fried has been closely aligned with conservative legal theorists who have risen to power under meese
but one source familiar with events leading to the resignations said fried had been working with burns on naming james m. spears to head the civil division earlier this month when they were surprised to learn in a newspaper that meese's ultra-conservative counselor william bradford reynolds engineered the selection of another department offcial, john bolton, for the post
the resignations came amid a year-old criminal investigation of meese but there was nothing to link them directly to any new developments in that probe, department sources said
one source said the precipitating factor at this time was an internal fight over the successor to stephen trott as associate attorney general, the department's no. 3 post
burns unsuccessfully supported weld for this post, according to this source. weld was unwilling to stay when he was passed over for the promotion, in part because his two predecessors as criminal division chiefs, lowell jensen and trott, both had won the same promotion
this source said weld believed he was being punished for disagreeing on legal issues with meese and his top aides
burns was angered to learn that reynolds has gotten meese's private approval to name as associate attorney general frank keating, the assistant treasury secretary who supervises the customs service and the bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms
another department source said, however, these fights might not have had so much significance were meese not under the cloud of a continuing criminal investigation. material</note>
the senate foreign relations committee voted 12-6 tuesday to approve a measure intended to bar future presidents from changing the current u.s. view of the meaning of the medium-range missile treaty with the soviet union
rep. daniel evans, r-wash., called the action ``a gratuitous slap'' at president reagan and said it might cause him and other gop treaty supporters to vote against the pact
in a separate development, sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the foreign relations panel, said another treaty problem has been solved with administration assurances that the pact does ban medium-range weapons based on such futuristic or exotic technology as laser rays and particle beam generators
the senate armed services committee had identified the issue of futristic weapons as one which had to be fully settled before the full senate acted on the pact
earlier tuesday, the senate met in unusual secret session to review conflicting intelligence estimates on the size of the soviet medium-range ss-20 missile force
but conservatives who called for the meeting to air claims that the soviets are hiding a large force of ss-20s, said few if any minds had been changed about the merits of the new treaty eliminating such nuclear weapons
the partisan dispute in the foreign relations committee over the meaning of treaty language stems from the controversy that developed after the reagan administration asserted in 1986 that a new reading of the negotiating record of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile or abm treaty permitted the deployment of a ``star wars'' strategic defense system despite the widely held view that the pact banned ``exotic'' missile-defense systems
the democratic sponsors of the language added by the committee to the treaty said it would block future presidents from changing the meaning of the pact on grounds that the senate had not been fully informed about the contents of the negotiating record or had otherwise been misled
sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., an outspoken opponent of the inf pact, unexpectedly voted for the measure after sen. alan cranston, d-calif., agreed to add language stating that a commonly accepted treaty interpretation cannot be changed except by the senate's ratification of a subsequent treaty or by enactment of a law by both houses of congress
sen. richard lugar, r-ind., told reporters later he believed helms acted out of a ``devious'' strategy intended to prolong the dispute and perhaps to torpedo the treaty itself
helms denied that saying that in its previous form the measure had been unconstitutional
lugar also accused the democratic sponsors of the proposal of ``a deliberate bid to embarrass the president,'' adding it is certain to cause a fierce fight on the senate floor
evans told reporters: ``i think this has made it a partisan situation. it's a gratuitous slap at the president.''
no one has worked harder for this treaty than me,'' evans said. ``but now i'm going to seriously take a look as to whether i will vote for it on the floor.''
the secret session, the first held by the senate since october 1986, was convened to discuss allegations the soviets may try to hide a covert force of more than 300 ss-20 medium-range missiles after the treaty banning such weapons goes into effect
i think they heard some things they hadn't heard before,'' said sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., who has long pursued the theory that the soviet ss-20 force is far larger than the 650 missiles the soviets declare they have
but sen. steven symms, r-idaho, told reporters: ``i would be surprised if any minds were changed.''
i don't know if it changed any minds,'' said sen. malcolm wallop, r-wyo., when asked to describe the three-hour secret session held for security reasons in the old senate chamber, last used on a regular basis in 1859
the treaty has a political life which is in large part independent of its own terms,'' wallop said, adding that many senators fear explosive political results inside the north atlantic treaty organization were the treaty to be denied senate ratification
the inadequacies of this treaty are probably tolerable for a majority who feel that the political consequences in europe far outweigh concern about the failures and weaknesses in the treaty,'' wallop said
symms said he doubts if more than a dozen or so senators will vote against the inf pact
but symms, wallop and other conservatives said the debate over the medium-range missile treaty has set the stage for a far more divisive and uncertain battle over a treaty making deep reduction in intercontionental nuclear arms
inf is the appetizer for the main course, the start treaty,'' symms said
start, an acronym for strategic arms limitation talks, would be far more significant militarily and provide far more incentive for the soviets to cheat, symms contended
the senate foreign relations committee is scheduled to vote wednesday on whether to send the medium-range missile pact to the full senate
the senate armed services committee voted 18-2 on monday to recommend the treaty be approved
but in doing so it ignited a new controversy, declaring it was not clear from the text of the treaty or the negotiating record whether the accord covers futuristic, high-technology weapons such as those using laser rays or particle beam generators. excerpts sted statements were read, update with gates was taken into custody, add possible parole time. picks up 10th graf pvs, `the judge...'.</note>
a judge on tuesday sentenced an ex-conrail engineer to five years in prison for driving three locomotives into the path of a passenger train, killing 16 people in amtrak's worst accident
although rick l. gates, 33, of essex, md., admitted smoking marijuana on the train before the jan. 4, 1987 wreck, baltimore county circuit judge joseph p. murphy said he did not believe the engineer was under the influence of the drug
but what he did in terms of failure to follow procedures was to show us that he didn't give a damn. he just didn't care,'' the judge said
gates pleaded guilty feb. 16 to a single misdemeanor manslaughter count and admitted in a statement of facts to failing to make several safety checks that might have prevented the accident
i would like you to know i accept full responsibility,'' gates told the judge. ``i will never be able to forget.''
gates and family members in the courtroom wept as excerpts from five statements from victims' relatives were read
in a plea bargain, 16 original misdemeanor charges of manslaughter by locomotive were consolidated into a single charge, reducing gates' possible prison time from 80 years to five
murphy also fined gates the maximum $1,000. gates was taken into custody immediately after sentencing. he could be eligible for parole after serving about 18 months, state's attorney sandra o'connor said
mrs. o'connor asked murphy to sentence gates to the maximum allowable term, while his public defender, donna shearer, asked for a two-year prison term, plus mandatory rehabilitation
the judge said, ``no matter what i do, we are at the mercy of people who will simply not behave properly behind the wheel of an automobile or at the stick of an airplane. there's nothing i can do that will deter those people.''
prosecutors accepted the plea bargain after examining vehicular manslaughter cases from several maryland counties and finding that none of the sentences were longer than five years, mrs. o'connor said
dr. roger horn, whose daughter ceres was killed in the crash, said he did not know what sentence would have been appropriate. he said he was angry that no railroad safety legislation has been approved by congress since the crash. ``that crime is right up there with mr. gates','' he said
mrs. o'connor said her office would join the victims' families in lobbying the general assembly next year to increase the severity of the crime
ms. shearer said she was disappointed in the sentence but doubted an appeal would be filed
more than 175 people were injured when gates missed a track signal and drove three linked conrail locomotives in front of the 660-passenger amtrak train traveling about 120 mph. the impact trapped riders in the wreckage for hours in bitter cold
gates was unhurt and his brakeman, edward cromwell, suffered a broken leg
the plea bargain was announced just before a trial at which cromwell was expected to testify that he and gates fabricated a story to cover up their drug use on the train
tests performed on blood samples taken from both men after the accident showed traces of marijuana and possibly alcohol in their systems, the national transportation safety board said
a january ruling by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals against post-crash drug testing is under appeal to the u.s. supreme court
although vice president george bush is running virtually alone for the republican presidential nomination, it will be at least a couple of weeks before he can gain enough delegates for a majority at the gop convention
going into tuesday's primary in connecticut, bush had 788 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the republican nomination. another 250 delegates, most of whom are the remnants of the presidential campaigns of sen. bob dole and rep. jack kemp, now are counted as uncommitted
if bush were to pick up all of those delegates, he still would be 101 short of the number needed to win the nomination
the connecticut primary could give bush 35 delegates and he could gain 47 more next week in wisconsin. minnesota holds the next republican event yielding national convention delegates when the party there holds its state convention on april 15
that convention, where 24 delegates are at stake, would be the earliest opporunity for bush to go over the top
however, if bush gains none of the currently uncommitted delegates, his road to the nomination will be a bit longer. assuming he wins every delegate that can be won from now on, bush would cross the threshold on may 3, when ohio, indiana and the district of columbia hold their primaries
bush's only challenger is former television evangelist pat robertson, who has 17 delegates and has all but quit campaigning
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis defeated jesse jackson in the connecticut presidential primary tuesday night and bid for a victory strong enough to reassure party leaders about his troubled democratic candidacy
president oscar arias met tuesday with three guatemalan guerrilla leaders and said he would try to help arrange new negotiations between guatemala's government and leftist rebels
he told reporters after the meeting that he would intercede with president vinicio cerezo of guatemala to see if negotiations could be resumed
it has been proven that peace and democracy can be reached through dialogue,'' arias said
cerezo's government and the rebels held their only peace talks in 27 years of fighting last october in madrid, spain
those negotiations were in line with the peace plan signed in guatemala in august by the presidents of the five central american countries _ costa rica, guatemala, el salvador, nicaragua and honduras. arias was the author of the plan and was awarded the 1987 nobel peace prize
arias met for more than an hour with rebel leaders rodrigo asturias, luis becker and hector nuila. asturias is the son of miguel angel asturias, who won the nobel prize for literature in 1971
asturias told reporters the rebels proposed another negotiating session to be held in costa rica next month with archbishop prospero penados del barrio, the roman catholic prelate of guatemala, as mediator
penados del barrio agreed earlier this year to the guerrillas' proposal that he serve as mediator, but cerezo's government has rebuffed calls for a resumption of the talks
we place no conditions on these talks, instead we offer an open agenda to discuss the problems of guatemala and from there look for a political solution for our country, with the participation of all social sectors,'' asturias told a news conference
he is a commander of the guatemalan national revolutionary union, a coalition of three guerrilla groups that claim a total of 3,500 combatants
the central american peace plan calls for cease-fires in the regional conflicts, democratic reforms, amnesties for political prisoners and a ban on outside military assistance. trial</head> to update with prosecutor saying dealership sale would have no immediate effect, defense resting on second count, and to correct that witness who was admonished was trying to read from earlier testimony, sted from a law. picks up 7th graf, `l'ecuyer continued...'.</note>
while the arizona senate heard testimony about an allegedly improper loan to gov. evan mecham's car dealership, the governor's son announced tuesday that the family has been forced to sell the business to avert financial ruin
the confusion and questions this avalanche of negative publicity has caused ... has forced my family to come to this decision to sell mecham pontiac while the condition of the company remains solvent and salable,'' dennis mecham told a news conference at the dealership in suburban glendale
dennis mecham said sales have decreased dramatically for over a year as the result of mecham's political battle and its effect on consumers. the dealership was sold for about $4 million to a neighboring auto dealer, he said
dennis mecham testified last week that the mecham car dealership was on sure footing last july when his father arranged an $80,000 loan to the business from a protocol fund. the prosecution has sought to show that mecham pontiac was in desperate straits and needed the money. the governor denies this
prosecutors said the sale would have no effect on mecham's impeachment tral at this time
mecham attorney jerris leonard said he was sure mecham would reap ``a substantial amount of money'' from the sale although not as much if he had sold before the political crisis
leonard rested his case late tuesday on the $80,000 loan count, and the prosecution said it would call at least one rebuttal witness before closing its evidence on the charge wednesday
senators then would decide whether to vote on mecham's guilt or innocence of the two charges already considered or move on to evidence on the third and last count
meanwhile, a defense witness who testified that the $80,000 loan was ``legal but stupid,'' was threatened with contempt of court
the warning to political consultant and lawyer robert l'ecuyer from presiding officer frank x. gordon came at mecham's impeachment trial as l'ecuyer tried to blunt a piercing cross-examination by reading sections of another witness' earlier testimony about which he had not been questioned
l'ecuyer continued his discourse even after gordon, the chief justice of the arizona supreme court, ruled him out of order
mr. l'ecuyer,'' you see this thing in my hand?'' gordon asked, pointing his gavel at the witness
i have been a judge for 26 years, sir. i have never had to rap this gavel and find a lawyer in contempt but you are tempting me.''
i am properly admonished,'' said l'ecuyer
earlier, l'ecuyer was admonished for trying to read a lengthy statement to defuse a prosecution disclosure that he had been reprimanded by the arizona bar for unethical conduct in 1979 and voluntarily stopped practicing law for three years
he admitted that he improperly borrowed $5,500 from a client's trust fund which he said was in lieu of his fee
and your defense was that you were borrowing at a higher rate of interest than it could otherwise get?'' prosecutor paul eckstein asked to laughter from the gallery
part of mecham's defense on the charge that he misused the protocol fund by loaning $80,000 to his mecham pontiac dealership was that he borrowed the money at a higher rate of interest than it was receiving at the bank
asked by mecham lawyer jerris leonard whether he knew of any law that made the governor's loan illegal, l'ecuyer replied: ``i know of no such law.''
l'ecuyer testified, ``i told the governor when i found out that it was stupid. i thought it was legal but stupid.''
mecham contends the protocol fund was not public money because it was raised by his inaugural committee to pay off campaign debts
when state law barred that use, the money was placed in a fund for such uses as the governor's trips and entertainment to promote arizona's image
l'ecuyer, who was hired by mecham to analyze laws relating to the public funds issue, said, he concluded that the money raised by the inaugural committee remained private and in mecham's control
the status of the funds is they are purely private funds of a private unincorporated organization in that association's bank account,'' he said
eckstein noted that the chairman of mecham's inaugural committee, william long, has said his committee ceased to exist after its funds were transferred into the protocol fund
l'ecuyer said he felt long was not qualified to make that decision, which he said he considered a legal opinion
mecham, who testified earlier this week on the loan charge, also is accused of thwarting investigation of an alleged death threat on a grand jury witness and concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
the campaign loan, for which mecham faces felony charges and a criminal trial april 21, is scheduled to become the focus of the impeachment trial later this week
on tuesday, maricopa county superior court judge michael ryan rejected two defense motions to dismiss charges against mecham in the criminal case
the defense had claimed mecham was being selectively prosecuted and prosecuted under the wrong law. the judge also refused to separate mecham's case from that of a co-defendant, his brother willard, who was his 1986 campaign treasurer
mecham, the first u.s. governor impeached in six decades, also faces a recall election may 17. update with texaco's statement, stock's closing price, and to correct in 8th graf pvs that pickens seeking up to 15 percent of shares, sted more than 15 percent. picks up 9th graf, `in addition...'. version moved on the financial wire.</note>
the investment firm kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co. stirred up the waters around texaco inc. on tuesday, saying it will seek federal approval to acquire up to 15 percent of the oil giant's stock
kohlberg kravis, which has carried out some of the largest leveraged buyouts in u.s. history, said an affiliate already has acquired 11.95 million texaco shares, or about 4.9 percent of the roughly 242 million shares outstanding
a statement said the shares had been purchased ``some months ago in the open market.''
at its the white plains, n.y., headquarters, texaco's response was upbeat
kohlberg kravis roberts has in past situations demonstrated an ability to be a constructive shareholder, which recognizes the importance of building value for the long term,'' the company said in a statement. ``we have no indication that their intentions with texaco are any different.''
kohlberg kravis directed queries to kekst and co., a public relations firm, where ruth pachman declined further comment
investors responded enthusiastically to kohlberg kravis's anouncement. in nationwide trading of new york stock exchange-listed issues, texaco jumped $3.25 a share from the previous day's close, to $48
kohlberg kravis became the fourth party to express interest in texaco, which is to emerge from chapter 11 bankruptcy court reorganization early next month
financier carl c. icahn is the white plains, n.y.-based company's largest shareholder, holding 14.8 percent of its shares
oilman t. boone pickens also has sought federal regulatory permission to buy up to 15 percent of texaco's shares
in addition, getty petroleum co., an independent marketer of petroleum products that was born of texaco's 1984 getty oil co. acquisition, has made a similar filing
the texaco-getty oil deal started the nation's third largest oil company on the road to bankruptcy court
in november 1985 a houston jury ruled texaco had improperly interfered with a move by houston-based pennzoil co. to acquire part of getty, then bought getty itself. the jury awarded pennzoil $10.53 billion in damages
while the figure was reduced by $2 billion on appeal, it still stood at $10.3 billion, including interest, when texaco filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection last april
the company said it was forced to do so to avoid having to post an $11 billion bond while appealing the houston jury's decision
last week, a u.s. bankruptcy court judge approved a reorganization plan that will bring texaco out of chapter 11 protection. as part of that plan, pennzoil agreed to accept a $3 billion payment to settle its damage claim. no outdated material</note>
house negotiators reached ``agreement in principle'' late tuesday on a $50 million package of humanitarian aid for nicaragua's contra rebels and for children injured in that country's civil war
as part of the deal, speaker jim wright would agree to give ``fair'' consideration to any future request president reagan might make for new military aid for the rebels if the peace process should break down, said rep. david bonior, d-mich
the package was worked out in a negotiating session between wright and house minority leader robert michel, r-ill., and final details were to be approved by both sides at a meeting wednesday morning
the rules committee late tuesday approved ground rules for bringing the package to the floor on wednesday and approval by a bipartisan majority was expected, if no further snags developed
i think we have an agreement in principle,'' said rep. dick cheney, r-wyo
the tentative agreement would send about $2.7 million monthly in food, clothing, medicine and shelter to the rebels over the next six months. communications gear and other expenses would push the total six-month rebel aid package to $20 million, said bonior leader of a democratic task force on the contra issue
an identical ammount would go into a new program to care for children injured in the seven-year civil war, he said
it also would provide $10 million to finance a verification commission to ensure adherence to a cease-fire worked out last week between the contras and the leftist managua government. not included in the $50 million total is additional money to transport the aid
the money would be administered by the state department's agency for international development, bonior said
in addition, wright, d-texas, would write a letter to reagan and michel assuring the president of a chance to submit a proposal for new military aid if the peace process becomes derailed
the speaker would promise ``fair'' treatment of such a package, but would retain control over the precise timing of any final vote and the rules under which the package would be considered, bonior said. the verification commission would also have ``a substantial say'' in whether new military aid is justified, he said
republicans have said they do not trust the sandinistas to fulfill promises made as part of the 60-day cease-fire agreement reached in talks with the rebels last week at sapoa, nicaragua. they had wanted a guaranteed speedy vote in congress on future military aid to put pressure on managua to live up to those agreements, which include amnesty and restoration of civil liberties
earlier, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the amounts mentioned were agreeable to the administration
the issue is not money but how fast we can get it'' to help assure the survival of the contra rebels as a fighting force, he said. ``we want it as fast as we can get it.''
the money would keep supplies flowing to the rebels as they wait out the continuing negotiations over a long-term truce while based in cease-fire zones inside nicaragua. the aid would flow at a rate comparable to that provided before feb. 29, when the last u.s. support ran out
any new aid for the contras would have to conform to the requirements of the cease fire reached last week. that agreement said the contras would receive only humanitarian aid and that the aid would be routed through ``neutral organizations.'' the cia has delivered past u.s. aid supplies to the rebels. ^eds: 1st name boy in 2d graf cq</head>
the pro-apartheid conservative party extended its series of recent political victories by winning a special election tuesday to fill a vacant seat in parliament's white house of assembly
conservative candidate corne mulder received 8,437 votes to 4,726 for boy geldenhuys of the governing national party in the balloting in rural randfontein district
the seat became vacant jan. 13 when mulder's father, connie mulder, died of heart and kidney failure. the elder mulder had captured the seat for the conservatives in the national whites-only election last may
tuesday's lopsided vote was a further indication of the conservative party's growing support, especially among rural whites
president p.w. botha's national party holds 133 seats in the whites' 178-seat house of assembly, conservatives 23 and the anti-apartheid progressive federal party 17 with five seats held by minor parties or independents
there are three separate chambers in the white-dominated parliament, with the mixed-race chamber having 78 seats and the asian chamber 45
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the conservatives won two special parliamentary elections on march 2 in rural white districts similar to randfontein, which is 50 miles west of johannesburg
in the national elections in may the conservatives won 26 percent of the votes and they are expected to gain ground on the national party in nationwide municipal elections in october. the national party has governed south africa since 1948
the conservatives oppose all concessions to the black majority and say botha is capitulating to blacks and international pressure
botha's party has said it seeks gradual race reform that eventually would give blacks a say in national politics, but with the whites maintaining ultimate control
the progressive federal party has been losing support in recent years and did not enter a candidate in tuesday's election
