a group that sponsors meetings for recovering alcoholics voted against buying an abandoned schoolhouse tuesday after wary park township officials imposed nearly two dozen restrictions
the rules would have prohibited members from gathering outside on the 4-acre property, which includes soccer and softball fields and a playground, and would have limited the number of cars on the premises to 35
those two stipulations were the ones most bothersome to the holland alano association, said spokesman donald hann
we cannot and we will not turn away people seeking help because they happen to arrive in the 36th car,'' said hann, whose association provides meeting space for 250 to 300 people in six groups, including alcoholics anonymous and al-anon
directors of the non-profit organization had planned to buy the former ventura school, a vacant four-room building in a rural area six miles north of holland, because its lease on a decaying warehouse expires may 1
the holland alano association finds it impossible to purchase the ventura school because of the onerous and unfair restrictions placed on the use of the premises by the parkship township planning commission,'' the group said in a statement after meeting tuesday night
the rules, which included a ban on alcoholic beverages and ``mood altering substances,'' were imposed monday night by the ottawa county township's planning commission on a special-use permit sought by the association
several homeowners had contended the presence of the organization would destroy the peaceful character of their neighborhood
i still don't feel it belongs in a quiet residential area,'' said carol vaniwaarden. ``it's too bad. they need a place to go and they are a necessary organization, but they should be in an area where there's more activity.''
hann said the alano association must begin searching for a new building immediately
we thought an abandoned schoolhouse in the country would be ideal for us, but i guess we were wrong,'' he said. picks up 6th graf pvs, ``he was xxx</note>
vice president george bush, given a lock on the republican presidential nomination by the withdrawal of sen. bob dole and bolstered by a big win in his boyhood home state of connecticut, declared: ``the immediate task ahead is unity.''
now is the time for all of us to join together and unify the party,'' bush told a campaign rally after learning of dole's announcement. later, learning of his lopsided win in connecticut, he said: ``let's get together, keep together and get to work.''
the kansas senator dropped out of the race earlier in the day in washington, pledging to ``do all i can to elect republican in november and doing all i can for our nominee, george bush.''
it's been a hard-fought campaign and i respect the tenacity of bob dole,'' bush said
the vice president said he had called dole in washington to thank him for the ``very generous statement.''
he was a tough competitor and i wanted to congratulate him on a hard-fought race,'' bush said
bush also said dole's departure from the campaign ``changes some of the dynamics. it removes some of the tension.'' he added, ``i don't like running against other republicans.''
former television evangelist pat robertson has indicated he has no plans to withdraw from the gop race, but he has only 17 delegates _ to bush's nearly 800 _ and is no longer actively campaigning in most states
dole's withdrawal came as bush was headed toward overwhelming victory in tuesday's gop primary in connecticut, and as he campaigned in wisconsin where he had been expected to easily dominate dole in this state's april 5 primary
bush said he intended to continue cmapaigning in states with key primaries, mentioning california, ohio, pennsylvania and new york
overall, however, ``the schedule will be somewhat lighter and i'll have more time to flesh out the issue positions,'' bush said
he denied that there had been animosity between him and dole. ``i don't feel that way, never have.'' he told reporters
although bush's camp was clearly elated at the development, one top bush supporter, wisconsin gov. tommy thompson, said that dole's exit could hurt bush's chances in the long run
i can't see the fact that the vice president doesn't have any more opposition is that good for him. it's good to have a primary,'' said thompson, speaking to reporters on air force two. ``those individuals who come out of a hotly contested primary can use it as a springbord to solidify the party,'' thompson said
bush faced hecklers and students chanting, ``just say no'' as he addressed an audience at lawrence university in appleton, wis. ``this is nothing. this is small bore stuff. a preview of the democratic convention that is about to come,'' bush told the college audience. u.s. base; no pickup.</note>
the roman catholic church on tuesday called for gen. manuel antonio noriega to resign and offered to act as a mediator between the strongman and opponents demanding his ouster
a church spokesman said archbishop marcos a. mcgrath had talked with both sides and received ``a positive impression'' that a solution could be found to the agonizing crisis that has gripped panama for more than a month
in other developments tuesday:
_a general strike continued for the ninth day, with shopowners keeping their stores closed despite a violent crackdown against government opponents on monday
_the u.s. helicopter carrier okinawa passed through the panama canal on its way to its home port in san diego. the u.s. defense department described the passage as ``routine.'' but noriega called the passage ``a threat and an agression.''
_noriega said in a speech tuesday night that he would not be vanquished by what he said was an imperialist plot against him
_in washington, panamanian ambassador juan b. sosa, speaking on behalf of ousted president eric arturo delvalle, asked the united states to send a military force to remove noriega, head of the defense forces. ``we're asking the international community to help,'' sosa said. ``we're paying the price. but we've got no weapons. give us weapons.''
the call for noriega's resignation marked the first time the church had made its stance public. last week, church officials privately urged noriega, under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges, to step down
on monday, troops firing shotguns, tear gas and water cannon smashed a demonstration by thousands of anti-government marchers in panama city
afterward, troops raided the marriott hotel, which serves as the headquarters of panama's opposition and the foreign press
about 20 opposition leaders and ten foreign journalists were arrested. the journalists and most of the opposition leaders were released tuesday although carlos gonzalez de la lastra, a founder and director of the national civic crusade, was still missing
the crusade is a coalition of about 200 business, professional, labor and political groups that has been seeking noriega's removal since last june
president reagan's chief spokesman expressed outrage at monday's action by noriega's troops
we are all angry at this latest demonstration, at people being beaten and threatened,'' spokesman marlin fitzwater said, adding that the noriega regime ``is showing its true colors.''
the united states has imposed sanctions on panama's government and supported efforts by delvalle to freeze panamanian funds in u.s. banks
eight of the foreign journalists arrested monday night were taken to a military intelligence center in panama city and held for three hours. two other journalists _ ignacio medrano of cbs and nbc cameraman domingo rex of mexico city _ were arrested separately, witnesses said
noriega told a ``solidarity with panama'' conference tuesday night that the united states had spent more than $100 million in the effort to topple him
but with all the gold in the world they have not been able to bring this people or this commander or these defense forces to their knees,'' he said, shaking his fist to wild applause
delegates from about 25 latin american and caribbean countries attended the conference, but few represented governments
a spokeswoman at the marine traffic office of the panama canal said the helicopter carrier okinawa passed through the canal tuesday afternoon and was anchored at rodman naval base, a u.s. facility. she said she did not know whether it was loading or unloading anything
the church agreed to intercede in panama's crisis at the request of president oscar arias of costa rica, prime minister felipe gonzalez of spain, and former presidents carlos andres perez of venezuela and daniel oduber of costa rica
monsignor oscar brown, the auxiliary bishop of panama city, said mcgrath received their request monday and immediately began contacting ``all the parties involved,'' including noriega and opposition leaders
but brown noted that the opposition demonstration was broken up ``in the precise moments when we were pursuing the first steps of this initiative.''
he said representatives of the civic crusade ``who have been contacted have responded favorably.''
in a statement to reporters during brown's news conference, the church said a committee of bishops met with noriega on thursday and asked him to resign
last month, noriega engineered delvalle's dismissal and installed a new chief executive, manuel solis palma. the civic crusade and the united states continue to recognize delvalle as panama's legitimate president
earlier tuesday, ricardo arias calderon, the president of the opposition christian democratic party, said the government had reacted to the request for church mediation ``as if it just doesn't give a damn.''
referring to monday's violence, arias calderon said, ``they are responding to this initiative by simply going ahead in their repressive manner and doing it dramatically so nobody misses the point.''
latin america urged the united states on tuesday to end its economic blockade of panama, while encouraging panama at the same time to make its democracy more effective
the 26 member nations of the latin american economic system ended a two-day emergency conference, convened at panama's request, by condemning the u.s. economic measures as contrary to international law and the charters of the united nations and the organization of american states
the nations said they were opposed to foreign intervention in panama and asked washington to honor a treaty which turns full control of the panama canal over to panama in 1999
we urge the u.s. government to revoke immediately the coercive measures it has adopted against panama,'' organization members said in a final three-page communique released late tuesday
we reaffirm the sovereign right of all nations to decide their own economic, social and political destiny in peace and liberty, free from foreign pressure, aggression and threats.''
the organization, based in caracas, was founded in 1976 as an economic forum for latin american countries
u.s. economic action against panama is aimed at forcing the removal of gen. manuel antonio noriega as chief of his nation's defense forces and as de facto ruler of panama. noriega is under indictment in the united states as a drug trafficker and money-launderer, charges he denies
the reagan administration has imposed economic sanctions and has backed moves by former panamanian president eric arturo delvalle to freeze panamanian accounts in u.s. banks. the united states still recognizes delvalle as president, although he was ousted by noriega
the latin american economic system ``took note'' of a promise by panama to ``deepen its democratic system.''
the group said a request for economic aid by panama's cash-starved government will be considered ``with a spirit of solidarity'' by economic system members
individual delegates clearly separated their support for the principle of self-determination from their position regarding noriega
we have not come to defend a regime, or even less a person who has been insubordinate to civil and constitutional authority,'' peru's foreign minister, allan wagner, told delegates tuesday
our solidarity is with the people of panama.''
he called for an end to panama's political crisis ``through free elections and the removal of any obstacles that prevent this clear expression of the will of the people of panama.''
foreign minister jorge abadia arias of panama said monday his nation was ``fully committed to deepening panama's democratic system.''
mexico and venezuela were among the individual nations monday that indicated their opposition to outside interference in panama's affairs, without specifically mentioning the united states by name. new york; picks up 5th graf pvs, ``swiss red ...</note>
more than two dozen kurds burned on their faces, backs and hands from reported iraqi poison gas attacks that killed 5,000 were flown to four european countries and the united states on tuesday for treatment
some coughed violently, others lay motionless on stretchers as they were taken from an iran air ambulance plane that touched down in austria, switzerland, west germany and britain
one 6-year-old child, said by iranian and kurdish officials to have lost her entire family in an attack, sobbed constantly and called for her parents. at least four other children were among the wounded
the plane, dropping off six patients each in vienna, geneva, frankfurt and london, arrived in new york later tuesday with five wounded. the man, woman and three girls were taken to st. john's episcopal hospital in queens, where they were admitted in stable condition, hospital spokesman jim wellen said
he said they suffered from skin and eye wounds, burns and inhalation injuries
swiss red cross president felix christ said the iranian goverment was paying for the medical treatment
iran said the iraqi air force dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three kurdish towns in iraq, killing 5,000 kurds and injuring 5,000 other people. the attacks first targeted the town of halabja, which had been captured by iran, on march 16. some chemical bombs reportedly hit the nearby villages of khormal and dojaila during the next few days. most victims were in halabja
dr. gerhard freilinger, department head of vienna's university clinic for plastic surgery, said the patients he talked to appeared to have been injured by mustard gas that may have been mixed with a nerve gas
it was possible the mustard gas was ``in combination with a light nerve gas, because they all have bad headaches, are dizzy and (some) may have been unconscious,'' he told reporters in vienna
mustard gas causes changes in the lungs that can lead to suffocation, burns the skin and also destroys bone marrow, freilinger said
the gas is heavier than air, which he said would explain how it seeped into cellars where the patients said they had been hiding during the attacks
freilinger said poison gas penetrates everything, including clothes
they can't run away from it because if they do, they breath it in even deeper,'' he said
in the past, iran has sent soldiers allegedly poisoned by mustard gas to vienna and other european cities for treatment. in july, iranian civilians were sent for treatment for the first time
since 1984, freilinger has treated about 30 victims of alleged chemical weapons attacks in the 7{-year-old persian gulf war. he said about half of them had survived, but the latest victims were injured nearly two weeks ago, meaning the damage done by the gas could not be reversed
freilinger said he visited areas allegedly bombed with chemical weapons in 1984 and had taken a sample of the gas for verification and testing
he said two of the patients, a child and a severely wounded iranian soldier, were to be placed in the intensive care unit at his university clinic
three women and a man were brought to private clinics in the austrian capital
in geneva, three children aged between six and 11 were driven by ambulance to the lausanne university hospital and two men and a woman were flown on to zurich and taken to the city's university hospital
a swiss foreign ministry spokesman said the six were granted visas for switzerland for humanitarian reasons. in 1985, five iranian soldiers allegedly wounded by iraqi chemical weapons were treated in zurich and lausanne. the following year, six more were treated in lausanne and in liestal near basel and two died
five men and a 6-year-old girl were taken to recklinghausen, 125 miles north of frankfurt. scores of iranians injured in the war have been flown in recent years to the west german town, which has several clinics that specialize in respiratory ailments
about 70 iranian protesters waving placards and photographs of civilians allegedly burned by chemical gas gathered at london's heathrow airport. three male and three female patients were due to be taken from the converted jumbo jet to cromwell hospital. quotes, other details. picks up 4th graf pvs, ortega spoke ... with minor editing to trim</note>
president daniel ortega urged the united states on tuesday to negotiate a return to normal relations with his leftist sandinista government
ortega said president reagan had promised to begin discussions with nicaragua if the sandinistas met with u.s.-supported contra rebels. a truce agreement with the contras was reached last week
we hope president reagan keeps his word,'' ortega declared. ``he has repeatedly said that the day the sandinistas sit down for direct negotiations with the contras, then the united states government would sit down and negotiate with the sandinistas.''
contra and sandinista representatives reached general agreement tuesday on the size and location of zones where the rebels will gather during a temporary 60-day cease-fire to begin friday
a communique at the end of two days of talks in the southern nicaragua border town of sapoa said two zones would be in the northern part of the country, two on the caribbean coast and one in the south
aristides sanchez, head of the rebel delegation, said exact locations would not be disclosed yet
still to be decided was how the truce will work, said maj. gen. joaquin cuadra, chief government delegate
he said it would be a main topic when talks resume in sapoa next tuesday
the agreement signed last week does not say if the rebels must lay down their arms during the truce
what is important in these meetings is that they have advanced,'' cuadra said
he called the talks ``an important step toward the permanent cease-fire.'' cuadra said the cease-fire will take effect friday as scheduled, even though the conditions were not agreed upon
sanchez said the talks ``are quite delicate. we are trying to guarantee the physical and moral security of our combatants.''
ortega spoke at a ceremony honoring anti-war activist s. brian willson of san francisco as a ``hero of peace.'' willson lost both legs when a train ran over him during a protest at a u.s. navy weapons depot in concord, calif., last fall
reagan told the organization of american states in november that secretary of state george p. shultz was prepared to meet with the sandinistas as part of discussions with other central american countries ``once serious negotiations'' on a nicaraguan cease-fire were under way
direct talks between the united states and nicaragua have not been held since 1984
on march 23, the sandinistas and contras ended three days of meetings with a signed agreement to work out a permanent cease-fire in the civil war, which began in 1981, and restore democracy to nicaragua
ortega's government refused for years to meet with the contras, insisting instead on negotiations with the united states
the nicaraguan president said tuesday: ``we hope he (reagan) is a man of his word and immediately fulfills his word to accept bilateral conversations to deal with security issues that concern the united states with respect to nicaragua and with nicaragua in respect to the united states.''
those talks should concentrate on normalizing relations, not the internal policies of nicaragua, ortega said, and added: ``we will not directly discuss the democratic regime in nicaragua or the democratic regime in the united states.''
washington contends the sandinistas broke promises made to the oas in 1979 in exchange for its support. the reagan administration says they promised democracy and delivered marxism
the sandinistas came to power in a revolution that ousted the pro-american, rightist regime of the late president anastasio somoza in july 1979. the united states supported the sandinistas initially, but in 1981 began financing the contras
in his remarks tuesday, ortega urged the u.s. congress not to approve any contra aid that would conflict with last week's agreement, in which the contras agreed to accept only humanitarian assistance from neutral organizations
u.s. aid to the rebels expired feb. 29 and sandinistas sources have cited lack of aid as the reason the contras signed the truce agreement
rebel spokesmen say continuing the war is unnecessary if the sandinistas keep their promises of restoring democratic freedoms
for the sandinistas, the agreement could ease internal pressures created by dissatisfaction with the war, an unpopular military draft, food shortages and a shattered economy
bernhard h. goetz on tuesday appealed his conviction on weapons charges in the 1984 subway shooting of four teen-agers, saying the instructions to the jurors did not give them the option of being merciful toward him
the appeal, which contained a legal attack on his sentence as well as his conviction, was filed at the state supreme court's appellate division by his lawyer, barry slotnick
goetz, 40, is free on $5,000 bail pending appeal. after a widely publicized trial, the man dubbed the ``subway vigilante'' was convicted last june on one count of third-degree weapons possession but acquitted of more serious charges in the december 1984 shootings
goetz said he shot the four young men, all 19, because they were trying to rob him when they approached and asked for $5. the men said they were merely panhandling
in the appeal, slotnick argued that the trial judge, stephen crane, illegally violated goetz's right to have a jury decide his guilt or innocence on the weapons charge by telling the jurors they ``must'' _ rather than they ``may'' _ convict, if they found goetz guilty beyond a reasonable doubt
the lawyer argued the judge voided the jury's power to find that a defendant committed a criminal act but also deserved mercy
jury mercy is indeed a well-recognized phenomenon indigenous to out justice system,'' slotnick wrote
slotnick also argued against the sentence that crane imposed last october: six months in jail and 4{ years' probation, plus community service, a fine and counseling
paradoxically, slotnick argued for a longer, one-year jail sentence, because a definite one-year sentence would make goetz eligible for parole in two months. his sentence as it now stands means he must serve the six months with the possibility of being jailed again if he violates probation
the one-year sentence is required because there is a state law requiring a mandatory year in jail for a weapons possession conviction, and the law does not mention splitting the sentence into part jail time, part probation, the lawyer said
the appeals brief also argued that a jail sentence would be ``unduly harsh'' in goetz's case because of his state of mind. slotnick said goetz continues to suffer ``psychic pain'' because of the intense publicity the case received
goetz had no comment on the appeal
a meeting including mother teresa, the dalai lama, carl sagan, and officials from the united states, soviet union and united nations will be a unique collaboration on problems that threaten human survival, planners said tuesday
most of the world's forums, national and international, approach problems only politically, which is just one side of the world's ``two vast structures,'' said the very rev. james parks morton, dean of new york's episcopal cathedral of st. john the divine
religious forces ``have been excluded from the debate,'' he said, adding, ``it seems that the adjudication has got to be both sides working together.'' morton is co-chairman of the global conference of spiritual and parliamentary leaders on human survival april 11-15 at oxford university in england
about 100 elected leaders from around the world and about 100 religious leaders of five major faiths are scheduled to participate. morton's co-chairman is sen. sat paul mittal of india
angier biddle duke, chairman of the international advisory committee for the conference, described it as ``first time in modern history'' for religious-political collaboration on such a range of critical issues. duke is a former u.s. ambassador to spain and el salvador
in dealing with dangers to life on earth, ``politicians haven't been able to do it on their own,'' said rep. james h. scheuer, d-n.y., who plans to attend the conference
we must merge the ethical and the practicial, the politician and the priest, the sacred and the secular.''
he and sagan, a cornell university astronomer, ticked off a long list of threats to the planet, includingtoxic waste, acid rain, depletion the protective ozone layer allowing in more destructive ultraviolet rays, the temperature-raising ``greenhouse effect'' of fossil fuels, aids, and nuclear arms
some of the effects ``are so serious as they can be described only in words of catholic theology as crimes against creation,'' sagan said
political leaders have looked at the problems without doing much, he said, and religions, ``repositories of classical wisdom,'' must become involved to raise consciousness
other participants include archbishop of canterbury robert runcie, cardinal franz koenig of austria, soviet academy of sciences vice president evguenij velikhov, u.n. secretary general javier perez de cuellar and macarthur foundation chairman thornton bradshaw
financing for the conference, expected to be about $1 million, has come from individual religious donors, said the conference executive coordinator, akio matsumura of new york
two network journalists beaten at their hotel in panama by plainclothes police flew here tuesday, and one said he wouldn't believe his experience if he had seen it in a movie
i've never seen anything like it in any other country, grabbing people like that,'' said ignacio medrano, a cbs cameraman who limped in a stoop as he was helped off a chartered private jet at miami international airport. ``if we'd seen it in a movie, i would've said they were lying.''
medrano was admitted to mount sinai medical center in satisfactory condition tuesday night with broken ribs, a hospital spokeswoman said. before being taken there by ambulance, he said x-rays in panama had indicated no broken bones, but his ribs had turned purple and his legs ached from a beating with a nightstick
at least 10 foreign journalists and 20 opposition leaders were arrested monday when troops raided the marriott hotel in panama city. most were released by tuesday
medrano said he came to the aid of nbc cameraman domingo rex of mexico city, who said he suffered a broken nose when punched by a plainclothes security agent. the officer broke his wrist throwing the punch, rex said
he tried to grab my camera and we started fighting. he got real mad,'' said rex, whose nose was covered with gauze and tape. ``at this point, ignacio medrano tried to save me and they beat him too.''
it is really scary because they are up. they are looking for the press. they were after them,'' rex said, adding he paid a $365 fine to be released from jail, returned to his hotel and left the country
at one point, i was really scared a lot, scared about leaving this place alive,'' said rex, who had been in panama for 17 days. ``i decided it was time to go.''
people in the hotel, which serves as the headquarters of panama's opposition and the foreign press, were attacked by agents with guns pointing in the air, medrano said
they just threw me in the van with the rest of the people,'' he said. ``they kicked me all the way to the van.''
alfredo gudino, an nbc sound technician, also returned on the chartered plane. he was detained but not injured
the overseas press club, a new york-based organization of jounalists, sent a letter of protest tuesday to panama's ruler, gen. manuel antonio noriega
oliver tambo, head of the african national congress, accused south africa tuesday of a plot to kill anc representatives in mozambique with poison sugar
tambo told a news conference in harare that south africa had arranged for a third country to deliver the poisoned sugar, apparently as a gift, to anc officials in maputo, the capital of neighboring mozambique
he did not name the third country allegedly involved but said the sugar ``was brought into mozambique by a country in which the pretoria regime operates freely.''
tambo did not say if any anc officials had been poisoned
the anc is the main guerrilla group fighting south africa's policy of apartheid, or legalized racial discrimination by the white minority
tambo is in harare for a 3-day conference of west european parliamentarians on apartheid. the conference, attended by delegates from 14 countries, ends wednesday
as long as it (apartheid) remains there will be no peace in the region,'' tambo said. ``this message was clear yesterday when for no reason at all south africa attacked botswana.''
he referred to the south african military attack monday on a house on the outskirts of gaborone, the capital of botswana, in which four people were killed
south african confirmed the raid and said the four people killed were terrorists. botswana said one man and three woman were killed. it said the man was a ``south african refugee,'' two of the women were botswanans and the third woman had not been identified
in an attack tuesday in paris, dulcie september, the anc representative for france, was shot to death in her office. french news reports said mrs. september, 45, was shot in the face while entering the office at about 9 .m
anc officials claimed south africa was behind the killing, but south africa denied it and suggested the attack was related to strife within the outlawed organization
tambo, based in the zambian capital of lusaka, told the news conference: ``we must step up our attacks on the police, the army and other personnel associated with the institution'' of apartheid
we will strike against its economic infrastructure and do much more intensively what we have been doing all the time.''
by south african law and custom, apartheid establishes a segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the panchen lama, highest tibetan religious leader in the chinese government, said tuesday four people were killed in a pro-independence protest earlier this month in lhasa, capital of the remote himalayan region
official chinese reports have said the only fatality was a chinese policeman
the panchen lama told western reporters a monk and two civilians also were killed. he spoke after meeting with a small group of tibetan delegates to the national people's congress in beijing
western travelers in lhasa have said tibetans were reporting 21 civilians and 3 policemen killed, and many arrests. the panchen lama would not comment on the reports of arrests
buddhist monks and lay people in lhasa held a violent anti-chinese protest march 5 at the close of the annual moinlam qenmo, or great prayer festival, that lasted more than 12 hours
reports from witnesses said they attacked police with stones, knives and steel bars, seriously injuring 30 officers, and set bonfires throughout the city
buddhist priests seeking independence for tibet led a protest last october in which at least 14 people were killed and a police station was destroyed
the panchen lama, tibetan buddhism's second-highest leader after the dalai lama, continued his campaign tuesday for a lenient policy toward tibet
the dalai lama, a god-king to tibetan buddhists, went into exile in india after an unsuccessful rebellion in 1959. china took over tibet in 1950
under the panchen lama's proposals, efforts would continue to heal wounds caused by china's radical cultural revolution of 1966-76. religious belief was outlawed and many buddhist temples and monasteries were destroyed during that period
how we implement our religious policies will have a great affect on the thinking of the masses in tibet, where nearly everyone is religious,'' said the panchen lama, a loyal supporter of china's communist government
he also addressed militants advocating tibetan independence: ``some separatists outside china want to split tibet from the motherland,'' he said. ``they'd better stop their dirty tricks. tibetan affairs are chinese domestic affairs, and they are family affairs.'' news digest: panama city, panama _ pm-panama, a0495; managua, nicaragua _ pm-nicaragua-divisions, a0419; washington _ pm-speakes speaks, a0430; undated _ pm-political rdp, a0477; washington _ pm-veep selection, a0435; washington _ pm-jackson's story, a0447; ramallah, occupied west bank _ pm-israel, a0483; hackensack, n.j. _ pm-surrogate mom, a0476; pembroke, n.c. _ pm-activist killed, a0505; washington _ pm-arms treaty, a0440
