president reagan says americans won't accept trade restrictions and retaliation against foreign manufacturers and threatened to veto legislation aimed at curbing u.s. trade deficits
reagan, promoting his free-trade stance even in the face of mounting u.s. trade imbalances, warned monday that a trade bill under consideration in congress could weaken international trading systems and ``require the president to start trade wars.''
i'll veto if i must,'' reagan told reynolds metals co. workers on the eve of a crucial house-senate conference committee meeting on the bill
the federal fund that insures deposits in commercial banks could suffer a loss in 1988 for the first time in its 54-year history, federal deposit insurance corp. chairman l. william seidman says
seidman said monday a loss to the insurance fund, if any, would depend on how much the fdic spends to resolve the problems of first republicbank of dallas, which earlier this month received a $1 billion infusion of government aid. he said it is too soon to say with certainty what the cost of restoring first republicbank to health will be
a merger between photofinishing giants eastman kodak co. and colorcraft corp. is aimed at making the firms more competitive rather than forcing other companies out of the industry, a federal appeals court says
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals on monday reversed a preliminary injunction granted to phototron corp. that blocked the kodak-colorcraft merger
a lower court ruled feb. 22 that phototron had standing to challenge the merger, and that the merger between kodak and colorcraft could substantially reduce competition in the wholesale photofinishing market
american stores co. said it was prepared to up its bid for lucky stores inc. to more than $1.9 billion in an effort to create the nation's largest grocery store chain
in a letter to the board of the dublin, calif.-based company, american stores chairman l.s. skaggs said his company was ready to offer $50 per share if a ``mutually acceptable agreement'' could be worked out with lucky stores
earlier monday, american launched a cash tender offer for lucky at $45 per share, or a total of $1.74 billion. that offer expires at midnight april 22
federated department stores inc. says its board will move wednesday to end the bidding war for the retailer by acting on the final competing purchase offers of r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. and campeau corp
a committee of federated's outside directors met monday to determine bidding procedures and would inform macy and campeau of those guidelines, federated said in a statement
macy and campeau have each offered more than $6 billion to buy federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer. macy's bid has the approval of federated management
corning glass works and smithkline beckman corp. have each raised their bids for international clinical laboratories, a chain of clinical-testing laboratories that is based in tennessee
corning moved first, increasing its tender offer monday to about $360 million, or $35 a share for icl's 10 million-plus outstanding shares and common stock equivalents
but smithkline, based in philadelphia, soon followed by raising its offer to $37 a share, which it said would amount to about $400 million. it had previously offered $32 a share
the internal revenue service said it is closing a loophole that allowed procrastinating taxpayers to slip out of the country briefly on april 15th and gain an automatic two-month extension on filing their income taxes
the new ruling, announced monday, is effective for tax forms due next month, and requires taxpayers to be out of the country for at least two weeks, including april 15th, to qualify for the automatic extension. in the past, someone who left the country for just hours or minutes on the 15th was eligible
the supreme court has refused to rule that playboy enterprises violated federal copyright law when it used material intended for an easter seal telethon in a pornographic movie
the justices, over one dissenting vote, rejected an attempt monday by the easter seal society to collect damages from playboy
the court also refused to revive a $300 million copyright-infringement lawsuit against the creators and marketers of trivial pursuit, a popular board game. the justices rejected arguments by the author of several encyclopedias on trivia that many of the questions contained in the game infringed on his copyright works
international business machines corp. leads forbes magazine's list of the nation's most valuable companies for a fourth consecutive year, the magazine says
the forbes survey released monday said ibm's stock market value at the end of 1987 was $69.0 billion, a decline of 5.2 percent from a year earlier
but that was still enough to surpass exxon corp., whose stock market value rose 4.5 percent to $52.6 billion
a state court judge reserved a decision on a request that he prohibit six former top executives of lord, geller, federico, einstein inc. from soliciting business or employees from lord geller for their new ad agency
justice herman cahn asked monday that attorneys for lord geller, which had made the request for a preliminary injunction, and for the defecting lord geller executives to work out a plan for introducing evidence in the case
the six executives, led by lord geller founding partners richard lord and arthur einstein jr., walked off the job march 18, saying they felt unduly constrained under the ownership of the british firm, wpp group plc
three cabinet officers have unveiled a guide to workplace literacy that includes tips for businesses to learn just how well or poorly their workers read
the three officials _ labor secretary ann mclaughlin, education secretary william j. bennett and commerce secretary c. william verity _ all agreed in making the release monday that bolstering the basic skills of workers is essential to maintaining a strong economy
stock prices finished mostly lower monday, although a key blue-chip issue indicator, the dow jones average of 30 industrials, rose 0.82 to 1,979.77
bond prices tumbled, pushing long-term yields to their highest levels in more than two months
the dollar plunged despite central bank intervention
the possibility of severe drought damage to brazilian soybean crops helped propel u.s. soybean futures prices, but grain futures retreated
u.s. sen. john heinz promised to push for a law that would make a hostile takeover of koppers co. unpalatable for british investor brian beazer, and sen. arlen specter asked the attorney general to enter the case personally
heinz, a pittsburgh republican, charged at a news conference monday that if a $1.7 billion tender offer from bns inc. succeeds, beazer will gain a monopoly in various markets for aggregates, road building materials that include sand and pebbles added to concrete to make cement
a strangle hold on the existing aggregates business'' is financially attractive because ``environmental laws are such at the state and local level that you cannot easily open ... a new source of aggregate,'' he said
specter, a philadelphia republican, said he is concerned whether an initial jusice department review satisfied the hart-scott-rodino act, which sets guidelines for corporate takeovers. he asked attorney general edwin meese to personally review the koppers case and to respond to the request by thursday
heinz withheld details of his proposed legislation
to reveal our strategy might very well be to jeopardize its success,'' he said
the proposal will be offered this week or after the easter break as an amendment to pending legislation, heinz said
i'm not in the business of making hollow promises, and i do not make idle threats,'' heinz said. ``i have drafted and am prepared to introduce and press legislation to make the takeover of koppers extremely unpalatable
the corporate raiders will be and should be as surprised by this legislation as koppers was by this raid,'' he said
we are not corporate raiders,'' beazer declared in a full-page advertisement monday in pittsburgh's newspapers. ``our goal is not to make a quick buck. rather, we are in the process of creating a vital, dynamic worldwide organization.''
beazer said that after he acquired the atlanta homebuilder cohn communities and the dallas construction materials company gifford-hill in 1985 and 1986 respectively, ``each of those companies has grown and prospered under our ownership.''
bns inc., a takeover company formed by beazer and shearon lehman hutton inc., bid $60 cash per share for koppers stock under a tender offer open until april 7. a federal court in california temporarily has blocked the acquisition over antitrust concerns
koppers management says it may sell all or part of the company or pay cash to shareholders to keep the company out of beazer's hands
heinz said taxpayers will spend more for public roads if the takeover succeeds
the two of them combined in what are essentially local market areas would, if the sale went through, amount to a de facto local monopoly on very costly road-building materials,'' he said
the senator, allegheny county commission chairman thomas foerster and others at the news conference said the takeover jeopardizes the approximately 1,100 pittsburgh-area jobs in koppers' chemicals businesses. beazer has said he would sell chemicals and related businesses, although it is not clear that all those jobs would be eliminated
opponents also worry about the $232 million that koppers contributes to the area economy
heinz joined city, county and state officials who have lambasted shearson for going a step beyond traditional takeover financing and becoming an equity partner in the takeover company, bns
i am appalled by the involvement of shearson,'' he said. ``shearson stands to gain tens of millions of dollars in fees simply for shuffling some paper around.''
shearson officials have said their ownership in bns is merely a temporary method of helping finance the takeover
companies faced with increased competition and more demanding consumers are learning to stress customer satisfaction over bottom-line profit strategy, the president of a boston-based corporate research and training firm says
right now, there are a lot of people playing around in each others' back yard,'' said richard c. whiteley, president of the forum corporation. ``with more options, the consumer is in a better position to be selective.''
a forum corporation survey of nearly 5,700 employees and consumers released monday said top-level management should rely on ``front-line'' employees and the public to gauge service quality and corporate image
companies are learning that they need the consumer and that service has got to improve or they can lose their business overnight if they're not careful,'' said whiteley, who estimates consumer complaints have doubled since 1980
the survey, which included more than 3,200 employees at 14 large companies in the united states and canada, revealed a trend toward stressing consumer satisfaction
there's a certain arrogance in companies on a downward spiral,'' whiteley said. ``they think they know what their customers need more than their customers do.''
the survey indicated that empathy and responsiveness among so-called front-line workers who deal directly with the public leads to customer loyalty and new business
but the report noted that managers constantly must seek comments and advice from front-line employees and customers, who have the best sense of how the company is perceived in the marketplace
the report also notes that the attitudes of front-line workers is heavily influenced by upper management
consumer focus ... has come to be regarded as a complex notion that involves the entire organization, and not just something that is the responsibility of people who are sometimes the lowest-paid, least-trained and least-motivated employees in the company,'' the report said
whiteley cited toll-free information numbers, consumer questionnaires and maintaining executives' connection with the public as methods successfully used by companies seeking to enhance image and customer satisfaction
you now hear, `thank you for calling at&amp;t' when you call,'' he said. ``that wasn't the case years ago.''
whiteley predicted more u.s. companies will foster better consumer policies as foreign and domestic competition grows
forty percent of the 2,374 consumers interviewed late last year in the two-month survey said poor service prompted them to pull away their business. an additional 30 percent cited ``other reasons'' for switching, including some service-related problems, according to the report
but between 60 percent and 73 percent of consumer respondents rated service quality with the companies ``excellent,'' according to the report
we found their standards are just lower,'' said thomas atkinson, who supervised the survey. ``there's the impression that service just is not very good in america anymore.''
the number of employees who said that ``satisfying customers'' was among their companies' top three priorities ranged from 8.7 percent to 63 percent
in addition, ``attracting new customers'' was considered a priority almost twice as often as ``keeping customers'' among the corporate sponsors of the survey, which included manufacterers, high-techonology firms and service-oriented companies
the names of the companies were not released
in general, priorities having to do with customers or better financial performance were seen as key by the employees ... while objectives such as emphasizing quality, finding new products and finding new markets ranked lower,'' the report said
a final version of the findings is scheduled to be released in september, atkinson said
the dollar recovered from an early plunge in tokyo trading today following moderate intervention by japan's central bank, while stock prices posted substantial gains for the second consecutive day
traders said the u.s. currency's recovery during the day's trading was due mostly to technical factors, including dollar purchases by participants with dollar-short positions
sentiments toward the dollar are still bearish,'' said a trader who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``the bank of japan's intervention wasn't large, and much of the dollar buying was by people who recently sold dollars and were beginning to feel nervous.''
the u.s. currency now has fallen 2.78 yen in tokyo over the past four trading days
the bank of japan began buying dollars shortly after the u.s. currency opened at 123.88 yen, down 0.55 yen from monday's close of 124.43 yen. traders estimated the central bank's purchases at about $100 million. as usual, the bank did not comment officially on its market activity
the dollar then reversed direction, and ended the day's trading at 124.37 yen, down 0.06 yen from its close on monday. it ranged between 123.87 yen and 124.85 yen
traders said the dollar also was boosted by fiscal year-end buying by some corporations. the japanese fiscal year ends thursday
on the tokyo stock exchange, the 225-stock nikkei average gained 330.38 points, or 1.29 percent, closing at 25,953.09. on monday, the index rose 301.99 points
nobuo ishikawa of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage, said market participants were relieved to see the dollar stabilizing during today's trading. a bust</head>
foreign visitors are boosting attendance at south florida tourist attractions from the everglades to ocean world, while the number of vacationing collegians has plummeted to an all-time low this decade
you have a truly unique place,'' said klaus mueller, who was bird watching on the anhinga trail in the everglades, the greatest expanse of sawgrass in the world. ``everybody in the world knows about the everglades.''
attendance at everglades national park is up 43 percent over last season with 306,202 visitors in january and february compared to 213,384 during the same time last year, spokesman pat tolle said monday
it's like a language school outside my office,'' said park superintendent michael finley. ``i'm hearing french, german, japanese everywhere.''
jerome scherr, president of miami's parrot jungle, where attendance was up 16 percent, said the attraction is ``something different than they've got back home in europe and japan ... we're subtropical _ palm trees and glamour.''
the weak dollar against foreign currencies and the slick image created by the television series ``miami vice'' are attracting many of the foreign visitors to south florida
nigel and rosy collins visited miami's seaquarium during their week-long trip to south florida and orlando from london. the couple expected their vacation to cost half of what they would have paid two years ago because of the weak dollar
everything is so warm, so clean, so new, so cheap,'' collins said, as his wife chimed in, ``and you've got don johnson.''
but the traditional spring break market in fort lauderdale is going bust instead of boom this year, according to broward county tourism officials
a turnout of 200,000 college students had been expected, matching last year's dismal turnout. however, the numbers now being forecast range from 110,000 to 180,000, and the hotels and bars that report solid business say it's due to the influx of european tourists
although south florida tourist officials are uncertain of the number of foreign tourists, international traffic at miami international airport was up 9 percent to 786,951 passengers in january compared to the same month last year
finley expects europeans to generate 80 percent of the business at flamingo lodge at the southern tip of the everglades in the mosquito-swarming months of july and august
at lion country safari, the palm beach county big-game preserve and amusement park, a 25 percent boost in attendance over last year was reported, said lion country marketing director brian osborne
ocean world, where fort lauderdale visitors can pet dolphins and watch sharks feed, reports 18 percent more visitors so far this season. the attraction does not release specific admission figures, said general manager george boucher
businesses that thrive on tourism expect the boom to continue as long as the dollar is low
the english should be here big in april,'' parrot jungle's scherr said. south americans will then travel north to avoid winter, and europeans will keep coming
eastman kodak co. will seek to complete its merger with fellow photofinishing giant colorcraft corp. now that an appeals court has ruled the two were not trying to force other companies out of the industry, a kodak spokesman said
we're absolutely gratified,'' spokesman henry kaska said monday evening after hearing of the federal court ruling. ``it does mean that we will be proceeding with that merger.''
however, kaska said it was still too early to tell when the merger would actually take place
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals on monday reversed a preliminary injunction granted to phototron corp. that blocked the kodak-colorcraft merger. the court ruled the merger was aimed at making the firms more competitive and was not an attempt to put others out of business
a lower court ruled feb. 22 that phototron had standing to challenge the merger, and that the combination of kodak and colorcraft could substantially reduce competition in the wholesale photofinishing market
kaska said the merger would not result in a monopoly of the wholesale photofinishing business and retail operations known as mini labs, but he could not immediately provide figures on how much of the market the companies would control
kodak operates 50 photofinishing labs throughout the united states, while colorcraft operates 41 labs. phototron operates nine labs in the southern and western united states
kodak and colorcraft decided to merge to make their photofinishing operations more competitive. phototron sued, asking a district court in texas to block the merger
the lower court issued a preliminary injunction, saying it was appropriate given the threat of loss and damages phototron could suffer
however, the three-judge panel of the 5th circuit said the district court had ``erred in handing down a preliminary injunction without first finding phototron had demonstrated a substantial likelihood of having suffered an antitrust injury.''
the appeals court went on to say that under a previous ruling by the u.s supreme court, a competitor can obtain a permanent injunction against a merger only if it can prove the transaction would violate antitrust laws
under cargill, a competitor ... has standing to challenge the merger if an allegation and proof of predatory pricing is made,'' the appeals court said
the panel said phototron has not offered substantial proof that the merger would fall under the predatory pricing guidelines, and therefore has not demonstrated the ``substantial likelihood'' it would prevail in a trial
phototron argued to the district court that kodak and colorcraft had undercut the price phototron offers retailers, and therefore claimed that its two competitors could be operating unprofitably and violating the predatory pricing prohibition
the appeals court said phototron must prove kodak and colorcraft are offering services below their own cost in order to satisfy the ``substantial likelihood'' requirement for a preliminary injunction
kaska said the legal obstacles have only delayed the merger several weeks. ``obviously any delay would mean a loss of revenue, but the delay was not that long,'' he said
prices on the london stock exchange moved higher tuesday, aided by modest technical strength, bargain-hunting and pre-holiday apathy
at midday, the financial times-stock exchange index of 100 selected stocks was up 11.6 points, or about 0.6 percent, at 1,758.1
gains in tokyo overnight, where the nikkei stock average rose 330.58 points, and in new york, where the dow jones industrial average was up 0.82 point on monday, were less a support for the market than a sign that markets were likely to take a temporary breather until after the easter weekend
traders depicted the london advance as a technical bounce following six consecutive days of declines
but they said the rally lacks momentum and predicted shares would not advance much further barring an unexpected move by wall street
one broker reckoned that after the four-day easter holiday, institutions could make a big showing in the market
they've got plenty of liquidity,'' he said. ``we could see quite a good rise out of that after the holiday.''
the common market's executive body has approved french government aid to giant automaker renault, but has set certain conditions on the assistance
the european economic community commission said tuesday it has approved french aid to renault of 20 billion french francs, or about $3.54 billion at current exchange rates
the decision, made a month before the french presidential elections, marked the end of a two-year investigation into government assistance to regie nationale des usines renault, which is a state agency
the decision means that the french government is authorized to proceed with a 12 billion franc write-off of renault's debt. renault had 46.4 billion francs of debt at the end of 1987
the commission said in a statement it also approved a previously-made capital injection into renault of 8 billion francs because it had not been used to undercut prices in the 12-nation common market
the commission has the power to investigate government aid to industry because of the potential anticompetitive effects of such assistance
however, the commission said it approved the aid under certain conditions, including the conversion this year of renault into a state-owned company from a state agency, which escapes company law
other conditions included the completion of an 83.4 billion franc restructuring program and a pledge from the french government not to grant further aid
the french industry ministry said in a statement in paris that the commission's decision ``was good for the company.'' it said renault would now be in a position ``to compete on an equal footing with its main competitors.''
the commission said renault had been ``particularly hard hit'' by the crisis in the common market's auto sector in the early 1980s when many companies had to reorganize their activities in the face of reduced demand and rising imports from japan
renault's restructuring plan, which runs through 1990, involves modernizing factories, cutting the workforce by at least 38,000 and reducing production capacity by more than 25 percent
the commission said the program would make a ``significant contribution'' to resolving some of the problems of the european car industry
stocks prices staged a broad-based rally in early trading today following monday's mixed performance
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 12.77 to 1,992.54 in the first half hour of trading on wall street
advancing issues outpaced declines by about 4 to 1 on the new york stock exchange, with 864 up, 220 down, and 406 unchanged
volume on the big board was about 24.21 million shares
traders attributed the improvement to several factors, including the dollar's stability in foreign exchange, which lessened fears of inflatin and higher interest rates, and some bargain hunting
the market is in an oversold condition,'' explained larry wachtel, market strategist and first vice president at prudential-bache securities inc. ``you usually snap back from that. it could be nothing more or nothing less than that.''
the nyse composite index was up 0.97 at 147.08. at the american stock exchange, the market value index rose 0.92 to 292.92
on monday, the dow jones industrial average closed a scant 0.82 higher at 1,979.77, after posting moderate declines through much of the trading session
declining issues outpaced advances by more than 2-to-1 on the nyse, with 1,059 issues falling, 468 gaining and 420 unchanged. big board volume totaled 142.82 million shares, down from 163.17 million in friday's session
spiegel inc., the mail-order retailer, has announced an agreement to acquire honeybee inc., a specialty retailer of women's apparel for $23 million
the definitive merger agreement call for spiegel to buy about 75 percent of honeybee stock from members of the controlling einbender family for $7.60 a share and to buy the rest of the stock from public shareholders for $11.18 a share
new york-based honeybee closed at $10.25 a share monday on the american stock exchange, up $2.37{ from friday's close
honeybee sells higher-priced brand name and designer women's clothing through catalogs and 18 retail stores in new york, new jersey, pennsylvania, illinois, missouri, connecticut and tennessee. it had sales of about $33 million for the year ended jan. 2
oak brook-based spiegel sells apparel, household furnishings and other general merchandise through catalogs distributed to more than 30 million u.s. households
the chicago board of trade has suspended trading in its 5-month-old cbot corporate bond index futures contract because of a lack of sustained volume
the contract, based on an index of bonds issued by 100 u.s. corporations, was launched oct. 28, nine days after the stock market collapse
the launch date, sandwiched between the market's plunge and the traditionally low-volume winter holiday season, may have been one reason for the contract's disappointing performance, william murschel, an exchange spokesman, said monday
the commodities futures trading commission approved the exchange's request to place the contract in ``dormant status,'' meaning the exchange could relaunch it at some future date, murschel said
the commodity exchange in new york also trades a corporate bond index futures contract. that contract, based on moody's investment-grade corporate bond index, was launched one day after the cbot contract and also has failed to attract much interest
japanese exports of cars, trucks and buses fell 0.3 percent last month from february 1987 levels, the japan automobile manufacturer's association announced tuesday
japan's automakers exported 528,605 vehicles last month, the association said
the decline followed a 9.1 percent slide in january and december's 2 percent climb, the first in 11 months
the environment surrounding japan's automobile exports continues to be severe,'' a jama official said. ``shipments to some markets showed growth, but those increases are marginal since they are small markets.''
exports to the country's two largest markets, the united states and the european community, remained stalled as the yen continued to climb
shipments to the united states totaled 208,266 vehicles in february, down 8.2 percent from a year earlier, while those to europe slid 5.4 percent to 133,473 vehicles
the strong yen has eroded the price-competitiveness of japanese-made autos, as well as those produced overseas
the investment firm of entertainment entrepreneur merv griffin amended a lawsuit against developer donald trump to allege the controlling shareholder in resorts international inc. schemed to depress the value of the casino operator's shares
griffin and trump are making rival bids to take over the hotel-casino concern, which has operations in new jersey and the bahamas
the amended suit, filed by the griffin co. in federal district court in manhattan, ``adds to our claims concerning mr. trump's scheme to depress the value of resorts shares and lock up his control in order to acquire resorts on the cheap.''
trump has denied the charges
the suit added no new allegations. rather it sought to buttress its existing claims with new evidence
the suit, which seeks $500 million in damages, contends trump misled other shareholders, the public and government agencies by withholding material information regarding the value of resorts
trump controls nearly all of resorts' 572,000 class b shares, which has 100 votes per share, giving him 88 percent of the company's voting power
he is offering $22 per share for the remainder of the class b stock and the company's 5.7 million shares of class a common stock, which has one vote per share
griffin initially offered $35 per share, or $225 million, for all of the company's stock. he has since boosted that offer to $295 million, allowing resorts' directors to decide how to apportion it between class a and class b stockholders
following in your father's footsteps is never easy. it's even tougher when your father built a nearly $3 billion computer company from scratch
but to hear fred wang talk, it's not that big a deal
i don't think i'm under any more stress or pressure than anybody else seems to be at work,'' said the 37-year-old president and chief operating officer of wang laboratories inc
having always worked for him, never having had a different father, never having worked for anybody else, i don't know what it's like _ i can't compare _ to be in a different environment.''
but that doesn't mean wang isn't under the gun: he must prove he can turn around a company that's had more than its share of hard times and a reputation for less-than-stellar customer service
wang, based in lowell, mass., was once a wall street darling. for over a decade its earnings increased more than 30 percent a year as its word processors became standard equipment in the secretarial suites of major corporations
but the good times collapsed in its fiscal year 1985, when, beset by the computer industry slump and its own high operating costs, wang's profit slid to $15.5 million from $210.2 million the year before
to shore up the company, the management under wang's father, an wang, went through several rounds of layoffs, pay freezes and other cost-cutting measures. but things got worse instead of better: the company reported a loss of $30 million in the quarter ended sept. 30, 1986. its stock price and its image both sagged
fred wang was named president in november 1986 and almost immediately took action. he eliminated 1,000 jobs _ on top of the 1,600 cut in 1986 and a like number the year before _ and reduced salaries by 6 percent for all u.s. employees
but things didn't improve quickly. in fact, they appeared to get worse. a little more than a month after he took office, the company announced a loss of $78.6 million in the quarter ended that dec. 30
morale among the 30,000 wang employees probably hit its nadir when that loss was announced, he recalled in an interview here
we said ok, we've really got to get the place turned around, get people focused in on, basically, expenses, getting more new orders in,'' he said
the tonic finally took its effect in the quarter ended march 31, 1987, when the company reported a profit of $5.9 million. but it still ended its fiscal 1987 a quarter later drenched in red ink _ $70.7 million worth of it
wang also changed the structure of the company, letting out some slack in the tight reins his father held by giving divisional chiefs more authority. and he launched an innovative advertising campaign _ in which actors posing as wang employees boast in computerese about their products
since the profitable quarter ended march 31, 1987, wang has recorded earnings in three more quarters, including $34.1 million in the period ended dec. 31
the mood has turned around, and i think we've done some things not only on the expense side but also on the advertising side and really on the management side to get things moving in the positive direction,'' he said
an wang, a chinese immigrant who founded the company in 1951 as a maker of custom electronics components, has denied speculation that he made his son the president because of the company's problems. instead, he said, the younger wang was ready for more responsibility. an wang remains chairman and chief executive officer
and fred wang denies that he's made any real departure from the way the company was run by his father, universally called ``doctor'' in deference to his harvard doctorate in physics. instead, wang says, he's managed to communicate better with the employees to battle corporate inertia
what sometimes gets lost in this fred vs. dr. wang issue is that a lot of the changes he has been a proponent of for some years anyway, but a lot of the people said, `we did this five years ago, that's the way we are going to do it
where he always had a grand strategy for the organization, he kept most of it in his head. ...''
wang says he never set out to work at the company, let alone run it. but when he graduated from brown university with a math degree _ after changing majors several times _ he had little career direction
so here i was, 21 years old, june of 1972, unemployed,'' he said
but since he learned to write computer programs at brown, he said he decided to work at wang
after going through the ranks in the programming department, wang moved into marketing. later, he headed the research and development operations, and served as corporate treasurer. he also is on the board of directors
now, at the helm, wang faces several challenges. in addition to maintaining profitability, he must manage the company's transition from a maker of word processsors to a broad-based seller of minicomputers, data networks and information storage and management tools, finding a niche for it alongside the giants of the computer industry, international business machines corp. and digital equipment corp
wang says he's not talking about sheer size. instead, he wants wang labs to be viewed as an industry leader in other areas, such as technology
the ads are part of the company's image-raising plan. he said they're designed ``to change the nagging image of our being a word-processing-only company to one of being a computer company that specializes in the office.''
they also serve another purpose: ``our sales people had gone through one hell of a year, with the industry slowdown and our own internal problems. we wanted them to be seen as the hero of the ad program,'' he said
grain and soybean futures opened mixed to lower today on the chicago board of trade
soybean prices were pressured by profit-taking after monday's sharp gains. but the outlook for soybeans remains bullish, said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc
i think today may be the pause that refreshes,'' lespinasse said. ``hopefully we'll resume the uptrend tomorrow.''
