prime minister margaret thatcher told parliament that there isn't any policy split between herself and chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson, the treasury's top official
both mr. lawson and i put downward pressure on inflation as topmost priority. both of us think interest rate stability can be very useful to industry,'' mrs. thatcher said tuesday in response to a question in the house of commons
it was the first time that the conservative prime minister had publicly denied a split with lawson, according to observers
after the government's recent decision to allow the british pound to rise above 3.00 west german marks, there were press reports that lawson had been against allowing the pound to rise but had been overruled by mrs. thatcher. the prime minister was more concerned about the inflationary impact of any effort to stem the pound's rise on world currency markets, the reports said
a stronger pound could hurt british exports and company profits
earlier tuesday, lawson told a gathering of the association of american correspondents in london that ``the whole (government) policy is to ensure to continue to have downward pressure on inflation.''
there is no sign whatsoever of resurgence of inflation,'' lawson said. britain's annual inflation rate is currently 3.3 percent
he said britain's intervention in the foreign-exchange markets wasn't inflationary
lawson also said he is ``perfectly satisfied'' with the current trading level of the pound against the mark
the british currency was quoted at around 3.1050 marks on tuesday afternoon in london
but lawson added that ``you shouldn't draw the conclusion from that that there is a target'' for the pound against the mark
lawson's lack of concern about the current inflation rate might mean there is room for british interest rates to fall further. the banks' base lending rate currently stands at 8.5 percent
the reported policy split between mrs. thatcher and lawson fueled speculation in recent weeks that he would resign his post, which he has held since 1983
i haven't formed myself a view of how long i will remain chancellor,'' lawson said. ``i am not worn out and you can see my hair hasn't turned gray.'' but he also said that no one holds a job forever, and added, ``i have been chancellor longer than most.''
lawson also said he wasn't particularly concerned about britain's widening trade deficit, ``provided there is no resurgence of inflation.''
the treasury is forecasting a doubling this year of the current-account deficit to 4 billion pounds, or about $7 billion. but the government on friday reported a worse-than-expected february deficit of 1.56 billion pounds, or around $2.9 billion, which made the financial markets nervous
