american stores co. says it is prepared to increase its offer for lucky stores inc. to more than $1.9 billion if a friendly merger of the two grocery store chains can be worked out
american also filed a lawsuit in delaware state court to enjoin lucky officers from defending against american's unsolicited tender offer, indicating american may be bracing for a takeover battle
in a letter to the board of the dublin, calif.-based lucky late monday, american chairman l.s. skaggs said his company was ready to offer $50 per share if a ``mutually acceptable agreement'' could be worked out with lucky
earlier in the day, american launched a cash tender offer for lucky at $45 per share, or a total of $1.74 billion. that offer expires at midnight april 22
we made clear our willingness to negotiate concerning all aspects of our offer, including the price,'' said skaggs in his letter to lucky
so far lucky's representatives have declined to negotiate
american stores vice president michael holt today said the company would have no comment on either the lawsuit or increased stock cash offer. lucky officials were not available to discuss the matter this morning
the combination of american, the nation's third-largest grocery retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion, and lucky, the sixth-largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion, could produce the biggest grocery retailer in the country, analysts say
lucky officials were not immediately available for comment on the latest developments, which were announced in a press release after the close of stock trading
lucky shares advanced 87{ cents to close at $48.62{, while american shares lost $1.75 to finish at $54.87{ on the new york stock exchange
before american revealed the contents of its letter, lucky spokeswoman lissa perlman said company officials had been reviewing the offer with financial and legal advisers since last week
ms. perlman said lucky was advising stockholders not to take any action on the american offer until lucky's board of directors has a chance to study the bid and make its recommendation
american's lawsuit, filed friday in wilmington, del., alleges lucky and its executives have breached their fiduciary duties by ``following a course of conduct directed towards entrenching themselves in control of lucky stores.''
in the lawsuit, american said its representatives met with lucky's march 21 to announce the tender offer. american claimed the $45 offered for each lucky common share is about 40 percent over the market price of the company's stock immediately before the offer
american said its representatives advised lucky chairman john m. lillie that their company preferred to negotiate a friendly acquisition and requested a prompt meeting to do so
but ``within hours of this meeting, lucky ... set out on a course of conduct which would deny the lucky stockholders a premium price for their shares and would preserve the position of the company's management and the board,'' the suit alleged
the lawsuit further claimed that lucky initially threatened to take injunctive action against american and urged the utah company to delay its tender share filings with the securities and exchange commission, not to publicize the offer and to consider certain arrangements between the two companies leading to abandonment of the offer
based on those attempts, the lawsuit said, american believes lucky's management ``will continue to refuse to negotiate seriously ... and will employ an array of defensive measures to prevent the acquisition of the company in violation of the defendant's fiduciary obligation and duties to its stockholders.''
in a march 26 letter telling lillie of the takeover plans, skaggs praised lucky's management and marketing strategies and invited lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed
lucky's headquarters would remain in dublin, skaggs said
the bid for lucky came 16 months after takeover specialist asher edelman dropped his hostile effort to acquire the company. in return, lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills
lucky kept edelman at bay partially by selling off its non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures
after the text of the letter was released last week, lucky officials had no comment on the american's tender offer except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
in 1984, american spent $1.1 billion to take over jewel companies inc., a chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store chain
that acquisition expanded american's operations from just over 1,000 retail outlets to its present 1,700. the company has three divisions _ skaggs, which operates supermarkets in the western united states; american superstores, which runs outlets in the midwest and east, and osco drug stores, which has stores nationwide
the company operates stores under the names acme, jewel, star, buttrey, skaggs, skaggs alpha beta, and osco drug
british aerospace plc said tuesday it reached an agreement, as planned, to acquire rover group plc from the british government, for 150 million pounds, or $279 million
british aerospace said that after it acquired the government's 99.8 percent stake in the automaker, the government would make a cash injection of 800 million pounds, or $1.49 billion, into rover to cover the car maker's debt
british aerospace said the acquisition is conditional on approval of the cash injection by the european commission, and on the approval of british aerospace shareholders
rover's board of directors said it welcomed the agreement
british aerospace said it ``intends to hold and develop the principal businesses of the rover group.''
the group is made up of the austin rover carmaker and the land rover utility vehicle maker. it sold off its leyland truck operations last year
the government took over the automaker, then called british leyland, in 1975 to prevent its collapse. it sold off jaguar plc, the luxury automaker, in july 1984
british aerospace agreed to make unspecified payments to the government if it decides to sell any of rover's principal businesses as going concerns
rover recently announced trading profit, or profit before tax and interest charges, of 27.9 million pounds, or $52 million, for 1987. that compared with a trading loss of 355.6 million pounds, or $661 million, in 1986
british aerospace said it also intends to purchase the remaining 0.2 percent of rover shares, which are held by private investors. the company will detail the terms of that offer to the private shareholders after it secures the other approvals
british aerospace said it values rover's existing production agreements with the japanese automaker, honda motor co., and ``wishes to build upon that relationship.''
rover chairman graham day said the british aerospace deal ``offers a speedy route to privatization with the minimum disruption to our management, work force, dealer networks and suppliers.''
trade secretary lord young had announced in march that british aerospace had shown a serious interest in acquiring rover, which the government previously had said it intended to privatize
british aerospace makes a variety of airplanes and aerospace products for civilian and military use, and makes wings for airbus industrie, the european civilian aircraft consortium
