officials of ibp inc. said they will build a $40 million state-of-the-art hog processing plant at waterloo
we truly believe that waterloo will be good for ibp and ibp will be good for waterloo,'' ibp chairman robert l. peterson told a tuesday news conference
the pork and beef processing giant said in november 1986 it was considering building a plant in northeastern iowa. the company focused attention on a delaware county site south of manchester before opposition arose to ibp plans to dump treated sewage into tributaries of the maquoketa river
ibp will begin construction on the 365,000-square-foot plant this spring at a 130-acre site in northeastern waterloo. completion of the plant is expected to take a year and a half
when at full capacity, the plant will employ 1,200 to 1,500 people with an annual plyroll of more than $20 million and will process 4 million hogs a year. ibp currently has four pork plants _ at storm lake, louisa county and council bluffs in iowa and madison, neb. _ and employs 20,000 people at 15 plants in eight states
corporate raider carl c. icahn will not take over texaco inc., which is coming out of bankruptcy, company president james kinnear predicted today
icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of texaco and is the oil giant's largest single shareholder, has threatened to run a panel of five candidates for the texaco's 14-member board at the next annual meeting unless texaco offers to put itself up for sale
but kinnear, whose seat on the board of directors also is threatened for takeover, said texaco management will do its best to keep icahn out. texaco officials have repeatedly said the company is not for sale
he recently said in public that he has no intention of being on texaco's board or wanting to take control of the company, but the next day he said he might run a proxy slate,'' kinnear told a news conference. ``i just don't know what his intentions are. my prediction is that he will not take over this company.''
kinnear did not elaborate on the strategy for keeping icahn from making a run at the company
icahn is not the only takeover artist known to be interested in texaco. oilman t. boone pickens has said he is seeking federal regulatory permission to acquire 15 percent or more of texaco's stock, as has getty petroleum co., a large independent distributor that was born of texaco's takeover of getty oil
kinnear talked to reporters after a speech to the national petroleum refiners association
he said the company would become leaner and stronger by selling some assets to clear up its huge debt
last week, a u.s. bankruptcy court judge approved a reorganization plan that will enable texaco to emerge from chapter 11 protection early next month
texaco filed for that protection last april to avoid having to post an $11 billion security bond while appealing a $10.3 billion judgment against the company held by houston-based pennzoil co
the judgment stemmed from a november 1985 ruling by a houston jury that texaco had improperly interfered with a pennzoil bid to acquire part of getty oil co., then bought getty itself
texaco's reorganization plan calls for payment of $5.6 billion, with $3 billion going to pennzoil to drop the judgment and the rest going to creditors
texaco expects to sell $3 billion in assets to finance the program, kinnear said
in his speech, kinnear said that the petrochemical industry could profit if it remains lean
u.s. chemical manufacturers must adjust their thinking to a slower-growth economy and to competition from new players,'' he said. ``revamping facilities, stretching existing units, or making strategic acquisitions will generally yield far greater returns than investing in new, grassroots plants with the expectation of growing to full capacity in two or three years.''
