sundstrand corp., a major aerospace contractor, has agreed in principle to plead guilty to filing false statements with the government and pay $12.5 million for overcharging on military work, a newspaper reported
the proposed plea agreement covers allegations that the company's seattle-based sundstrand data control unit improperly included patent-litigation expenses in overhead costs on government military contracts, the wall street journal reported tuesday, quoting unidentified sources
sundstrand said in a filing with the securities and exchange commission that it expected to face unspecified criminal charges in both washington state and illinois in connection with federal grand jury investigations of its accounting methods for handling government contracts and tax matters
the government has advised that it intends to charge the company with criminal violations in both districts,'' sundstrand's filing stated
the document also reported that the company, rockford's largest employer, was working on a settlement in one, and possibly both, of the actions
federal charges could lead to the suspension of new government contracts for sundstrand, which had $579 million in military sales in 1987
but if the company settled the dispute by paying ``materially adverse fines and penalties,'' it might be suspended only temporarily from new government business, according to sundstrand's filing
the 12-nation european economic community loses at least $250 billion a year in extra costs and lost economic opportunities by staying divided along national borders, a two-year study concludes
the study, which was released tuesday, is designed to give economic undepinning to the trade bloc's plan to abolish national frontiers and create a single european market by the end of 1992
the report concluded that fusing the economies of the individual member states into one would add 5 percent to the bloc's gross domestic product and create up to 5 million new jobs
the report was prepared by a team of economists supervised by paolo cecchini, a former senior eec official,
jacques delors, president of the eec executive commission, said at a press conference that he hoped the report would launch a european debate about economic integration. ``we are simply providing food for thought ... we want to get a debate going,'' he said
he said the purpose of the study was not to provide an economic forecast, but rather to outline the economic potential of a europe united in a single market
lord arthur cockfield, the eec commissioner responsible for the integration process, gave a more prosaic appraisal of the study: ``we wanted to show there is a lot more juice to be squeezed from this particular lemon.''
pointing to the more than 6,000 pages that the report and its underlying studies contain, cockfield said, ``nothing like it has ever been done before.''
he said the results show ``clearly the extent to which the division of europe results in non-competitive behavior, missed opportunities, high unemployment and higher prices.''
according to the study, the eec stands to gain from market integration the equivalent of at least $250 billion a year, largely by foregoing the cost of border controls and by improving productivity and competitiveness
abolishing controls and removing non-tariff barriers to trade, the report concluded, could save up to $99.2 billion and shave as much as 3.5 percent of the cost of products
an additional $75.6 billion could be gained from ``exploiting economies of scale more fully,'' the report estimated
restoring competition in state-controlled industries and reducing ``business ineffectiveness'' would add $57 billion in economic benefits, the report said
the study predicted that in addition to boosting output, employment and the standard of living, the creation of a single market would ``simultaneously cool the economy, deflating consumer prices by an average of 6 percent.''
deregulation of public transport, the energy industry, banking, indurance and defence procurement would lead to price cuts of up to 20 percent, the report said
the report estimated that market integration alone would add 4.5 percent to the gross domestic product and add 2 million new jobs. but if combined with tax reduction and increased spending, the report said, a single market would boost gross domestic product by 7 percent and create 5 million new jobs
the report did not estimate which eec countries would benefit most from the single market, but said all 12 were likely to ``make substantial economic gains.''
