a law that barred publisher rupert murdoch from continuing to own television stations and newspapers in the same city was struck down today as unconstitutional by a federal appeals court
the divided panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals here voided a provision passed by congress late last year that would force murdoch to sell the boston herald or wfxt-tv in that city by june 30 to comply with rules that forbid single ownership of a newspaper and a television station in one city
the 2-1 court decision does not affect murdoch's $37 million sale of the new york post to real estate developer peter kalikow, a deal that was spurred by the law's enactment as part of a massive spending bill
in his contract to sell the post, murdoch retained the right to make the first offer for the paper if kalikow should decide to sell. howard j. rubenstein, spokesman for both men, said the contract obliges kalikow to allow murdoch to make a ``first offer'' for the paper, but does not oblige kalikow to accept it
but lawrence kessler, general counsel for news america, said murdoch was not contemplating repurchasing the post, which kalikow says he is committed to turning into a profitable newspaper. kessler also said he was ``heartened and encouraged that the court of appeals shared our concern for the protection of publishers' constitutional rights.''
the court's ruling could enable murdoch to retain temporarily ownership of both his boston media outlets if the federal communications commission extends his waiver from the enforcement of the common-ownership rule
the court ordered the fcc to consider murdoch's application to extend the temporary waiver that he has held since 1986
murdoch charged that the law forbidding the fcc to extend his temporary waivers for both the new york post and the boston herald was politically motivated and amounted to an unconstitutional attempt to silence criticism of sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., by the herald
the court ruled that the provision of a massive spending bill was unconstitutional because it singled out murdoch's news america inc
while the court declined to inquire into congress's motives, it concluded that the provison ``strikes at murdoch with the precision of a laser beam,'' and therefore violates the equal protection clause of the constitution
the amendment to the spending bill prohibited the fcc from extending temporary waivers to the common-ownership rules. it was sponsored by sen. ernest hollings, d-s.c. and supported by kennedy
the court did not rule on the merits of any claim that murdoch's news america publishing inc. should retain ownership of both the herald and wfxt-tv. but the judges cleared the way for murdoch to seek an extension of the june 30 deadline for complying with the common-ownership rules
murdoch has indicated he wanted to retain the herald and sell the television station if forced to do so
the court ruled that because murdoch's company was the sole holder of temporary waivers specified in the hollins amendment, the law was aimed solely at him
because the law appears to serve no legitimate purpose except to prohibit murdoch from obtaining extensions of his waivers, it unconstitutionally singled him out, the court said
congress's exclusive focus on a single party clearly implicates values similar to those behind the constitutional proscription of bills of attainder,'' judge stephen williams wrote in an opinion joined by judge laurence silberman. such bills are aimed at specific individuals
the safeguards of a pluralistic political system are often absent when the legislature zeroes in on a small class of citizens,'' he wrote
nowhere are the protections of the equal protection clause more critical than when legislation singles out one or a few for uniquely disfavored treatment,'' williams said
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., who had the legislation attached to the spending bill, said in a statement that the court's decision does not mean murdoch should retain ownership of his boston newspaper and television station
nothing in the constitution or even the court's decision says that rupert murdoch is entitled to be the only newspaper owner in american who can buy a broadcasting station and keep his newspaper in the same community,'' kennedy said
he said he continues to believe ``that congress was on sound constitutional grounds when it adopted the provision, and that the right of congress to take this action will be vindicated by the supreme court if the parties appeal today's decision.''
a stable dollar and lower interest rates helped push stock prices sharply higher today, with the dow jones industrial average surpassing the 2,000-mark again
the closely watched index of 30 industrial stocks jumped 23.88 to 2,003.65 with an hour to go on wall street. on monday it closed a scant 0.82 higher, while other indicators registered a loss
the broader market also posted gains today. advancing issues outpaced declines by 7 to 3 among issues listed on the new york stock exchange, with 1,022 up, 443 down, and 472 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 126.78 million shares as of 3 p.m. est, compared with 118.6 million shares at the same point in monday's session
traders said the dollar's improvement in foreign exchange trading helped stock prices by easing inflation fears and pushing interest rates lower
the fact that the dollar has stabilized and is no longer going into a free-fall, that's a psychological prop,'' said larry wachtel, market strategist and first vice president at prudential-bache securities inc. ``the market is in an oversold condition.''
hugh johnson, chief investment officer at first albany corp., said a report showing the index of leading indicators _ the government's chief economic forecsting gauge _ rose 0.9 percent in february also lent support to stock prices. the index had fallen in three of the past four months
maybe those fears that the economy is going to run out of steam either this year or next year are unfounded,'' he said
