roper corp.'s board of directors changed sides tuesday in the takeover fight for the appliance manufacturer, saying stockholders should sell to general electric co. instead of whirlpool corp
roper's board determined that ge's $508 million tender offer was clearly superior to whirlpool's $470 million one, the company said in withdrawing a recommendation of whirlpool made march 18
discussions with whirlpool ... have not to date led whirlpool to propose an increase in the price offered for roper shares,'' roper's statement said
the battle began in february when roper announced it had agreed to be acquired by whirlpool for $37.50 for each of roper's 9.4 million shares outstanding, or about $352.5 million. general electric then entered the fray with a bid of $45 per share, or $423 million
both companies have since increased their bids, with ge's currently at $54 per share and whirlpool's at $50
whirlpool and ge have filed federal court suits challenging each others' actions, with ge claiming the roper board failed to tell stockholders of an earlier interest in the company and whirlpool complaining ge was trying to sabotage an already announced deal. hearings are scheduled this week in whirlpool's suit
the board said roper stockholders should withdraw their shares already offered to whirlpool and tender them to ge instead
whirlpool, in a statement issued from its benton harbor, mich., headquarters, said the company will continue to pursue roper
our definitive merger agreement with roper still stands,'' david r. whitwam, whirlpool's president, chairman and chief executive, said in the statement. ``the roper board's action is disappointing in light of its corporate charter to consider the best interests of all constituents. ... however, it is understandable in view of the current price differential and the pressures being applied by ge.''
roper employs about 4,750 people, 3,000 of them in four georgia plants. in addition to electric and gas appliances, the company manufactures tillers, lawn mowers and lawn and garden tractors. its customers include sears roebuck &amp; co., the nation's largest retailer
it also manufactures some ge ranges, and the fairfield, conn.-based company has said its interest in roper stems from that association
roper had net income of $24 million on $703 million in sales for the fiscal year ended july 31
ge, which also has financial and broadcasting interests, had 1987 revenues of $40.5 billion and net income of $2.9 billion. its major appliance business was responsible for $4.72 billion in revenue and a pretax operating profit of $490 million
whirlpool had $4.2 billion in sales last year. counter</head>
odyssey partners sweetened its tender offer for j.p. stevens &amp; co. to $1.14 billion tuesday, but analysts predicted further bidding in the battle for the textile giant
west point-pepperell inc., which has made a $1.1 billion bid for stevens, is expected to compete fiercely for the crown jewels _ three state-of-the-art factories and licenses for hot designer labels that lure consumers around the world to stevens' quality sheets and towels
odyssey, a new york investment firm, said it would pay $64 for each of stevens' 17.8 million outstanding shares, up from the $61.50-a-share tender offer stevens' management accepted earlier this month
in ``consideration'' for the sweetened offer, stevens' board agreed to pay odyssey up to $8 million if it is acquired by a third party for more than $64 a share
pepperell made its $62.50-a-share bid after stevens forged its agreement with odyssey. pepperell had said it might be willing to increase its offer to $64 a share if stevens agreed to a friendly deal
a spokesman at pepperell's headquarters in west point, ga., had no comment after odyssey announced its increased offer
but asked in an interview last week whether pepperell would consider raising its offer above the conditional $64 a share, chairman joseph l. lanier said, ``i wouldn't preclude it.''
in afternoon trading on the new york stock exchange, stevens rose 37{ cents to $64.87{a share
odyssey partner brian d. young noted in a statement that while odyssey's bid matched what pepperell said it was prepared to pay under friendly terms, odyssey's tender offer expires on april 11 _ 10 days ahead of pepperell's offer
investors are likely to find the earlier expiration attractive unless pepperell raises its bid
west point-pepperell wants stevens very badly,'' said george zimmerman, director of research at gruntal &amp; co
the acquisition would quickly further pepperell in its goal of becoming a major international marketer of branded products
not only does stevens have some of the best brand names in the business, but they have bigger international operations, particularly in canada and japan,'' said josephine esquivel, a textile analyst at shearson lehman hutton inc
pepperell's brands include arrow, martex, lady pepperell and burberrys. among stevens' arsenal of top designer names are ralph lauren, laura ashley, pierre cardin, vanderbilt, perry ellis and givenchy
in addition to the attraction of the licenses to use those names, pepperell is keen on acquiring stevens' sheet plant in clemson, s.c., and two top towel plants in wagram, n.c., analysts agreed
how much higher pepperell can go is another matter. esquivel noted that the company's debt-to-equity ratio, currently at 28 percent, would jump to 63 percent based on a $64-a-share tender offer
odyssey's young has charged that a pepperell merger with stevens would violate antitrust laws
pepperell has sought to soothe potential antitrust concerns with a plan that includes the sale of half of stevens' bath lines and 20 percent of its sheet lines for about $170 million. pepperell signed a definitive agreement for the sale with ntc group, parent of bibb co., a textile manufacturer
but young said the proposed sale to bibb ``does not cure the antitrust problems.'' he said odyssey will ``strongly present our views to the appropriate governmental authorities and will continue to oppose any amended proposal if we believe that the antitrust problems have not been solved.''
bidding for stevens began after it received a leveraged buyout offer several weeks ago from a group led by its own senior management, including chairman whitney stevens _ a fifth-generation member of the family that founded the company in 1813
the management group initially offered $43 a share and later sweetened its bid to $55 a share in cash and securities. in a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely with borrowed money repaid with a target company's profits or the sale of assets
the stock market was broadly higher today, bolstered by a stable dollar, lower interest rates and some positive economic news
five minutes before the close, the closely watched dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 18.24 to 1,998.01
new home sales, which had fallen for three months following the october collapse of the stock market, soared 20.3 percent in february, the fastest increase in almost two years, the government said tuesday
the commerce department said that new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 628,000 units. it was the first monthly increase since a 1.4 percent rise in october, but it still left sales 14.9 percent below where they were a year ago
sales had fallen 10.3 percent in january, 6.8 percent in december and 4.2 percent in november, declines which analysts had blamed on high mortgage rates and consumer jitters following the record plunge in stock prices that occurred on oct. 19
because housing is often the first sector to weaken at the start of a new recession, the string of declines had raised concerns about whether another downturn was imminent
but analysts said the strong february rebound erased those worries and indicated housing should strengthen further in coming months
the february numbers spell relief and optimism,'' said david seiders, chief economist for the national association of home builders. ``we feel we are back on track where we should be.''
james christian, chief economist of the u.s. league of savings institutions, said the february housing performance ``is another piece of evidence that we are shrugging off the aftershocks from the stock market crash.''
christian predicted that new home sales would rise further during the spring sales season and help boost sales for the entire year to around 650,000. while that would be down from the 671,000 new homes sold in 1987, it would still be considered a strong sales year for the industry
analysts said it is unlikely that mortgage rates will fall much further. fixed-rate mortgages currently stand at 9.99 percent, down from a high last year of 11.58 percent just before the stock market decline
economists predicted rates would begin rising later this spring and would probably top 11 percent by the end of the year
the economy is too strong and the dollar is too weak to believe that interest rates will go down from here,'' said martin regalia, chief economist of the national council of savings institutions
the big february sales rebound was the largest monthly increase since a 21 percent gain in march 1986. it was accompanied by a sharp decline in prices, reflecting in part the re-entry into the market of first-time buyers, who normally buy less expensive homes
the median, or mid-point, price of new homes was $110,800 in february, down 6.1 percent from the record january price of $118,000
the average price of a new home fell 4.6 percent to $139,000 last month, down from $145,700 in january
the big jump in sales was propelled by a 42.9 percent surge in sales in the south. this region of the country, which accounts for 40 percent of all new homes sold, is still 9.6 percent below the year-earlier sales pace
sales were up 29.3 percent in the northeast and 18.2 percent in the midwest. the west was the only region of the country to suffer a sales decline in february, a drop of 7.1 percent
sundstrand corp. has agreed in principle to plead guilty to filing false statements with the government and to pay $12.5 million in connection with alleged overcharges on defense contracts, according to published reports tuesday
sundstrand corp., an aerospace contractor, previously revealed in a financial filing with the government that it would face criminal charges resulting from two federal grand jury investigations into alleged overcharges
the wall street journal reported tuesday that sundstrand had agreed to the guilty plea and payment in one of those investigations and that justice department officials hoped to gain an agreement in the second, larger investigation
sundstrand reported a year ago that the government was seeking repayment of $13.5 million plus interest and $102.9 million plus interest in two separate disputes over contract pricing
the journal said the two cases, taken together, could result in the largest total payment ever for alleged military contracting fraud
claude bernam, a spokesman for sundstrand, referred inquiries about the investigations to the company's lawyers, who were not available for comment
in a report filed recently with the federal securities and exchange commission, sundstrand acknowledged the ``government has advised that it intends to charge the company with criminal violations'' in both rockford and seattle
sundstrand is based in rockford and operates a subsidiary in redmond, wash., near seattle, that is part of its advanced technology group
sundstrand, which makes flight data equipment, engine start-up systems and other electronic equipment for commercial and military aircraft, said in its sec filing that it was ``in the process of entering a settlement in one or possibly both actions.''
such settlements, the company also noted in the filing, ``could result in the imposition of materially adverse fines and penalties.''
in the seattle case, the newspaper said sundstrand failed to disclose improper accounting procedures during negotiations with the defense department. in the rockford case, sundstrand allegedly charged private commercial costs to air force and navy contracts and subcontracts
sundstrand's military sales last year amounted to $574 million and accounted for more than half of all sales in the aerospace segment
in 1986, sundstrand put aside $61.5 million to cover settlement and legal expenses relating to the government disputes. as a result, 1986 profits were down 39 percent
one analyst said sundstrand has the market presence to weather a temporary halt in government business
the question is, is this jeopardizing on a long-term basis,'' said steven colbert, at prudential-bache securities. ``the answer right now is, `i don't think so.' right now they have very strong market share.'' 
the stock market pulled out of its slump today, bolstered by a more stable dollar, lower interest rates and some positive news about the economy
analysts, however, were uncertain whether today's broad-based rally represented a bullish trend or just a much-needed respite following three sessions of losses
in light of what we've seen in the equity market today ... much of this action is almost like an oversold bounce,'' said dennis e. jarrett, a technical analyst for kidder, peabody &amp; co. ``it's too early to say whether it's sustainable.''
the dollar's improvement in foreign exchange trading helped stock prices by easing inflation fears and pushing interest rates lower, analysts said. a sharp decline in the u.s. currency had been largely responsible for driving down the stock market on monday
the fact that the dollar has stabilized and is no longer going into a free-fall, that's a psychological prop,'' said larry wachtel, market strategist and first vice president at prudential-bache securities inc
the dollar was aided today by central bank intervention and remarks from japan's foreign minister, kiichi miyazawa, who called for major industrialized nations to follow last year's currency stabilization accord
hugh johnson, chief investment officer at first albany corp., said a report showing the index of leading indicators _ the government's chief economic forecsting gauge _ gained 0.9 percent in february also lent support to stock prices. the index had fallen in three of the past four months
maybe those fears that the economy is going to run out of steam either this year or next year are unfounded,'' johnson said
the senate on tuesday effectively rejected legislation to warn up to 300,000 workers a year they risk cancer and other diseases from occupational exposure to toxic chemicals
on a 52-42 vote, senate sponsors of the house-passed measured failed by 18 of the 60 votes necessary on a fourth attempt to break off a conservative republican filibuster over the past eight days against the union-sought bill
the bill's author, sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, conceded defeat but said the issue will not go away
in this one i've lost,'' he said. ``but as long as workers are kept in the dark about occupational hazards, we will continue to try to bring them light
the defeat was the first for the afl-cio on the senate floor since helping return the 100-member body to democratic control. but 15 of the senate's 54 democrats, most of them from the south, ended up siding with the leader of the filibuster, sen. orrin hatch, r-utah
we've had 50 years of these type of give-away programs that don't work,'' said hatch, who claimed the measure could cost businesses up to $7 billion if exposed workers began filing and winning liability suits against their current and former employers
the bill was aimed at addressing what the national institute of occupational safety and health estimates is one in every four americans who has been exposed to carcinogens at work, most of them unaware of it
metzenbaum, the measure's chief sponsor, repeatedly cited american cancer society estimates that warnings to at-risk workers could have saved 250,000 lives over the next 10 years
tens of thousands of american workers are dying each year from occupational diseases and could prevent many of these deaths ... by telling them the truth that they are at risk,'' he said
metzenbaum accused the national association of manufacturers and the u.s. chamber of commerce of waging an ``orchestrated campaign of misrepresentation, innuendo and hype'' in citing the potential costs to employers
alexander trowbridge, the nam's president, called metzenbaum's charge ``irresponsible,'' saying worker health is a prime concern of every responsible manager in the country
we care a great deal about preventing disease from happening rather than discovering it after the fact, which is what his proposal would bring about,'' trowbridge said
the bill would have established a panel of seven scientific experts to identify the most hazardous substances in workplaces and the groups of employees most susceptible to disabling diseases because of exposure to them
niosh would have been required to individually notify between 100,000 and 300,000 of those at-risk workers every year at an annual cost of $25 million. employers then would be required to finance medical monitoring program for them at a cost of up to $250 each annually
if a physician recommended transferring a monitored employee to less hazardous work, he or she would have had to be paid the same level of wages and benefits to them in the new job. if no other job is available, the employee would have been entitled to full wages for up to a year after leaving work
in addition to unions, the bill was supported by public health and environmental groups, the chemical and electronic industries and several giant companies, most of which have instituted such notification programs on their own. 03-29 0094</first>
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 18.57 to 1,998.34
advancing issues outpaced declines by about 13 to 6 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,015 up, 467 down and 482 unchanged
big board volume totaled 152.69 million shares, against 142.82 million in the previous session
the nyse's composite index climbed 1.11 to 147.22
at the american stock exchange, the market value index stood at 294.33, up 2.33. cross-ownership</head> ... today's decision.; and subs 26th graf pvs, the issue ... further action., to clarify that fcc barred from acting during current fiscal year. also on general news wires.</note>
congress unconstitutionally singled out publisher rupert murdoch by prohibiting his continued ownership of newspapers and television stations in the same city, an appeals court ruled tuesday
a recently enacted provision barring the federal communications commission from extending temporary waivers from its cross-ownership rule is unconstitutional because it ``strikes at murdoch with the precision of a laser beam'' without a legitimate purpose, the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington ruled in a 2-1 opinion
the law violates the the constitution's equal protection clause as well as the first amendment's guarantee of freedom of the press, the court said
the decision means murdoch may petition the fcc to extend past june 30 the waiver that allows his news american publishing inc. to own both the boston herald and that city's wfxt-tv
murdoch also had sought an extension of a waiver that allowed him to own both the new york post and wnyw-tv until march 6, but the newspaper was sold earlier this month for $37 million to real estate developer peter kalikow. the decision, therefore, won't affect the post's sale
lawrence kessler, general counsel for news america, said murdoch has no plans to repurchase the newspaper in light of the court's ruling
the provision that banned the cross-ownership waiver extension had been tucked quietly into a massive spending bill last december by sens. ernest hollings, d-s.c., and edward m. kennedy, d-mass
in its ruling tuesday, the court said the ban was so narrowly drawn that it applied only to murdoch _ who held the only two waivers from the cross-ownership rule
the court is saying congress ``should not enact legislation that is aimed in a punitive way at a single individual,'' said howard squadron, a new york attorney who argued the case for news america
i would think it's a benefit to all people who enjoy the first amendment freedom,'' squadron said
howard rubinstein, a spokesman for both news america and kalikow, said news america was ``gratified'' with the court's ruling and that kalikow has instructed his attorneys to seek to purchase a radio station or television station in new york city. he would not name stations
rubinstein said kalikow will challenge the cross-ownership rule itself because he believes the reasons for the rule no longer exist since there are an ample number of radio and televison stations
the fcc, which defended the law's constitutionality but not the policy it enacted, appeared as pleased with the decision as murdoch's lawyers
the court by this decision has demonstrated that the congress does not have a free hand in the regulation of the broadcast press,'' fcc chairman dennis r. patrick said in a statement. ``i am pleased the court will hold the congress to a higher standard when first amendment freedoms are implicated.''
the court did not specify how the commission should rule on murdoch's request for an extension except to say political pressure from congress should ``play no role in agency adjudications involving important constitutional rights.''
the court found that the law had no other purpose than to prohibit extensions of the waivers and therefore unconstitutionally targeted a specific individual for no legitimate purpose, the court said
congress's exclusive focus on a single party clearly implicates values similar to those behind the constitutional prosription of bills of attainders,'' judge stephen williams wrote in an opinion joined by judge laurence silberman. bills of attainder are aimed at specific people
murdoch and some politicians had criticized the ban as an attempt to muzzle the conservative editorial policies of the newspapers, particularly the herald, which repeatedly has been critical of kennedy
kennedy and hollings, however, said they merely were trying to force murdoch to comply with rules that other publishers must observe
in a statement tuesday, kennedy said the court's decision does not mean murdoch should retain ownership of his boston newspaper and television station
nothing in the constitution or even the court's decision says that rupert murdoch is entitled to be the only newspaper owner in american who can buy a broadcasting station and keep his newspaper in the same community,'' kennedy said
he said he believed congress ``will be vindicated by the supreme court if the parties appeal today's decision.''
hollings, meanwhile, said the court ``has arrested the policeman on the beat, while the culprit has gone free.'' he called the decision a ``legal contortion'' that ``set up murdoch for special treatment.''
while the court did not speculate on the senators' motives, it noted the provision did not bar new temporary waivers that are normally extended to give a company time to divest itself of a tv station or newspaper acquired during a merger or acquisition
nor did congress mention waivers from the cross-ownership rules, the court said
in dissent, circuit judge spotswood robinson said ``congress pursued a wholly legitimate purpose when it acted to protect the cross-ownership rule from circumvention or erosion.''
even though a statute so narrowly drawn ``naturally arouses suspicions about its legal propriety,'' robinson concluded that congress ``selected a method that was more than adequately related to the purpose it sought to achieve.''
the issue arose last fall when the fcc was asked in a petition to consider abolishing the cross-ownership rule. the fcc said it would solicit comments on the idea but the law's enactment barred the agency from taking further action during the current fiscal year
murdoch, meanwhile, has indicated he would keep the herald and sell his boston tv outlet if the fcc forces him to divest one of the properties
a stable dollar, lower interest rates and some positive news about the economy helped push the slumping stock market broadly higher tuesday
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks closed up 18.57 to 1,998.34, after venturing across the 2,000-mark during the afternoon. the closely watched index had lost more than 80 points since thursday
the broader market also gained ground tuesday. about 13 stocks rose in value for every six that fell on the new york stock exchange, with 1,015 up, 467 down and 482 unchanged
as measured by wilshire associates 500 equity index, stocks gained $18.5 billion in value
volume on the big board totaled 152.69 million shares, higher than the 142.82 million shares that changed hands in the previous session
stock prices started out on a strong note with the help of the dollar's advance in foreign exchange, which, in turn, eased inflation fears and pushed interest rates lower. a sharp decline in the u.s. currency had been largely responsible for the market's recent losses
the fact that the dollar has stabilized and is no longer going into a free-fall, that's a psychological prop,'' said larry wachtel, market strategist and first vice president at prudential-bache securities inc
the dollar was aided in part by reports of central bank intervention
hugh johnson, chief investment officer at first albany corp., said a report showing the index of leading indicators _ the government's chief economic forecasting gauge _ gained 0.9 percent in february also lent support to stock prices. the index had fallen in three of the past four months
maybe those fears that the economy is going to run out of steam either this year or next year are unfounded,'' johnson said
analysts said they were uncertain whether tuesday's rally represented a bullish trend or just a much-needed respite following three disappointing sessions
in light of what we've seen in the equity market today ... much of this action is almost like an oversold bounce,'' said dennis e. jarrett, a technical analyst for kidder, peabody &amp; co. ``it's too early to say whether it's sustainable.''
among most actively traded blue-chip issues, american telephone and telegraph was up [ at 26~; ibm fell 2\ to 105~; general electric rose [ to 41[; and exxon was down \ to 42]
texaco jumped 3\ to 48, after kohlberg kravis roberts said it would seek federal permission to buy up to 15 percent of the oil giant's shares
rjr nabisco was up 4[ to 52[. the company said it planned to buy back as much as 8 percent of its stock
lucky stores rose 1\ to 49~. american stores co. said it was prepared to raise its offer for lucky to more than $1.9 billion if a friendly merger of the two grocery store chains can be achieved
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 178.58 million shares
the nyse's composite index climbed 1.11 to 147.22
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials rose 2.62 to 301.70, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was up 2.01 to 260.07
at the american stock exchange, the market value index stood at 294.33, up 2.33. the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market closed at 372.96, up 2.54
the dollar surged upward tuesday from its lowest point since early january, responding favorably to reports of modest efforts by central banks to support it
gold prices edged higher. republic national bank of new york said gold was bid at $455.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from $455.10 late monday
there were conflicting reports on the extent of intervention by central banks, although traders agreed the bank of japan bought some dollars with yen in the tokyo market
the federal reserve bank of new york also bought dollars tuesday, said david h. arbesman, president of kemper currency inc
the rally generated by reports of the central banks' action squeezed out investors who had bet on further declines in the dollar, forcing them to buy dollars to cover borrowed positions, arbesman said
traders who bought dollars were pushing aside the concerns that have sent the dollar lower the past several weeks. the dollar closed monday at its lowest levels since the first week in january against major currencies
the bearish factors include ``disenchantment with anything being really done about the budget, the fear of renewed inflation, and the fear of another stock market collapse,'' arbesman said
those are all really still in the backs of people's minds, but they're taking a back seat,'' he said
the dollar showed little reaction to reports tuesday that the government's chief economic forecasting gauge rose 0.9 percent in february and sales of new homes shot up 20.3 percent, said david godwin, chief foreign exchange dealer for the union bank of switzerland in new york
the british pound was bolstered by rumors, later firmly denied, that british chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson had resigned and by a statement by prime minister margaret thatcher that keeping inflation down was the government's top priority
lawson, whose job is equivalent to the u.s. secretary of the treasury, reportedly has been arguing against allowing the pound to continue its recent rise against other currencies
in london, the pound rose to $1.8705 from $1.8590 monday. later, in new york, the pound fell to $1.8642 from $1.8705
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar fell 0.06 yen to a closing 124.37 yen. later, in london, it was quoted at 124.50 yen. at the end of the trading day in new york, the dollar jumped to 125.26 from 123.84 late monday
other dollar rates late tuesday in new york, compared with late monday, included: 1.6693 west german marks, up from 1.6562; 1.3768 swiss francs, up from 1.3652; 1.2360 canadian dollars, down from 1.2372; 5.6505 french francs, up from 5.6130; and 1,236 italian lire, up from 1,226
other dollar rates late tuesday in europe, compared with late monday, included: 1.6610 west german marks, up from 1.6605; 1.3735 swiss francs, up from 1.3705; 5.6280 french francs, up from 5.6275; 1.8690 dutch guilders, up from 1.8685; 1,232.50 italian lire, up from 1,231.00; and 1.2363 canadian dollars, down from 1.2377
on the commodity exchange in new york, gold bullion for current delivery was bid at $455.40 a troy ounce, down 40 cents from late monday
gold rose in london to a late bid price of $454.75 a troy ounce, compared with late monday's $454.00. in zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $455 compared with $453.50 late monday. earlier, in hong kong, gold rose $2.21 to close at a bid $456.88
silver bullion prices rose on the london market, where silver traded at a late bid price of $6.69 a troy ounce, compared with monday's $6.63. on new york's comex, silver bullion for current delivery was bid at $6.705 a troy ounce, up 4 cents from monday
platinum futures prices surged $7 a troy ounce tuesday on the new york mercantile exchange as the economic outlook continued to brighten and racial unrest in south africa prompted fears of supply disruptions, analysts said
on other exchanges, gold futures retreated while silver advanced; energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and stock-index futures advanced
platinum prices have been gradually re-establishing their traditional dominance over gold after falling to an even par with the yellow metal late last year, when recession fears were widespread
although it is considered a precious metal, platinum is also an industrial base metal and is more widely used by industry than gold
in a healthy economy, platinum is likely to do better than gold,'' said craig sloane, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co. ``the economic activity we've seen in the last couple of months is very positive for platinum.''
tuesday's government report showing a 0.9 percent increase in february in the index of leading economic indicators further dispelled fears that the october stock market collapse was a harbinger of recession, sloane said
most platinum comes from south africa, and a recent upswing in violence there sparked fears of supply problems that helped support platinum prices, said peter cardillo, commodity futures trading adviser for josephthal &amp; co. in new york
platinum settled $7 to $8.30 higher with the contract for delivery in april at $518.70 a troy ounce
tuesday's economic data had little impact on gold and silver futures prices, which registered only slight moves on new york's commodity exchange
gold settled 30 cents to 60 cents lower with april at $455.60 a troy ounce; silver was 3 cents to 4 cents higher with march at $6.705 a troy ounce
indications of continued overproduction by the organization of petroleum exporting countries sent crude oil futures prices sliding lower in light trading on the new york mercantile exchange, said michael rothman, senior energy strategist for merrill lynch capital markets
in addition, the market was skeptical that an opec meeting next month will produce support for a production cut, rothman said
heating oil futures prices also declined while unleaded gasoline gained a bit
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents lower across the board with may at at $16.98 a barrel; heating oil was .02 cent to .40 cent lower with april at 48.15 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .10 cent lower to .24 cent higher with april at 48.26 cents a gallon
soybean futures settled lower on the chicago board of trade but the grains finished nearly unchanged
the decline in soybean prices was mostly due to profit-taking after monday's sharp advances, said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc
contracts for may and july delivery of corn advanced slightly in reaction to news that the government had granted one-year extensions on certain corn loans taken out in 1984, 1985 and 1986
the extensions mean farmers can delay decisions about marketing hundreds of millions of bushels of corn that might otherwise have gone onto the market this year
wheat settled { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with may at $3.01 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with may at $2.11{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3 cents lower with may at $1.63} a bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents to 7{ cents lower with may at $6.50\ a bushel
livestock and meat futures finished mostly lower on the chicago mercantile exchange in position-evening ahead of thursday's quarterly usda hogs and pigs report and the three-day easter weekend
live cattle were unchanged to .40 cent lower with april at 75.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent to .55 cent lower with march at 82.82 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to .13 cent higher with april at 45.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .55 cent lower with may at 55.90 cents a pound
stock-index futures advanced slightly on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for june delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled .05 point higher at 259.95. the underlying spot index gained 2.01 points to close at 260.07. 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, weakness in ...</note>
the government's chief economic forecasting gauge shook off the october stock market slump to post a 0.9 percent increase in february in a performance which analysts said should lay to rest fears of a 1988 recession
in a second upbeat economic report tuesday, the government said that sales of new homes, which had fallen for three consecutive months, shot up 20.3 percent in february, the biggest monthly gain in almost two years
the positive economic news helped pull the stock market out of its slump in a broad-based rally. the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 18.57 points to 1,998.34, following steep declines last thursday and friday and a fractional gain in monday's session
share prices also were bolstered by a more stable dollar and lower interest rates. the u.s. currency surged upward from its lowest point since early january, responding favorably to reports of modest efforts by central banks to support it. the dollar jumped to 125.26 japanese yen in late new york trading from 123.84 yen late monday
interest rates declined, meanwhile, as bond prices rose. the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond jumped about ~ point, or $8.75 for every $1,000 in face value. its yield, which moves inversely to its price, tumbled to 8.75 percent from 8.83 percent late monday
weakness in home sales and in the index of leading economic indicators in the months following the oct. 19 stock market crash had raised fears that the five-year-old economic recovery was in imminent danger of collapsing
housing is often the first sector to weaken in a new downturn and the index of leading indicators is designed to forecast turning points in the economy. for that reason, the february rebounds in both were greeted as good news by economists
i think we can pretty well bury the recession fears,'' said robert dederick, executive vice president of northern trust co. of chicago. ``we have dodged the bullet from the stock market decline. the economy seems to be getting its second wind.''
similarly, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the index ``shows that the economy is very promising. the size and broad-based nature of last month's index of leading indicators are encouraging.''
the 0.9 percent rise in the leading index was the biggest advance since a 1 percent rise last june. the index had fallen in three of the past four months, including declines of 0.1 percent in october, 1.2 percent in november and 1.1 percent in january
only a 0.4 percent increase in december kept the index from posting a string of three or more consecutive declines, which is often viewed as a harbinger of a recession
analysts said the declines were correctly signalling slower growth this year than in 1987. but they said the economy should strengthen as it moves into the spring
the first quarter economic slowdown will be brief and mild and the fundamental strengths of the economy will emerge as the months go on,'' said lyle gramley, chief economist for the mortgage bankers association
gramley predicted that the economy, as measured by the gross national product, would rise 2.7 percent this year, an even more optimistic outlook than the administration's prediction of 2.4 percent growth
more than half of the strength in the leading index in february came from a big jump in building permit applications
analysts said the increase in building permits, after three months of declines, reflected optimism on the part of builders that home sales would strengthen because of declining mortgage rates
in the report on home sales, the commerce department said new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 628,000 units last month, the first advance since october and the biggest gain since march 1986
the housing rebound suggests that the october crash worries have been shaken off,'' said allen sinai, chief economist of the boston co. ``we have good fundamentals on consumer spending and consumer confidence because of strong employment growth and strong growth in disposable incomes.''
in all, five of the available nine indicators were positive forces on the leading index in february. after building permits, the sources of strength came from a drop in unemployment claims, a rise in stock prices, faster growth of the money supply and a rise in consumer goods orders
four indicators held the index back. the biggest negative factor was a decline in the length of the manufacturing workweek, followed by a decline in orders for plant and equipment, a change in raw materials prices and a speed-up in business delivery times, considered a negative because it is often a sign of dropping demand
the various changes left the index at 190.6 percent of its 1967 base of 100
right now the economy is looking a lot better than we thought it was going to look three months ago,'' said david wyss, an economist with data resources inc., of lexington, mass
at the end of last year, some analysts had feared the economy could suffer a decline in the gnp in the first three months of this year, something that has not occurred since the end of the 1981-82 recession. they feared that a big run-up in unsold goods would cause production cutbacks and rising unemployment at manufacturing plants
while there have been some production declines, notably in the auto industry, employment has risen sharply in the first two months of the year, pushing the jobless rate down to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent in february
former federal reserve board chairman paul volcker and david elliott, president of mbia corp., were elected directors of mbia inc., the company said tuesday
volcker will also serve as a consultant to the company, it was announced by william o. bailey, chairman and chief executive officer of mbia
mbia inc. is the holding company of muncipal bonds investors assurance corp., a leading insurer of municipal bonds
volcker is chairman of james wolfensohn inc., a new york investment banking firm, and was chairman of the federal reserve board from 1979 to august 1987
elliott has been the president and chief operating officer of mbia corp. since its formation in late 1986
mbia corp. insures municipal bonds, including new issues and bonds traded in the secondary market. said. updating with most passengers flown out of palma, other arrangements and detail. picks up 11th graf pvs, on tuesday ...</note>
a charter airline shut down operations unexpectedly for lack of funds, stranding about 7,000 angry easter vacationers in airports around europe on tuesday, an official of the carrier said
the spanish-based airline spantax, which is about $88 million in debt, closed operations after it ran out of money and couldn't find new investors, said pedro caro, the carrier's director of sales
about 100 employees protested the shutdown by blocking entry roads as 1,000 passengers waited anxiously for flights at son sant joan airport in palma, the capital of this mediterranean island where the company is based
caro said there was ``absolute chaos'' at the airport
late tuesday, airport official fernando echegarray said most of the passengers stranded on this island were able to leave on substitute flights
about 6,000 passengers were expected to be stranded at other airports in spain, finland, denmark and italy, caro had said earlier
there aren't enough airplanes in all of europe to resolve this,'' caro said
he said the situation was expected to get worse this weekend at the height of the easter vacation boom
by sunday i'll be hiding under the bed,'' he said
echegarray said tour operators made arrangements for palma passengers originally scheduled to fly on seven incoming and seven outgoing spantax flights, all canceled tuesday. spantax had 30 routes
he said charter airlines air europa, canafrica and tae arranged to carry spantax passengers. some passengers booked on a flight from palma to barcelona on the spanish mainland were to travel by boat, echegarray said
he said passengers reserved on a 6 a.m. plane tuesday to helsinki were expected to reach the finnish capital early wednesday
in madrid, a spokesman for a tour operator said 350 people scheduled to fly spantax to new york tuesday were to leave wednesday morning on another airline
earlier, antenna 3 radio reported in madrid that the passengers there staged a protest after being told their flight was canceled
on tuesday, spantax chairman wolfgang krauss told the company's 800 employees they would not be paid at the end of the month
there's no money to keep operating and no investors,'' the spanish national news agency efe quoted krauss as saying. the employees rejected krauss' appeal that they work unpaid for a 48-hour period
according to caro, the company's revenues totaled $150 million in 1987
in 1982, 51 people died and 121 were injured when a spantax dc-10 crashed while taking off from the mediterranean coastal city of malaga
first city bancorporation of texas inc. debt holders balked for a third time at tendering securities for a loss tuesday and officials responded by granting another extension and cutting its compliance goal for a federally assisted bailout
chicago investor a. robert abboud, who would become chairman under the bailout plan, and the federal deposit insurance corp. decided to modifiy the tender offer to 70 percent for the outstanding unsecured publicly held securities of first city
under the modification, the 90 percent minimum tender requirement has been eliminated,'' said first city spokesman jim day. ``but we still hope to get 90 percent. actually we'd like to get 100 percent
what we're saying is that we can get to 70 percent and still close and the projections of the company will be the same.''
another condition under the modification is that the new first city entity at the time of closing not differ materially from what was originally planned because of the lower participation level, day said
in addition, the terms of the offer have been amended to include payment of accrued interest on tendered debt securities through the date of acceptance and payment by first city acquisition of such tendered securities
houston-based first city also extended the deadline for the tender offer until april 12. the deadline now has been extended four times
as of tuesday, first city's third deadline, 62 percent, or $140 million, of bank's $225.8 million in bonds had been tendered. only 51 percent, or $115 million, were tendered by an earlier march 15 deadline
the deadline for debt holders was extended to march 15 when only 41.4 percent _ or $93.6 million _ was redeemed for cash by the first deadline of march 8
under the arrangement, first city senior debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the dollar for their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been offered 35 cents
since the current reorganization is the only open-bank proposal being considered by the fdic, it is unlikely under any alternative that holders of first city subordinated debt would receive anything for their interests: holders of first city senior public debt would in all likelihood receive, at best, only a fraction of the amounts represented by their securities,'' abboud said tuesday
wall street sources have said that almost $55 million of the outstanding bonds can be traced to arbitragers holding out for a sweetened offer
first city, with 59 banks in texas and one in south dakota, grew quickly during the texas oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. for 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss
the bailout plan for texas' fourth-largest bank holding company calls for $970 million in assistance from the fdic, $500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group headed by abboud and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets
on march 4, more than 71 percent of the houston-based company's 37 million shareholders approved the controversial bailout
other options available to the fdic, analysts say, include canceling the abboud deal and reopening bidding for the bank, or having the fdic itself take over first city
